<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Queen Meets With Politicians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- A day after the Dutch government  
collapsed over a constitutional dispute, Queen Beatrix met with 
political leaders at her palace Thursday to survey the wreckage of 
the former ruling coalition and decide the country's future. 
</P>
<P>
	The queen appointed a special adviser to look into the  
possibility of rebuilding the three-party coalition led by Prime 
Minister Wim Kok that resigned after splitting over whether to give 
citizens the right to vote in referendums. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers had rejected a push by the junior coalition partner,  
the centrist Democrats 66, to let citizens vote. Because its bill 
was not passed by Parliament, the party decided to step out of the 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	After hours of closed-door meetings, the two larger coalition  
partners -- the right-leaning Liberal Party and Kok's left-of-center 
Labor Party -- decided that resigning and beginning anew was the 
only solution. 
</P>
<P>
	The collapse of the Cabinet leaves the country with a weakened  
leadership thrust into a caretaker role. It comes at an awkward 
time, with Dutch troops participating in NATO's air campaign 
against Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	But acting Foreign Affairs Minister Jozias van Aartsen said the  
crisis won't influence the Dutch position or contribution to NATO 
actions. ``It has absolutely no impact on our Kosovo policy,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the current Cabinet will stay on temporarily, the  
acting government does not have the power to pass new legislation, 
only to settle pending issues and deal with matters of national 
security. 
</P>
<P>
	If the coalition cannot be rebuilt, the queen's other options  
are to let Labor and the Liberals form a two-party government or to 
call parliamentary elections, which are usually held every four 
years and were held just a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Elections appeared to be the most probable scenario because the  
Liberal Party and the Labor Party have indicated they prefer not to 
govern together without the Democrats 66 on hand to smooth out 
their differences. 
</P>
<P>
	The leading opposition party, the Christian Democratic Alliance,  
also has been named as a potential member of a new coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	The government collapse was prompted by a lone Liberal Party  
lawmaker in Parliament's upper chamber who voted against the 
referendum bill. It fell one vote short of gaining the two-thirds 
majority needed for passage. 
</P>
<P>
	Referendum voting rights, a longtime goal of the Democrats 66,  
would have permitted the public to vote on social and economic 
decisions already approved by Parliament, with the exception of 
issues involving taxation or the military. Opponents said they 
feared it would give citizens too much power over government 
policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
