<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Around lunchtime every Friday, Mohammad Abdallah  
left his sales job in suburban Lincolnshire for the 20-minute drive 
to his mosque. There, he removed his shoes, faced east toward Mecca 
and followed his spiritual leader, his imam, in prayer. 
</P>
<P>
	``For Muslims, Friday is the holy day,'' the 30-year-old  
Abdallah explains. 
</P>
<P>
	The service took him away from work for about an hour and 15  
minutes, including the 30 minutes he counted as lunch. ``I would 
make up the time I missed by coming in early or working late,'' he 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	The weekly observance, however, eventually cost the  
Jordanian-American his job. He took his case to the U.S. Equal 
Employment Opportunity Commission and won a $49,000 settlement in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	A growing number of worshippers are pursuing workplace  
complaints: among them, Muslim women who refuse to remove 
head-scarves at work; evangelical Christians who bring religious 
objects to the office; and Jews who oppose working on the Sabbath. 
</P>
<P>
	Jean Kamp, an attorney in the EEOC's Chicago office, says it's  
unclear to what extent an employer has to accommodate an employee's 
religious beliefs, and so the agency is giving priority to such 
cases in hopes the courts will provide answers. 
</P>
<P>
	In fiscal 1998, the EEOC considered 1,786 allegations of  
religious discrimination, compared with 1,584 two years earlier. In 
1998, 325 had outcomes favorable to the complainants, compared with 
165 in fiscal 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The numbers are much smaller for some other types of cases  
before the EEOC. In fiscal 1998, for example, there were 24,454 
complaints of sex discrimination, and $58.7 million in payments to 
complainants. That compares with $2.6 million for religious 
discrimination cases. 
</P>
<P>
	What does the law provide where workplace needs and religious  
practices collide? 
</P>
<P>
	Abba Cohen, Washington counsel for Agudath Israel of America, a  
national Orthodox Jewish organization, says employers are legally 
required to accommodate a religiously observant person unless doing 
so would cause what the law calls an ``undue hardship.'' And the 
courts have found it has to be only ``a little bit more than a 
minimal amount of hardship,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago attorney Michael Karpeles, who has represented  
businesses in religion discrimination cases, said employers must 
try to balance workers' religious interests with their companies' 
needs. 
</P>
<P>
	``If all the employer has to do is to make modest or minimal  
adjustments, they probably are wise to make those adjustments and 
work things out with the employee,'' Karpeles said. ``If they get 
to the point they are having so many requests and it's hard to 
accommodate all of them, they can feel comfortable drawing the line 
and saying, 'We've done all we can reasonably do.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Cases involving religious beliefs, however, aren't always  
clear-cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Abdallah's former employer, W.W. Grainger Inc., said it allowed  
his midday absences during his 15 months there until a co-worker 
died, leaving the staff stretched. 
</P>
<P>
	Grainger labor counsel Hank Galatz said Abdallah refused to  
temporarily suspend the absences. Abdallah, however, says 
short-staffing wasn't the real issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Had it been temporary, I would have been more than happy to  
accommodate them,'' Abdallah said. 
</P>
<P>
	In another case, seven Muslim women who said they were fired for  
refusing to remove their head-scarves while working security jobs 
at Dulles International Airport near Washington learned last month 
that they could return to work. The agreement was part of a 
settlement reached with Atlanta-based Argenbright Security Inc. to 
avoid an EEOC complaint. The company contended the women were never 
fired. 
</P>
<P>
	Muslims who strictly interpret their religion consider it  
obligatory for women to cover their heads. 
</P>
<P>
	In September, the EEOC accused the University of Chicago  
Hospitals of discriminating against an evangelical Christian 
employee. Victoria Levya, who recruited entry-level employees such 
as janitors, contends her supervisor told her not to hire people 
from her church and prohibited her from keeping religious objects, 
such as a church clock and inspirational calendar, on her desk. Her 
case is still pending. 
</P>
<P>
	Hospital spokesman John Easton denies Levya's claim of religious  
discrimination and said she was told not to recruit only people of 
a particular religion. ``There was concern that the prominent 
display of religious items in the employment office could be 
perceived as discrimination against candidates with other 
religions,'' Easton added. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyer Karpeles believes it's better for employees and employers  
``to try to work these issues out'' rather than resort to lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	Theologian Martin Marty, whose studies include religion in  
public life, agrees. 
</P>
<P>
	``My hunch is that many of these things used to get settled in  
the backyard,'' he says, ``or a walk down to the coffee shop ... 
and now immediately end up in court. If both sides would lower 
their voices ... we'd be better off.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
