<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Exchange Will Delist Alphatec </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Troubled Thai computer chip maker  
Alphatec Electronics will be delisted from the Stock Exchange of 
Thailand, a statement from exchange officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bankrupt firm will be delisted on Friday. Under its  
rehabilitation plan, the company must write off almost all its 
existing capital, which would bar its stock from being traded by 
the rules of the exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Alphatec was once considered the cornerstone company in  
Thailand's nascent attempts to forge a high-technology 
manufacturing sector. But a scandal erupted in 1997 when its 
chairman was accused of embezzlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite reporting stellar earnings, Alphatec was, in fact, in  
deep financial trouble. It became a symbol of the shady accounting 
practices and poor transparency that can make companies in emerging 
markets such as Thailand risky investments. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the rehabilitation plan approved by Alphatec's creditors  
in February, U.S. insurance giant American International Group and 
Sweden's Investor AB are to invest $40 million to take 80 percent 
of a new company, Alphatec Holding. Creditors of the old company 
are to hold the remaining 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Alphatec Holding owns 100 percent of Alphatec Semiconductor  
Packaging Co., a newly incorporated company that took over the 
computer-chip assembler's assets, personnel and operations in 
Thailand on April 22. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
