<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charity Rescued by Gates Donation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Silicon Valley's main United Way  
chapter, nearly destitute for lack of donations, suddenly has all 
the money it needs, thanks to the very deep pockets of Bill Gates 
and other high-tech leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've made it,'' United Way of Santa Clara's chairman, Michael  
Fox, said after the charity's coffers swelled by $7 million 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Microsoft tycoon and his wife, Melinda, donated $5 million,  
and the David and Lucile Packard Foundation contributed $2 million. 
Other high-tech leaders and foundations earlier gave $7.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes my heart sing that the `haves' are stepping up to the  
plate,'' said Mary Ellen Chell, executive director of Cupertino 
Community Services, which provides clothing, food and shelter to 
the homeless. 
</P>
<P>
	United Way had told its 104 member agencies last fall not to  
expect about $11 million in funding starting July 1. Mismanagement, 
and a lack of donations from technology workers with soaring stock 
portfolios, were blamed. 

</P>
</TEXT>
