<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	People Shot at Ga. High School  
</P>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- Several people were shot today at a high  
school as students were gathering for the day, but none of the 
injuries is believed to be life-threatening, said a spokeswoman for 
Rockdale County schools. The shootings happened about 8 a.m. at 
Heritage High School, near Conyers, a town east of Atlanta. 
``Somebody arrived with a gun and some people have been hit, maybe 
four or five,'' spokeswoman Bonnie Knight said. She did not know if 
the injured were students or teachers. The person who fired the 
shots was taken into custody almost immediately. The shooting comes 
exactly a month after the April 20 slaughter at Columbine High 
School in Littleton, Colo. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Visiting Columbine Families  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's trip today to Littleton,  
Colo., on the one-month anniversary of the massacre at Columbine 
High School retraces sadly familiar terrain for the president, who 
traveled one year ago to Oregon and another high school ravaged by 
gunfire. In the Oregon incident, two students were killed and 22 
injured during a rampage by a 15-year-old suspect also accused of 
killing his parents the day before and leaving their home rigged 
with bombs. The president and his wife, Hillary, will meet with 
victims' relatives at Littleton's World Roman Catholic Church, 
where counselors worked with survivors after the shooting. 

</P>
<P>
	Annan Calls for U.N. Role in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	KUKES, Albania (AP) -- Refugees cheered U.N. chief Kofi Annan  
today as he strolled through the dusty tent cities of northern 
Albania, and he called for the United Nations to play a key role in 
resolving the Kosovo conflict. Annan walked around two camps in 
Kukes, a town that is the temporary home to about 100,000 of the 
800,000 ethnic Albanians who have fled Kosovo. In Yugoslavia, NATO 
jets pounded Belgrade and its suburbs early today, directly hitting 
a hospital and killing at least three people. NATO is seeking a 
total withdrawal of all of Yugoslavia's 40,000 forces in Kosovo, a 
return of the refugees, and a well-armed international force to 
police the peace accord. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak Sees Israel Pullout in 2000  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak said in  
interviews published today that he can get Israeli troops out of 
Lebanon ahead of the one-year target date he has set -- and he wants 
to form a broad-based coalition to lower Palestinian expectations 
in the peace process. Barak, a former armed forces chief of staff, 
also said that handing over parts of the West Bank will be 
extremely painful for him. The prime minister-elect said he will 
not conduct negotiations with Israel's neighbors until his 
government is established. 

</P>
<P>
	Top Government Aide Killed in Rome  
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Gunmen shot and killed a top government aide to  
Italy's labor secretary today as he left home for work and Interior 
Minister Rosa Russo Jervolino called it a ``cold and professional'' 
ambush. Authorities said terrorism was one of the possibilities 
being investigated in the killing of Massimo D'Antona. A call to 
Italy's ANSA news service claimed responsibility after the shooting 
in the name of the Falange Armata, a right-wing terrorist group. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Trade Deficit Hits Record High  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's trade deficit soared to a record  
high for the third straight month in March as the politically 
sensitive deficit with Japan shot up to the highest level in more 
than four years, the Commerce Department said today. The March 
deficit of $19.7 billion was 2.9 percent higher than the previous 
record of $19.1 billion in February. So far this year, the U.S. 
trade deficit is running at an annual rate of $222.6 billion, 
nearly one-third higher than the all-time high of $169.3 billion 
set last year. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 3 in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices have opened narrowly higher with  
the Dow Jones industrial average up three points in today's early 
going. Advancers on the New York Stock Exchange hold a 3-2 lead 
over decliners. The Nasdaq Composite Index is up eight points. 

</P>
<P>
	Dolan Brothers May Buy New York Jets  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Cablevision chairman Charles Dolan and his  
brother, Larry, were said to be leading contenders to buy the New 
York Jets, Newsday reported today. People familiar with the team's 
situation were cited today as sources for the report, which did not 
identify the individuals. The sources also confirmed earlier 
reports that the team's late owner, Leon Hess, stipulated in his 
will that the team be sold upon his death. Cablevision is a major 
player on the New York sports scene as majority owner of Madison 
Square Garden, the NBA's Knicks and the NHL's Rangers. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
