<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 06:07:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Barclays To Cut 6,000 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Barclays Bank PLC plans to slash 6,000 jobs,  
almost 10 percent of its work force, in a cost-cutting move aimed 
at countering sagging profits and widespread doubts about the 
future of Britain's third-largest bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Barclays said Thursday it hopes the job cuts will help it save  
more than $320 million a year. The cuts will come mostly in the 
form of voluntary resignations and retirements by workers in its 
retail branches and corporate lending areas, the bank said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors bid the bank's share price up 3.9 percent in midday  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Barclays plans to computerize and centralize  
more of its operations in a restructuring program set to cost 
almost $650 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``The object of this is to produce a simpler, less complex  
structure that makes it easier to bank with us and to reduce our 
costs at the same time,'' chairmen Sir Peter Middleton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barclays has been struggling to shore up profits after its 1998  
earnings dropped 20 percent due to losses in developing countries 
by its investment banking unit, Barclays Capital. It also has been 
without a chief executive since last November. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank's problems have raised concerns among analysts that it  
lacks firm direction and have fed speculation that Barclays is ripe 
for a merger or takeover. Among those rumored to be interested in 
such a union are The Royal Bank of Scotland and the Abbey National 
and Halifax building societies. 
</P>
<P>
	Barclays currently employs more than 60,000 people. The job cuts  
come as the bank is seeking to offer customers more options for 
handling their finances, such as cash machines and banking by 
telephone or the Internet, Middleton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conservative Party's shadow trade secretary lamented the  
move as ``another body blow'' for British business. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Government is over-taxing and over-regulating,'' John  
Redwood said. ``Today, Barclays' staff are paying the price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barclays Chief Executive Martin Taylor resigned last November in  
what was widely believed to have been a dispute over the future of 
Barclays Capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
