<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 17:21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Face Tough Task Against Spurs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- After letting an opportunity at the  
Alamodome slip away, the Los Angeles Lakers were back home Thursday 
facing a harsh reality. 
</P>
<P>
	Trailing 2-0 to the San Antonio Spurs, they now must win four of  
five games from a team that has gone 35-6 since the beginning of 
March. 
</P>
<P>
	And that's just the beginning.  
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs are 4-1 in the playoffs after winning 12 of their  
final 13 regular-season games; they've won their last five road 
games and seven of their last eight, and they haven't lost two in a 
row since setbacks to Seattle and Utah at the end of February left 
them 6-8. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've proven themselves time and again this season,''  
Lakers' forward Rick Fox acknowledged. ``To say we share the same 
urgency would be reaching a little bit. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've made a commitment, you can sense a commitment from  
this side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Games 3 and 4 in the best-of-7 series are Saturday and Sunday at  
the Forum. 
</P>
<P>
	``As in tennis, they held serve,'' Fox said. ``We come home now  
to our home fans, home cooking. We can do what we do best, play 
Laker basketball, go back to San Antonio tied 2-2.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It appeared in the final minute of Game 2 on Wednesday night  
that the Lakers might come home tied 1-1, but it wasn't to be. 
</P>
<P>
	First, with the Lakers leading 76-75 thanks to a 3-point shot by  
Kobe Bryant with 36.9 seconds remaining, Bryant missed two free 
throws with 18.9 seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
	When Bryant stepped to the line, he had scored 28 points in Game  
2 and made 23 of his 25 foul shots (92 percent) in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, San Antonio's Tim Duncan, being guarded by J.R. Reid, made  
a short jump-hook from the right baseline with 8.4 seconds left to 
put the Spurs ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were supposed to come down and double-team him right  
away,'' Lakers coach Kurt Rambis said of Duncan. ``That was one 
thing we didn't do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They also should have fouled Duncan, since the Lakers had one to  
give. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess I didn't do a real good job in telling them,'' Rambis  
said. ``I did say we have a foul to give.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rambis said he assumed his players would use that foul before  
Duncan could shoot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was obviously incorrect in my assumption,'' he said. ``Once  
(Duncan) started getting in that low deep position, that was the 
time to foul him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers called their final timeout, after which Derek Fisher  
was unable to handle Bryant's inbounds pass. It ricocheted off 
Fisher's head, and San Antonio's Mario Elie came up with it. 
</P>
<P>
	Elie was immediately fouled -- the foul the Lakers had to give --  
and the Lakers then fouled Sean Elliott, who made two free throws 
with 5.3 seconds left to complete the scoring. 
</P>
<P>
	Without a timeout, Bryant took the inbounds pass downcourt and  
missed a desperation 3-pointer that could have tied the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kobe hit a big shot, but we executed in the end and that's  
what veteran teams do down the stretch, they make plays,'' Elie 
said. ``Going to Utah and Portland and winning close games earlier 
in the year gave us confidence. We've learned to keep our cool in 
close games down the stretch. We didn't do that early in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a tough game. This is a tough series.''  
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, it is -- for both teams.  
</P>
<P>
	``You're looking at almost like a textbook scenario of how to  
play defense,'' Rambis admitted of what the Spurs have done so far. 
``That to me is the key to their success, it's not what they've 
done offensively.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs have done an especially effective job of bottling up  
Shaquille O'Neal, holding him to 21 points in an 87-81 victory in 
Game 1 and 16 points in Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Neal averaged 26.3 points during the regular season and 29.5  
points in a first-round playoff series against Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	``Teams that win the way the Spurs have won all year, it's not a  
fluke,'' Fox said. ``We didn't give them two games, they took two 
games. You've got to give them credit.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
