<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 15:31:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elderly Man Gets Beating Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) -- A 72-year-old man allegedly beaten by  
supermarket security guards who mistakenly thought he had 
shoplifted two packs of cigarettes will get $290,000 in a 
settlement with Safeway Stores and the security company. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement between Richard Joy Clay, Safeway and Monument  
Security was reached shortly before Clay's case was to go to trial 
Wednesday. Neither company admitted any wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Clay was confronted last fall by two Monument security guards as  
he walked outside the supermarket after buying the cigarettes. The 
retired carpenter had put the receipt in his wallet. 
</P>
<P>
	He claimed the guards called him a thief, threw him to the  
ground and jumped on him with their knees, breaking five of his 
ribs. He said he was handcuffed and dragged back into the store, 
where a cashier told the guards they had made a mistake. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it was all said and done, a poor old man got the heck  
beaten out of him,'' said Doug Bosco, Clay's lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the guards was fired and is awaiting trial on assault and  
elderly abuse charges. Charges against the second guard were 
dismissed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 18:17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Guatemala Military Logbook Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House urged Guatemalan authorities  
today to protect anyone associated with release of a military 
logbook that dramatically documents nearly 100 killings by 
Guatemalan agents in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Mike Hammer said there is no reason to  
believe the book is not authentic. Human rights groups displayed 
the musty document for the first time at a Washington news 
conference on Thursday, saying it was smuggled out of the Central 
American country's military archives. 
</P>
<P>
	The groups declined to say exactly how they obtained the book  
but vouched for its authenticity and said it came into their 
possession after someone was paid an undisclosed sum for it. 
</P>
<P>
	The book lends further support to the conclusion of a Guatemalan  
truth commission in February that the military was responsible for 
extensive human rights abuses in the 1980s, Hammer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We call on the government of Guatemala to protect anyone  
associated with this document who may be put at risk because of its 
publication and we further believe the government of Guatemala 
should take this new evidence of wrongdoing seriously,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hammer also recommended action against those responsible for  
committing crimes during the period and protection of any other 
documents that may exist in the military archives. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Guatemalan President Alvaro Arzu, the country's chief  
human rights prosecutor, and the army asked that the logbook be 
returned. ``This document is valuable for five investigations I am 
carrying out. ... I am going to ask that it be entered in our case 
files,'' said human rights prosecutor Julio Arango Escobar. 
</P>
<P>
	The book includes photos and information about 183 people who  
were arrested, mostly in Guatemala City. Entries in the book 
indicate that about 100 of them were killed in captivity, the human 
rights groups said. 
</P>
<P>
	The book provides key evidence as well as first word of deaths  
for the families of some of the missing. 
</P>
<P>
	The Guatemalan truth commission, looking into the deaths or  
disappearances of more than 200,000 Guatemalans during the 
country's 36-year guerrilla war, concluded that more than 700 
massacres occurred, with most blamed on the army or armed civilian 
patrols formed by the government. 
</P>
<P>
	``This chilling document is the death squad equivalent of an  
annual productivity report, an account from inside the secret files 
of Guatemala's killing machine,'' said Kate Doyle, director of the 
National Security Archive's Guatemala Project. The organization is 
a private human rights research group. 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle spoke at a news conference at which the logbook was shown  
to reporters. The 53-page book is in a hardcover binder held 
together by three screws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 18:17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
