</P>
<P>
	The Guatemalan truth commission, looking into the deaths or  
disappearances of more than 200,000 Guatemalans during the 
country's 36-year guerrilla war, concluded that more than 700 
massacres occurred, with most blamed on the army or armed civilian 
patrols formed by the government. 
</P>
<P>
	``This chilling document is the death squad equivalent of an  
annual productivity report, an account from inside the secret files 
of Guatemala's killing machine,'' said Kate Doyle, director of the 
National Security Archive's Guatemala Project. The organization is 
a private human rights research group. 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle spoke at a news conference at which the logbook was shown  
to reporters. The 53-page book is in a hardcover binder held 
together by three screws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 17:11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Gen. Shelton Renamed to Top Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton nominated Army Gen. Henry H.  
Shelton to serve a second two-year term as chairman of the Joint 
Chiefs of Staff, the nation's top military position. 
</P>
<P>
	In a Rose Garden announcement Thursday with Shelton in uniform  
at his side, Clinton praised the four-star general as ``critical to 
our efforts in Kosovo and indeed to our entire national security 
program.'' As chairman of the Joint Chiefs, Shelton is the senior 
military adviser to the president and the secretary of defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our nation is fortunate that this critical post will continue  
to be filled by someone of his experience, ability and character,'' 
Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate must confirm Shelton for a second term, but there is  
no known opposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he and other members of his national security team,  
meeting in the Oval Office, had jokingly voted on whether Shelton 
should be kept in the job. All voted for it except ``he voted 
against it. But we overruled him and he's going to serve another 
term,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton, 57, became the 14th chairman of the Joint Chiefs of  
Staff on Oct. 1, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	A 6-foot-5-inch North Carolina native, Shelton is a decorated  
Vietnam combat veteran and former commander of the U.S. Special 
Operations Command, which oversees the Army's Green Berets, the 
Navy's Seals and other elite outfits. 
</P>
<P>
	As head of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Shelton has a leading  
voice in the U.S. role in NATO's air war against Yugoslavia, 
although he has no direct command of troops. He and the rest of the 
Joint Chiefs met in the Pentagon on Thursday with Gen. Wesley 
Clark, the top NATO commander and architect of the air campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton, in a statement issued at the Pentagon, said: ``It has  
been a particular privilege to represent our nation's soldiers, 
sailors, airmen and Marines during a period of great international 
uncertainty and an unprecedented pace of military operations.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
