<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Chip Maker To Give Bonuses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOUNTAIN VALLEY, Calif. (AP) -- Another successful year, another  
huge $20 million bonus to be shared by the 1,000 employees at 
computer memory-chip firm Kingston Technology Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Tenure and performance determine how much each employee gets out  
of the bonus. ``It's a huge range,'' company spokeswoman Heather 
Jardin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have always said they would do profit sharing. It goes  
along with Kingston's philosophy. It's a real family thing,'' Ms. 
Jardin said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kingston manufactures memory-chip modules for personal  
computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Company co-founders John Tu and David Sun told employees in  
memos that the big payoff will come in July. The company paid a $38 
million bonus to employees in 1997 and $20 million last year. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's bonus wasn't as large 1997's because prices have  
dropped for the chip modules, which plug into personal computers 
and store data. 
</P>
<P>
	``This place is an amazing place to work,'' said Ms. Jardin, who  
bought a house with her first bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	When the bonuses are handed out, a tent is erected at the Orange  
County firm and Sun encourages employees to spend wisely. 
</P>
<P>
	``He says pay off your mortgages, put it in the bank, pay off  
your debts or put a good down (payment) on something,'' Ms. Jardin 
said. ``This is a big chunk of money for people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One year, employees were besieged by Mercedes-Benz and BMW  
salesmen. As a joke, one worker drove to work in a Porsche he 
borrowed from a neighbor. 
</P>
<P>
	Employee Tim Westland was constantly approached by strangers  
looking for work when he wore his Kingston T-shirt around town. 
There were so many job applicants the company posted ``Not Hiring'' 
signs on its doors. 
</P>
<P>
	Tu and Sun each received about $750 million when Softbank Corp.  
bought the company in 1996 for $1.5 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
