<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rawlings Recalls Softball Bats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Rawlings Sporting Goods Inc. is recalling about  
45,000 aluminum softball bats because of safety concerns, company 
officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission and Rawlings have  
received 16 reports of the top of the bats shearing off. No 
injuries have been reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The recall is limited to aluminum slow-pitch softball bats. The  
bats include an end weight that is screwed in, which officials 
believe is creating the stress that causes the bat to break. 
</P>
<P>
	The recalled bats are model numbers SBZ2, SBZ3, SBZ4, SBB3,  
SBB4, SBB5, SBB6, SBB7, SPT-PK2, and DUAL-E. ``Rawlings'' and the 
model numbers can be found on the barrel of each bat. The bats are 
adult-sized, and come in various colors. 
</P>
<P>
	Major retailers, including Wal-Mart, Target and Kmart, and  
sporting goods stores nationwide sold the bats from September 1997 
through May 1999 for between $40 and $200. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers may call Rawlings at 800-367-3455, or write the  
company at P.O. Box 22000, St. Louis, Mo., 63126. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 16:12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> H.S. Gunman Described As Quiet Teen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- The boy who shot six students in his high  
school Thursday is a quiet, middle-class 15-year-old sophomore 
whose grades had slipped recently and whose heart was broken when 
his girlfriend dumped him, friends and neighbors said. 
</P>
<P>
	One other thing stood out to those who know the teen-ager: there  
were a lot of guns in the basement of his home. 
</P>
<P>
	``He showed them to me and my brother one time. I don't know  
much about guns, but I think they were like, hunting guns,'' said 
15-year-old Brad Morgan, who lives two houses away from the suspect 
and rode the bus with him to Heritage High School in suburban 
Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Said sophomore Chris Dunn, a friend of the suspect: ``He had  
lots of guns. They were his parents'.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some classmates said the teen-ager had boasted in recent weeks  
of shooting people at school. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have been saying he's been wanting to do this all year  
long,'' said 15-year-old Katie Bir. 
</P>
<P>
	Others, like Katrima Barton, said they didn't take it seriously.  
</P>
<P>
	The teen-ager, whose name was not released by authorities, lived  
with his mother, stepfather and 13-year-old sister at the end of a 
cul-de-sac of $275,000-plus homes with manicured lawns. His home is 
nestled on a large, wooded lot with a basketball hoop at the end of 
a winding driveway. 
</P>
<P>
	The family moved to Conyers two years ago from South Carolina.  
The boy's mother works as a secretary for a veterinarian. The 
neighbors were unsure where the stepfather worked. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were people that really kept to themselves,'' said  
Morgan's father, Allan, who sometimes drove the suspect to summer 
school last year in the neighborhood carpool. ``He was a quiet kid, 
but I just chalked it up to him being shy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, reporters swarmed the neighborhood and detectives  
searched the boy's home, carrying boxes in and out. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors described the teen-ager as someone who was quiet but  
had a few close friends. His family went to the local Catholic 
church, and the teen-ager had attended the church youth service as 
usual Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was pretty quiet, but around me and other people he would  
laugh and joke around,'' Dunn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Friends said the teen-ager's grades had fallen recently, and  
they weren't sure why. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wasn't even trying anymore, which I was kind of concerned  
about,'' Dunn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Friend and classmate Nathaniel Deeter, 15, said the suspect was  
``really upset'' about the breakup with a girl he had dated for 
about a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said, `I have no reason to live anymore.' And I told him he  
was crazy. I thought he was just feeling sorry for himself because 
a lot of kids feel like that,'' Deeter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Deeter said the suspect gave no clue about his shooting plans  
when Deeter spoke to him 10 minutes before the spree began. 
</P>
<P>
	Brad Morgan said the suspect didn't say or do anything unusual  
at the bus stop Thursday morning. ``He was acting just like any 
other day,'' Morgan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 13:33:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greenberg Named McDonald's Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- McDonald's Corp. on Thursday named Jack  
Greenberg, who has been credited with helping the fast-food chain 
make a sharp turnaround in recent months, its chairman and chief 
executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenberg, who had been the company's president and chief  
executive officer, becomes only the fourth chairman since 
McDonald's was founded in 1955. His promotion was announced at 
McDonald's annual shareholders meeting and is effective 
immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts have praised Greenberg for steering the chain in the  
right direction over the past year. 
</P>
<P>
	After months of struggling sales and declining market share, the  
chain last year gained market share and boosted sales at stores 
open at least a year, in part because of such successful promotions 
as Beanie Babies and Monopoly. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say McDonald's has experienced a remarkable turnaround  
as it decentralized its domestic operations to give grumbling 
franchisees more say in developing their menus and planning 
promotions. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also has benefited from increased expansion  
overseas, particularly in Europe, where revenues soon will exceed 
domestic sales despite having far fewer restaurants per capita. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenberg replaces Michael R. Quinlan, who will remain a member  
of McDonald's board and chairman of its executive committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenberg has served as McDonald's president and chief executive  
officer since April 1998. He joined the company in 1982 as 
executive vice president and chief financial officer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 09:12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dolan Brothers May Buy New York Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Cablevision chairman Charles Dolan and his  
brother, Larry, were said to be leading contenders to buy the New 
York Jets, according to Newsday. 
</P>
<P>
	People familiar with the team's situation were cited today as  
sources for the report in the newspaper, which did not identify the 
individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	The sources also confirmed earlier reports that the NFL club's  
late owner, Leon Hess, had stipulated in his will that the team be 
sold upon his death. Hess died May 7 at 85. 
</P>
<P>
	Jets spokesman Frank Ramos said today the team would not comment  
on whether it is entertaining offers. ``We're not making an 
announcement today'' regarding any potential sale, Ramos said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cablevision is a major player on the New York sports scene as  
majority owner of Madison Square Garden, the NBA's Knicks and the 
NHL's Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	The cable television company announced today it would become a  
partner with the New Jersey Devils in their plan to build a new 
arena in Hoboken, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Cablevision would bear half of the $206 million cost to  
construct the new venue above the Hoboken commuter rail station, 
Devils president John McMullen told The Star-Ledger in today's 
editions. He was not available today for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dolan brothers made an unsuccessful bid to buy the Cleveland  
Browns expansion franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Shula, retired coach of the Miami Dolphins, could be part of  
the Dolans' effort to acquire the Jets, according to Newsday. He 
was part of their bid for the Browns. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel free to comment on that,'' Shula said when asked  
about his possible involvement in the move to buy the Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he enjoyed his relationship with the Dolans when they  
tried to get the Browns' franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	It has been estimated that the Jets may sell for about $500  
million. The NFL finance committee voted this week to recommend 
that the Washington Redskins be sold to Daniel Snyder for $800 
million, but that deal would include the team's new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets play at Giants Stadium at the Meadowlands sports  
complex in East Rutherford, N.J. That complex also has the 
Continental Airlines Arena, home of the Devils and the NBA's Nets. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the other possible buyers for the Jets was New York Mets  
principal owner Nelson Doubleday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
