<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rescue on Mt. McKinley Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Three British climbers, one of them  
injured, were stuck high on Mount McKinley on Thursday in a 
wind-lashed spot with little food or other supplies, the National 
Park Service said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jane Tranel, a park service spokeswoman in Talkeetna, said the  
climbers were stranded at 19,000 feet on the West Rib route of 
North America's highest peak. They radioed a mayday at about 3 
a.m., she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Names of the three men were not released.  
</P>
<P>
	Rescuers have had limited radio contact with the climbers,  
either because of transmission problems or dying batteries. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the climbers was hurt too badly to descend on his own.  
</P>
<P>
	Tranel said they were traveling with little gear, apparently to  
make a quick trip to the 20,320-foot summit and back down to their 
camp at 15,700 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	The men were in an area without much protection from McKinley's  
notorious winds, which Tranel said were blowing up to 50 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Other climbers with a radio were moving up the mountain toward  
the stranded men. Poor visibility made rescue by helicopter 
untenable. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year two British military climbers were plucked from almost  
the same place after being stranded by fierce blizzards for more 
than three days without food or shelter. One suffered badly 
frostbitten feet, while the other had only minor injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Weather Service was forecasting partly cloudy  
conditions on Friday, Tranel said, so an aerial rescue attempt 
might be possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
