<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 04:41:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Driver Accused of Hitting Blacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) -- A white man accused of intentionally  
running down two black teen-agers on their bicycles had a note in 
his car that referred to inciting racial friction, police records 
show. 
</P>
<P>
	Relatives of the 14-year-old victims -- Dontrell Langston and  
Austin Hansen-Tyler -- want the driver, James G. Langenbach, to be 
charged with a hate crime for the incident Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	An officer who took Langenbach's car to a garage found  
handwritten papers with the phrase: ``I'm here to get this 
white/black race B.S. started and it looks like I did,'' according 
to search warrant records released Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Langenbach, 27, of Kenosha, who has been treated for psychiatric  
problems, failed to attend anger management sessions and did not 
get his high school equivalency test despite a court order, records 
show. 
</P>
<P>
	Langston was hospitalized in good condition Wednesday, while  
Hansen-Tyler was listed in serious condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Langenbach was charged Monday with causing great bodily harm to  
a child and leaving the scene of an injury accident, each as a 
repeat offender. The charges carry up to 66 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1991, he was sentenced to two years probation for endangering  
safety for ramming his car twice into a van holding five black 
passengers. He was ordered to undergo an alcohol assessment, anger 
management and other counseling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
