<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ray Turns Fastest Lap at Indy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Greg Ray turned the fastest lap of the week  
and Tony Stewart, expected to be his chief rival for the 
Indianapolis 500 pole, hit the wall Thursday in practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who left Team Menard at the end of last year and is now  
the hottest rookie in NASCAR's Winston Cup series, had supplanted 
Ray at the top of the speed charts on Wednesday with a lap of 
226.683 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	But Ray, Stewart's replacement on John Menard's team, took the  
challenge Thursday and upped the top speed to 227.192. 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels nice to be this consistently quick,'' Ray said. ``We  
regard our competition very highly. We're not taking anything for 
granted. From here, we want to try to go even faster but, above 
all, keep it off the wall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Stewart, wasn't able to keep his car off the wall.  
</P>
<P>
	Shaking down his primary car, he got too high in turn 3 on the  
2 1/2-mile Indianapolis Motor Speedway and bounced twice off the 
concrete wall before stopping on the main straightaway. 
</P>
<P>
	``I needed about 12 more inches of racetrack,'' Stewart said.  
``Unfortunately, I just ran out of racetrack and hit the wall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The car was not badly damaged, but Stewart was upset.  
</P>
<P>
	``I just made a stupid mistake,'' he said. ``I'm disgusted with  
myself. They pay me to drive a race car, and I take these things to 
heart. Thankfully, it wasn't too bad. 
</P>
<P>
	``Knock on wood, we haven't had an engine problem of any kind  
yet and I've had more fun so far this week, and the most relaxing 
week leading up to qualifying that I've ever had at Indy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robby Unser, last year's top Indy rookie, jumped to fourth  
overall at 225.079. 
</P>
<P>
	Other fast drivers on Thursday included two-time Indianapolis  
champion Arie Luyendyk, retiring following the May 30 race, at 
225.073; Stephan Gregoire at 224.792; 1996 Indy winner Buddy Lazier 
at 224.361, and defending champion Eddie Cheever Jr. at 224.193. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnny Unser, Robby's cousin, also crashed in practice Thursday,  
spinning in turn 3 and hitting the wall twice. He also escaped 
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Harrington, who also found the wall this week, had a much  
better day on Thursday, thanks to his persistence. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington, who drove in a CART race in 1989, finishing 16th at  
Elkhart Lake, Wis., in his debut, didn't make it back to the top 
level of the open-wheel sport until the 1996 Indianapolis 500, 
placing 15th in his first Indy Racing League start. 
</P>
<P>
	His racing has been sporadic enough so that Harrington is the  
leading IRL rookie of the year candidate after finishing 25th in 
the season-opener at Orlando, Fla., and a career-best fifth at 
Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the story of my career,'' Harrington said. ``Seven  
years between races.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even after finally making the show at Indy, the struggle  
continued for Harrington, whose underfinanced team -- currently 
co-owned by Harrington, his father, Gene, and longtime open-wheel 
crew chief and team manager Darrell Soppe -- couldn't find a sponsor 
willing to make a commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	But Harrington finally got that commitment Thursday, with  
CertainTeed Roofing Products Group stepping up as sponsor of the 
Harrington Motorsports Dallara-Infiniti for the Indy 500 and the 
rest of the IRL season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their involvement with our program is the answer to our  
prayers,'' said Harrington, who left the news conference, got into 
uniform and happily began running practice laps. 
</P>
<P>
	He ran 42 laps with a top speed of 216.320. That was just shy of  
his top lap of 218.330, run Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	But everything hasn't been wonderful for Harrington this week.  
He tore up one car Monday in a crash in turn 3, walking away with 
only a bruised left foot. 
</P>
<P>
	It was only the latest in a series of crashes at Indy.  
</P>
<P>
	He got through rookie orientation in 1989 without crashing, but  
didn't make the race. In 1996, Harrington passed his refresher test 
two days before final time trials and promptly hit the wall in 
practice, bruising his left foot and shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	He came back to make the field with 23 minutes left on the final  
day of qualifying, but crashed in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no money and no Indy effort in 1997, but he came back  
last year and nearly made the field in a last-ditch effort in one 
of A.J. Foyt's backup cars. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't going too fast and A.J. made a lot of changes to  
the car before we went out for that qualifying run,'' Harrington 
said. ``We needed a 210 to make it and, when I came by after the 
first lap, the pit board said 210. 
</P>
<P>
	``Actually, it was 214, but I didn't know that, so I stayed in  
the gas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As he drove that second of four qualifying laps, his engine blew  
and Harrington slid hard into the wall. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made it as far as turn 2 and woke up in Methodist  
Hospital,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Concussions and bruises don't stop race drivers, but Harrington  
has developed a healthy respect for Indy. 
</P>
<P>
	``This place is different than any other track,'' he said.  
``It's more mental than any other track we run on. The turns are so 
long and the straightaways so fast, you have a lot of time to 
think. 
</P>
<P>
	``But, if you get even 6 inches off here, that can be 6 feet off  
in a quarter-mile. It's very easy to get frustrated. You can't let 
that happen. You can't lose concentration for a moment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Qualifications to determine the 33-car lineup are set for  
Saturday and Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
