<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Law for Ships Entering U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Beginning July 1, all ships entering the  
United States will have to tell the government what they have done 
on the high seas to protect fragile American waterways from 
invading species. 
</P>
<P>
	The interim regulation, published today by the Coast Guard, puts  
into action a 1996 law extending to all ports measures so far in 
effect only on the Great Lakes. 
</P>
<P>
	The law asks big ocean vessels to empty their ballast tanks at  
sea and replace the local liquid with sea water, in theory washing 
out bacteria, plants and animals that otherwise would end up in the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign creatures such as the sea lamprey and zebra mussel had  
no natural enemies in the Great Lakes and became such a problem 
that a law was passed in 1990 to first ask, and later require, the 
ballast swaps. 
</P>
<P>
	The new regulation requires officers of ships that have been  
outside U.S. waters to fill out forms stating what they did with 
their ballast water. The Coast Guard will monitor those reports and 
determine whether the ballast moves were adequate. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the Coast Guard issued voluntary guidelines asking  
tankers, container ships and other vessels to make ballast-water 
swaps in mid-ocean, no matter where their ports of call. 
</P>
<P>
	Problems caused by non-native plants and animals have become  
increasingly visible around the country, with ballast-water dumps 
frequently identified as a prime culprit. 
</P>
<P>
	James Baker, administrator of the National Oceanic and  
Atmospheric Administration, estimated earlier this year that 40,000 
gallons of foreign ballast water is dumped into U.S. harbors every 
minute. 
</P>
<P>
	That's how the zebra mussel made it into the Great Lakes,  
hitchhiking in the ballast water of a ship that originated in 
either the Caspian Sea or Black Sea, the animal's natural habitat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
