<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Merrill Lynch Charged in Copper Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators charged Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.  
on Thursday with allegedly helping a commodities firm manipulate 
the world copper market. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Commodity Futures Trading Commission said that Merrill  
Lynch worked with New York-based Global Minerals and Metals Corp. 
and Japan's Sumitomo Corp. to artificially force prices higher in 
late 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Geoffrey Aronow, the enforcement director for the CFTC, said  
Thursday's action capped a three-year investigation of ``one of the 
most serious worldwide manipulations'' of a commodity in 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch denied the allegations and said it will defend  
itself. An attorney for Global Minerals also denied the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street firm said it fully cooperated with the CFTC's  
investigation and was ``extremely disappointed'' that the agency 
decided to proceed with charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The CFTC also announced charges against the commodities firm,  
Global Minerals and Metals Corp., its president and chief executive 
officer and its chief copper trader. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Haveles, an attorney for New York-based Global Minerals,  
and Global Minerals' president and CEO, R. David Campbell of New 
York City, said the CFTC's complaint was ``based on an 
Alice-in-Wonderland view of the facts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, Haveles said the company's trading activities  
occurred in a market with a big copper deficit due to a dramatic 
increase in demand in the mid-1990s, which would have pushed up the 
metal's price. He also said British commodities regulators were 
``fully informed'' about Global Minerals' activities at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is confident the complaint will be judged to be  
baseless, the attorney said. 
</P>
<P>
	The case stems from a scandal that rocked the world copper  
market in 1996, based on trades that occurred as much as 10 years 
beforehand. 
</P>
<P>
	Yasuo Hamanaka, a former Sumitomo star trader who has been  
convicted of fraud and forgery by a Japanese court, caused $2.6 
billion in losses in unauthorized copper trading over a decade 
after cornering as much as 5 percent of the market. When the losses 
were exposed in 1996, copper prices plunged. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders have said Hamanaka's activities kept the price of copper  
high on the New York and London futures markets in 1995 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related move a year ago, Sumitomo agreed to pay $150  
million to settle the CFTC's charges that it manipulated the world 
copper market. The big Japanese trading house, which also agreed to 
pay $8 million to British regulators, neither admitted to nor 
denied wrongdoing in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The CFTC alleged that Merrill ``knowingly and intentionally  
aided, abetted and assisted'' the manipulation scheme by providing 
substantial credit and financing that Global Minerals and Sumitomo 
used to corner warehouse stocks of copper. The regulators also 
accused Merrill of intentionally advising Global Minerals and 
Sumitomo on how they could best corner the market. They alleged 
that Merrill benefitted from the scheme in its own copper trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement Thursday, Merrill said it had no knowledge that  
Sumitomo's conduct was unlawful and had no intention of aiding any 
improper activities. 
</P>
<P>
	``The business transactions that occurred more than three years  
ago between Merrill Lynch and Sumitomo, including copper trading 
..., were conducted in a commercially reasonable fashion and were 
fully visible to the regulators at the time,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Merrill spokesman said the company similarly had no knowledge  
of unlawful conduct by Global Minerals and had made reasonable 
transactions with the commodities firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Also named in the CFTC complaint was Global Minerals' chief  
copper trader, Carl Alm, of Massapequa, N.Y. His attorney, David 
Frankel, didn't immediately return a telephone call seeking 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The CFTC filed a civil complaint against the companies and  
individuals, asking for a hearing before an administrative law 
judge at the agency to determine if the charges are true and what 
penalties may be appropriate. 
</P>
<P>
	Possible penalties include an order requiring the companies and  
individuals to refrain from future violations of federal 
commodities laws and civil fines and restitution of damages, the 
agency said. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
