<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> France Offers Four Films at Cannes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANNES, France (AP) -- Intellectuals may love them, but danger  
lurks at the box office for the long-winded abstractions being 
presented by French directors at Cannes. 
</P>
<P>
	The four films in competition pretty much sum up the state of  
cinema in France, where generous state subsidies encourage 
producers to worry less about attracting a large audience and 
guarantee near-complete freedom for directors. 
</P>
<P>
	``There may be a danger in our system because it allows  
directors to be indulgent,'' says Michel Ciment, editor of the 
French film monthly Positif. 
</P>
<P>
	Wildly different in tone and style, the French entries at Cannes  
share slender plots that fail to sustain running times of well over 
two hours. Many also have shocking sex scenes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pola X,'' a somber, unsettling tale of incest starring  
Catherine Deneuve and Guillaume Depardieu, son of the famous actor 
Gerard, was enfant terrible Leos Carax's first feature film since 
1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the strong visuals, this adaptation of Herman Melville's  
``Pierre, or the Ambiguities,'' racked up almost unanimously bad 
reviews. 
</P>
<P>
	Veteran Chilean director Raoul Ruiz, who adapted Marcel Proust's  
classic, ``Time Regained,'' fared a bit better. 
</P>
<P>
	The plodding costume drama with an all-star cast of Deneuve,  
Emmanuelle Beart, Chiara Mastroianni, Arielle Dombasle and John 
Malkovich managed to convey a hint of Proust's analytical lyricism. 
But it was long and boring. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruno Dumont's skillful but snail-paced ``Humanity,'' about a  
hapless small-town cop investigating a sordid murder, is an 
intellectually ambitious take on sexual obsession and guilt. 
</P>
<P>
	But the meticulous attention to detail -- including an  
excruciatingly long close-up of the genitalia of a murdered 
11-year-old girl -- left some viewers with a feeling of physical 
revulsion. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, the camera zooms in on Domino, a fleshy factory worker  
lying naked and spread-eagled. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the black-tie crowd bolted from the official screening,  
but French critics deemed ``Humanity'' prize-worthy and praised 
Dumont for defending the colors of French cinema. 
</P>
<P>
	``Humanity isn't a great film, but there's a great film if you  
lopped off 30 minutes,'' Ciment said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's no wonder French audiences have turned their backs on  
homegrown films in favor of big Hollywood productions. 
</P>
<P>
	According to National Cinema Center statistics released this  
week, French films in 1998 made up 27 percent of national 
box-office receipts -- the lowest ever. Hollywood's market share was 
a record 64 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm all for the intellectual films that please Cannes juries,  
but I think a film can be edifying and entertaining at the same 
time,'' said Jack Valenti, President of the Motion Picture 
Association of America. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacques Maillot's ``Our Happy Lives,'' the fourth French entry,  
isn't exactly entertaining, but this plunge into the troubled lives 
of six dysfunctional young adults has its fun moments. 
</P>
<P>
	The acting is superb, but some say it uses heavy-handed cliches  
that oversimplify the complexity of contemporary France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
