<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 06:09:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jimmy Buffet Sticks Up for Manatees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- He may be a parrothead, but Jimmy  
Buffett's got another creature on his mind. 
</P>
<P>
	The musician says humans are causing far too many manatee  
deaths, mostly by hitting the animals with boats. He met with Gov. 
Jeb Bush on Wednesday to urge him to do something to help the 
lumbering sea mammals. 
</P>
<P>
	``The manatee to me serves as a symbol of the quality of life  
and the future of Florida,'' Buffett said after the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	A coalition of environmental groups is threatening to sue  
federal and state agencies, saying not enough is being done under 
the federal Endangered Species Act to protect the giant animals 
that ply Florida's coastal regions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've basically felt that there's not a lot of enforcement of  
the laws designed to protect manatees and we'd like to see it 
done,'' Buffett said. ``One day we'll wake up and it will be too 
late.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buffett, whose fans are called ``parrotheads,'' lives in Palm  
Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Rose, director of government relations for Save the Manatee  
Club, said 28 manatees have been killed by boats this year and, of 
the 231 that died last year, 66 were killed by boats. The state 
says about 2,400 remain in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor wasn't available for comment after the meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 15:12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Healtheon Buys WebMD for $9.86B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors overwhelmingly supported Healtheon  
Corp.'s planned acquisition of Internet health care information 
company WebMD Inc., pushing shares of Healtheon up 25 percent 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	At its current value of $9.86 billion, the purchase ranks among  
the largest Internet industry deals in history, rivaling America 
Online Inc.'s $10.2 billion purchase of Netscape Communications 
Corp. earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The all-stock transaction will create a powerful Internet  
company offering health care services and information for 
consumers, doctors, insurers and drug makers. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal made huge sums for early investors and left bystanders  
scratching their heads. 
</P>
<P>
	Is the market overvaluing the acquisition?  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think anyone can answer that,'' said James Clark,  
co-founder of Healtheon, and one of the original founders of 
Netscape. ``Typically markets are very efficient.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than $1.2 trillion is spent every year on health care in  
the United States, and Clark estimates $250 billion is wasted in 
duplicative and paper-based processes. 
</P>
<P>
	Healtheon/WebMD, as the new firm will be called, aims to break  
into the industry by offering doctors the ability to order 
supplies, prescriptions, check lab results, verify insurance 
coverage. The company also will offer continuing education and 
certification services. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 200,000 consumers, on the other hand, currently log on  
to the WebMD site to access information on prevention and diseases, 
and get physician referrals. 
</P>
<P>
	``This merger is about leadership and this merger is about  
winning,'' said Jeff Arnold, the 29-year-old chief executive of 
WebMD, who will keep his title at the combined venture. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the promise of riches, both companies have yet to make a  
dime of profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Healtheon went public in February at $8 a share. Thursday, its  
shares closed up $20.37 1/2 at $100.62 1/2 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
All this for a company that was $54 million in the red last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, WebMD lost $7.8 million on sales of $75,000 for the  
first nine months of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Healtheon will issue 1.815 of its shares, worth $182.63  
Thursday, for each of the privately held WebMD's 54 million shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Healtheon's ``current valuation for the stock basically gives  
them a remarkable advantage, which is they have virtually free 
money to buy other businesses,'' said Linda R. Killian, a 
co-manager for the Renaissance Capital Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to its big stock price, Healtheon/WebMD also has  
big-name backers. 
</P>
<P>
	Signaling not only the importance of the deal, but also the  
potential profits seen in Web-based health care services, Microsoft 
Corp. will invest $250 million in the new venture. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, the world's largest software company, will pay $150  
million to help cover the $29.95 monthly fee for 11,000 physicians, 
allowing them to subscribe free to the service. Microsoft also will 
pay at least $100 million to help Healtheon/WebMD get advertising 
revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	Healtheon/WebMD, in exchange, will use Microsoft's technology  
extensively. 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont will spend $180 million to pay for physician fees and $40  
million to generate advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	Another group of technology leaders, including Intel Corp.,  
Excite Inc. and Softbank, also will invest a combined $110 million 
to forge strategic operating agreements with WebMD. 
</P>
<P>
	``The depth and breadth of our partnerships simply cannot be  
equaled by any of our competitors,'' Arnold said. ``With this 
merger we are the clear leader in Internet health care services.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Healtheon/WebMD will have about 1,300 employees, a headquarters  
in Atlanta and a technology headquarters in Santa Clara, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies will each control 50 percent of the new firm.  
Each company will have four representatives on the new board of 
directors and Microsoft will have one. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the third Internet health care deal this week.  
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, CVS Corp., the nation's second-largest pharmacy  
chain, said it would buy Soma.com, and online drug retailer, for 
$30 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday, Synetic Inc., a competitor to Healtheon, agreed to pay  
$1.3 billion in stock for Medical Manager Corp., the largest maker 
of software for physician practices. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
