<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Continue Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybeans futures prices continued  
their downward spiral Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade as favorable 
growing weather boosted prospects for bumper production. 
</P>
<P>
        Corn futures were pressured by favorable growing and planting  
conditions across the Midwest, while prices found some support from 
strong weekly export figures reported by the U.S. Agriculture Department. 
</P>
<P>
        The government reported sales of 742,900 metric tons, a figure  
below previous weeks' sales but still above expectations. Corn sales 
now are 30 percent higher than this time a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat futures fell amid mediocre export numbers and continued  
reports of above-average yields in winter wheat growing areas. 
</P>
<P>
        Soybeans were pressured by expectations farmers will complete  
plantings in the next week amid generally favorable weather conditions. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for July delivery fell 3 1/2 cents to $2.56 1/4 a bushel;  
July corn fell 1/2 cent to $2.19 a bushel; July oats fell 1/2 cent 
to $1.21 1/4 a bushel; July soybeans fell 3 1/2 cents to $4.68 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Beef futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while  
lean hogs were mixed and pork bellies retreated. 
</P>
<P>
        June live cattle rose .20 cent to 62.87 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .70 cent to 74.62 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose .43 cent to 56.50 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell .40 cent 
to 54.05 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
