<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> David Duke Questioned About Payment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Former Ku Klux Klan leader David Duke on  
Thursday was called before a grand jury investigating a $150,000 
payment he received from Gov. Mike Foster during the 1995 
gubernatorial campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Both men say the payment was for a list of Duke supporters and  
they have done nothing wrong. But the high price for the list has 
raised questions about whether the money was actually for something 
else. 
</P>
<P>
	Some have suggested the money was a payoff to keep Duke out of  
the race, which Foster won. When asked about it, Duke responded: 
``Ridiculous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I already had decided to get out of the race'' before the list  
was sold, Duke said. 
</P>
<P>
	Foster also denied it.  
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, I didn't pay him to stay out of the race,'' said  
Foster, who said he had not been summoned before the grand jury but 
would cooperate with investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke decided not to run in the 1995 governor's campaign,  
surprising many observers who thought he might try to capitalize on 
his strong support in the predominantly white New Orleans suburbs. 
</P>
<P>
	At the grand jury Thursday, Duke exercised his Fifth Amendment  
right against self-incrimination and refused to answer questions. 
He contends the investigation is a smear effort on Foster 
orchestrated by U.S. Attorney Eddie Jordan on behalf of Congressman 
William Jefferson, who is running against Foster for governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Jordan and Jefferson are black and worked in the same law  
firm at different times. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan refused comment, citing grand jury secrecy laws.  
</P>
<P>
	Jefferson said he had never talked with Jordan about the case  
and called on Foster and Duke to produce ``some straight talk'' 
about the payment. 
</P>
<P>
	Selling mailing lists is common during political campaigns.  
</P>
<P>
	Duke said a similar list was sold to state Rep. Woody Jenkins  
for $82,500 during Jenkins' unsuccessful bid for the U.S. Senate in 
1996. Jenkins said the payment included money for computer 
equipment that maintained the list and automatically dialed names 
on the list. 
</P>
<P>
	Terry Ryder, the governor's deputy chief of staff, said Foster  
bought the list with his personal money and never used it in the 
campaign so it was never reported on campaign finance forms. Ryder 
said $100,000 was for exclusive use of the list and another $50,000 
to renew the exclusive use. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke said he did not personally sell the lists but went through  
a broker, Impact Mail Inc., of Metairie. Duke said he believed the 
company received a 10 percent commission. Duke said he did not own 
any part of the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke has not been given immunity and he has not been labeled a  
target of the investigation, said his attorney, James McPherson. 
However, McPherson advised Duke not to answer questions on grounds 
of self-incrimination, saying Duke had nothing to gain by 
testifying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
