<DOCNO> APW19990520.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 07:51:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hacker Case Against Analyst Dropped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prosecutors have dropped charges against a fired  
analyst for the Morgan Stanley brokerage firm, saying the company 
may have paid a witness $10,000 to help set him up on a forgery 
rap. 
</P>
<P>
	Charges against Christian Curry, 24, were dismissed Tuesday.  
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and the witness are now under 
investigation, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as we're concerned, the case against Christian Curry is  
over,'' said Daniel Castleman, the chief investigator for the 
Manhattan district attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
	The odd case began in April 1998 when Curry was fired from his  
entry level job as an investment analyst. The company said he was 
dismissed for abusing his expense account. But Curry claimed he was 
fired because he is black and because they thought he was gay after 
explicit photographs taken of him while he was in college were 
published in a gay magazine without his knowledge. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Curry's attorneys, Benedict Morelli, said Curry is not  
gay. Morelli filed a grievance challenging Curry's dismissal. 
</P>
<P>
	While awaiting the company's response to the grievance, Morelli  
said, Curry talked to a college acquaintance about planting phony 
e-mail in the company computer system to bolster his claim that 
Morgan Stanley was racist and homophobic. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquaintance, C. Joseph Luethke, reported their talks first  
to Morgan Stanley officials, then to police, who sent in an 
undercover detective posing as a computer hacker. Morelli 
acknowledged that Curry offered the undercover detective $200 to 
plant the phony e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Curry was arrested in August and charged with forgery, coercion  
and tampering with physical evidence, but the district attorney's 
office said it has since learned that the company paid Luethke. 
</P>
<P>
	``In fact, within days of the defendant's arrest, officials at  
Morgan Stanley wired a $10,000 payment into an account designated 
by the confidential informant,'' said Leroy Frazer, an assistant 
district attorney, at a court hearing Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Morgan Stanley officials withheld from this office information  
regarding the facts and circumstances of this payment,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan Stanley officials wouldn't comment Tuesday and did not  
immediately return calls today. 
</P>
<P>
	Curry's attorney said he was considering a lawsuit against  
Morgan Stanley, accusing the firm of libel, conspiracy and 
violating Curry's human rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Curry is now working as a model in Beverly Hills, Calif. He  
referred all questions to his attorneys. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 20:51:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Up at Midday / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks edged slightly higher Friday, with  
many investors sidelined to monitor upcoming corporate earnings 
announcements. The dollar dropped against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 34.63  
points, or 0.21 percent, to 16,234.62 by the end of the morning 
session. On Thursday, the average closed up 71.81 points, or 0.44 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar slipped against the yen after early gains, falling to  
123.83 yen, 0.65 yen below its level late Thursday in Tokyo and 
also below its late New York level of 124.40. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the Nikkei 225 briefly dropped below 16,000  
for the first time since April 1. But with the index down more than 
6 percent from a high set on May 6, further downside risk is 
limited, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, they don't expect a quick rebound in share  
prices either, especially since the U.S. Federal Reserve's hint at 
an interest rate hike has cooled off the action on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the U.S. market's volatility declining after the Federal  
Reserve's change in bias for its monetary policy, Tokyo shares 
should also stabilize at current levels,'' said Masaaki Higashida, 
deputy general manager at Nomura Securities Co. ``Adjusting 
positions for a while, players are waiting for the market's 
rebound.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Players were also waiting to monitor corporate earnings  
statements, which have been coming out this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue chips were mixed. Sony, TDK, Fujitsu, Tokyo Electron,  
Kyocera, Honda, Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, NTT Mobile 
Communications and Fuji Photo were weaker, while NEC, Advantest, 
Toyota and Bridgestone were up. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in banks and brokerages are generally higher after recent  
declines. Major commercial banks will announce earnings results 
later Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section was up 4.80 points, or 0.37 percent, to 
1,306.67. The TOPIX closed up 1.26 points, or 0.10 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the greenback had gained early Friday  
following remarks from U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin that 
the United States had no intention to use its currency as a trade 
policy tool. That indicated the government had no plans to make 
American exports cheaper by undermining the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 131.36 yen, down  
from 132.44 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.325 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.295 percent, driving 
its price down to 101.55 yen from 101.82 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 06:41:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Morgan Stanley Sued for Bias </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A former investment analyst sued one of Wall  
Street's largest firms for $1.35 billion Wednesday, alleging they 
fired him because he is black, told lies about him, and then had 
him arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	Christian Curry, 25, said he worked for Morgan Stanley Dean  
Witter as a real estate analyst from July 1997 until he was fired 
in April 1998. He says he suffered bigotry and harassment almost 
the entire time. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials said they fired Curry for expense account  
abuses, but Curry says they fired him because he is black and 
because they thought he was homosexual after nude photos of him 
appeared in a gay men's magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Four months after they fired Curry, company officials told  
police he was plotting to plant racist and homophobic e-mail in 
their computers. Curry was arrested Aug. 20 on charges of forgery, 
coercion and computer trespass. 
</P>
<P>
	The Manhattan district attorney's office Wednesday dropped  
charges against Curry and is now investigating Morgan Stanley and 
the informant who tipped them to the alleged scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Curry's lawyers, Earl Rawlins, admits that Curry paid a  
hacker, actually an undercover police officer, $200 to plant the 
phony e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	The informant and Morgan Stanley officials never revealed to  
investigators that they were negotiating with each other, which 
ruined them as witnesses in the case, said Assistant District 
Attorney Leroy Frazier. 
</P>
<P>
	``Within days of the defendant's arrest,'' Frazier said  
Wednesday in Manhattan Criminal Court, ``officials at Morgan 
Stanley wired a $10,000 payment into an account designated by the 
confidential informant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference to announce his lawsuit against Morgan  
Stanley and several company officials, Curry said ``the most 
outrageous incident'' involving him occurred at a Christmas party. 
</P>
<P>
	He was asked to mock one of Morgan Stanley's black executives by  
wearing an Afro wig and making his lips appear larger. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I refused I was berated,'' Curry said.  
</P>
<P>
	Jeanmarie McFadden, spokeswoman for Morgan Stanley, said the  
firm had not seen Curry's lawsuit, but she issued a statement 
saying the firm ``regrets the decision on the part of the DA's 
office to drop the charges against Christian Curry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that our conduct and the conduct of our employees  
in this matter was entirely appropriate and legal,'' McFadden said. 
``We do not tolerate harassment of any kind at the firm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked to explain the $1.35 billion that the lawsuit is asking,  
one of Curry's lawyers, Benedict Morelli, said, ``When you punish 
someone who is worth $45 billion, you don't sue for a million.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
