<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan Backs U.S. Reform Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told  
Congress today that Fed policy-makers support Clinton 
administration efforts to make the global financial system less 
susceptible to future Asian-style currency crises. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin sounded the same  
reform themes in a joint appearance before the House Banking 
Committee. They outlined steps policy-makers have taken to deal 
with the 22-month-long crisis that has plunged one-third of the 
global economy into recession and sent America's trade deficit to 
record levels. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin told the committee that a number of steps have already  
been taken to strengthen rules to encourage greater financial 
disclosure by developing countries and to put into place guidelines 
that will discourage these countries from taking too many risks 
when they borrow money. 
</P>
<P>
	``The international community, with the leadership of the United  
States, has made important progress so far,'' Rubin said. ``There 
is now a broad-based consensus on the appropriate framework for 
reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, the administration's point man in dealing with the Asian  
crisis, announced last week that he will step down as treasury 
secretary in July and President Clinton said he will nominate 
Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers as Rubin's replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan, who issued a strong statement of support for Summers  
last week, continued to signal to financial markets that he and 
other Fed policy-makers are working closely with the administration 
to deal with the global crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``We at the Federal Reserve are in broad agreement with the  
approach outlined by Secretary Rubin and expect to continue to work 
closely with the Treasury in this area,'' Greenspan said in his 
committee testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Rubin and Greenspan called on the private sector to share  
more of the burden of bad investment decisions. One of the 
principal criticisms of the massive bailouts of Mexico in 1995 and 
Asian nations, Russia and Brazil in the recent crisis has been that 
much of the money went to repay foreign investors who made bad 
bets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the ill-advised investing of recent years can be  
avoided in the future if investors ... are more appropriately 
forewarned'' that they will suffer losses, Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin in his testimony repeated a package of proposals the  
administration first unveiled last month immediately before the 
spring meetings of the 182-nation International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Those suggestions for the most part represent alterations of  
existing rules to encourage greater disclosure by nations of their 
true financial position and discourage inappropriate risk-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF last month adopted a key Clinton proposal to provide  
countries with preapproved loans in hopes it will discourage 
speculative attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that the result of the approach I have outlined  
will be a more robust global economy that is less susceptible to 
instability and crisis,'' Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said countries need to put in place improved financial  
reporting standards, citing in particular the need for foreign 
central banks to publish accurate statistics on the amount of 
foreign currency reserves they are holding. 
</P>
<P>
	``I find it difficult to believe, for example, that the crises  
that arose in Thailand and Korea would have been nearly so virulent 
had their central banks published data prior to the crisis on net 
reserves instead of the not very informative gross reserve 
positions only,'' Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan repeated that he favors a rule of thumb put forward by  
Pablo Guidotti, the deputy finance minister of Argentina, that 
countries should manage their external debt holdings so their 
reserves could carry them a full year without any new foreign 
borrowing. 
</P>
<P>
	While the U.S. economy has escaped relatively unscathed from the  
global turmoil, certain sectors, most notably manufacturing and 
farming, have been battered by the loss of overseas markets and 
increased competition from imports. 
</P>
<P>
	The government reported earlier today that the U.S. trade  
deficit for March set a third straight monthly record, rising to 
$19.7 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
