<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Fall, Tokyo Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian markets fell Thursday on lingering  
worries over a possible rise in U.S. interest rates, but Tokyo's 
key index bounced back from a five-day decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 71.81  
points, or 0.44 percent, closing at 16,199.99. Before Thursday's 
rebound, the Nikkei had lost 819.19 points over the previous five 
trading days, including Wednesday's 250.44-point drop, or 1.53 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei was down most of the day, but rebounded in the last  
30 minutes of trading as institutional investors picked up 
selective shares, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors remained bearish on worries that Japan's economy is  
not gaining momentum and frustration that the government appears 
reluctant to push new steps to stimulate the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the U.S. dollar extended its seven-month  
high against the Japanese yen. In late trading, the dollar bought 
124.48 yen in late afternoon, up 0.78 yen from late Wednesday in 
Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 124.21 yen 
overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the blue-chip index fell on local interest rate  
concerns, but China-related shares bucked the downward trend on 
expectations of more economic restructuring in mainland China. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng index fell 27.72 points, or 0.22 percent, at  
12,375.42. On Wednesday, the index fell 1.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were concerned that Hong Kong interest rates were  
unlikely to fall in the coming months, following news Tuesday that 
the U.S. Federal Reserve was inclined to adopt a tighter monetary 
policy to curb inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong interest rates usually follow the movement of U.S.  
rates because the Hong Kong dollar is pegged to the U.S. currency. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Shares fell following a drop in blue-chip Securities  
One PCL. The SET index fell 3.90 points, or 0.8 percent, to 479.60. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Shares rose as local investors bought blue chips  
through state-owned securities houses. The JSX Composite Index rose 
0.449 points, or 0.07 percent, to 594.053. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares rose on renewed buying interest in blue  
chips. The Composite Index rose 3.89 points, or 0.5 percent, to 
779.62. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Shares fell on selling in technology stocks. The  
Weighted Price Index fell 5.72 points, or 0.1 percent, to 7,608.88. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares fell on worries of a rise in U.S. interest rates.  
The PSE Index fell 21.62 points, or 0.9 percent, to 2,369.20. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Shares fell 3.6 percent as foreign and local investors  
sold on a weak yen against the U.S. dollar. The KOSPI fell 26.38 
points to 108.98. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares rose on robust export figures, which were  
higher than earlier forecasts. The STI rose 15.39 points, or 0.8 
percent, to 1,926.89. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares fell on a late sell-off in the futures market.  
The All Ordinaries index fell 28.6 points, or 0.95 percent, to 
2,952.6. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares fell 1.6 percent following a 39-point drop by  
Telecom Corp. of New Zealand Ltd. The NZSE-40 Capital Index closed 
35.55 points lower at 2,135.14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
