<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Officer Said To Boast of Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In an account never before made public, a police  
sergeant testified that an officer bragged about brutalizing a 
prisoner in a police station bathroom before showing off the stick 
he allegedly used to torture the Haitian immigrant. 
</P>
<P>
	``I took a man down tonight,'' Sgt. Kenneth Wernick quoted  
Justin Volpe as saying about the attack on Abner Louima that 
shocked the city and raised tensions between police and minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe, 27, is charged with ramming a broken broomstick into the  
handcuffed prisoner's rectum and mouth in a fit of rage. 
Prosecutors say Volpe mistakenly thought Louima, 32, punched him in 
a disturbance outside a Brooklyn nightclub. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Wernick, Volpe said he ``took a stick and put it  
five or six inches up his (rectum), took it out and put it up to 
his mouth and teeth area, kind of like showing it to him. ... He 
told him that if he told anyone, he'd kill him and his whole 
family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After asking Wernick if he wanted to see the stick, Volpe took  
him into the bathroom and retrieved a 2- to 3-foot, gray-colored 
stick from a sink area, the witness said. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, ``He pointed the stick at me and said, `You see this  
sh--? You see this sh--?'' Wernick said. The witness said he then 
watched Volpe go over to a dumpster and raise the stick, but turned 
away before seeing whether he threw it in. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want to be involved,'' Wernick said.  
</P>
<P>
	Officers Charles Schwarz, Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese are  
also charged with violating Louima's civil rights by beating him in 
a patrol car en route to the station. A fifth defendant, Sgt. 
Michael Bellomo, is charged with covering up the incident. 
</P>
<P>
	Wernick -- a former patrolman who was promoted shortly after the  
Louima scandal broke -- was to return to the stand today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
