<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Helms Praised on Nominations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A day after the Clinton administration lost  
another nominee for a key diplomatic post in a dispute with Sen. 
Jesse Helms, State Department spokesman James P. Rubin praised 
Helms for ``great cooperation'' in getting nominations through the 
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said Wednesday that the State Department fares better than  
other agencies in getting its nominees confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	The spokesman also soft-pedaled differences over the  
long-delayed nomination of Richard Holbrooke to be U.N. ambassador, 
putting most of the blame for delay on the State Department's own 
investigative process. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was only quite recently that all the paperwork was provided  
following the work that the administration had to do,'' Rubin said. 
``So I wouldn't presume that he (Helms) has slowed the process. 
There's an investigative process that went through. It took a very 
long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Agency for International Development Administrator Brian Atwood  
withdrew his nomination to be ambassador to Brazil on Tuesday, 
saying he would never get past Helms, chairman of the Senate 
Foreign Relations Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The North Carolina Republican opposed the nomination, Atwood  
said, because of Atwood's successful campaign to defeat the 
senator's proposal to merge USAID into the State Department. Helms 
had no comment on Atwood's withdrawal. 
</P>
<P>
	The senator and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright had agreed  
to a merger of three agencies into the State Department, but their 
plan never made it through Congress. The final merger plan retained 
USAID's independence while consolidating the arms control and 
information agencies into the State Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said Atwood made his own decision to withdraw just Tuesday  
and the administration had fully supported him. 
</P>
<P>
	The question of Helms' cooperation came up at a State Department  
briefing in which Rubin was asked about opposition to the 
nomination of Peter Romero, who is acting assistant secretary of 
state for Western Hemisphere affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., wrote a letter to Helms recently urging  
that he block the nomination of Romero to become assistant 
secretary because of concerns over Romero's stance on Cuba and his 
role in U.S. contacts with the Colombian rebel group FARC. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said U.S. contacts with FARC came at the request of the  
Colombian government and Albright fully supports Romero as the 
nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombia's new president, Andres Pastrana, ``thought that our  
assistance might help stop this brutal civil war and thus enable 
Colombia to be in a position to better fight the drug war without 
having to deal with the civil conflict that's going on,'' Rubin 
said, dismissing Burton's concerns as misplaced. 
</P>
<P>
	On Helms, Rubin said ``he believes it is his right to pursue his  
prerogatives in this area. And he certainly has that right under 
the Senate's rules. We think that, by and large, we have received 
great cooperation from Senator Helms in putting through an enormous 
number of nominees.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
