<HEADLINE> Mazda Reports a Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Mazda Motor Corp. posted its first annual profit in  
six years on Thursday, citing gains in North America and Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Hiroshima-based Mazda, which is 33.4 percent owned by Ford Motor  
Co. of the United States, earned 38.71 billion yen, or $310.97 
million, in the fiscal year ended March 31 compared with a loss of 
6.8 billion yen a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's fifth biggest auto company also credited the impact of a  
weaker yen against the dollar, which increased the value of its 
dollar-denominated income from overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am confident that Mazda is on the right track for a complete  
turnaround,'' company president James Miller said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda's group sales in the business year ended in March climbed  
0.8 percent to 2.06 trillion yen, or $16.54 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also said it expects net income to grow to a record  
40 billion yen on sales of 2.59 trillion yen in the current fiscal 
year, despite a prolonged recession in its home market of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Group earnings should be helped by cost-cutting moves and  
Mazda's disposal of low-yielding assets, said senior managing 
director Gary Hexter. 
</P>
<P>
	It forecast domestic sales will climb 8.1 percent in fiscal 1999  
to 340,000 vehicles, spurred by the debut of new models such as the 
Premacy. Exports were projected to increase 6.1 percent to 580,000 
units, led by shipments to North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda estimates its overall production will rise 5.7 percent to  
865,000 vehicles over the course of the fiscal year, which ends 
March 31, 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
