<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Cup-Winning Teammates Duel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A decade ago, the Calgary Flames won the Stanley  
Cup with help from second-year center Joe Nieuwendyk and rookie 
right wing Theo Fleury. Young and talented, Nieuwendyk and Fleury 
had reason to expect more titles to follow. 
</P>
<P>
	It hasn't worked out that way. Despite solid careers, neither  
has even come as close as the conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Until now.  
</P>
<P>
	Nieuwendyk and the Dallas Stars meet Fleury and the Colorado  
Avalanche in the Western Conference finals beginning Saturday. No 
matter which team wins the series, either Nieuwendyk or Fleury will 
get a chance to again have his name etched onto hockey's premier 
trophy. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of players on both sides who can put the puck  
in the net, and both teams have good goaltending,'' Fleury said. 
``It's going to be a great series. I'm just excited to be a part of 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars reached this round last year, but Nieuwendyk missed it  
with a knee injury suffered midway through the first period of the 
first postseason game. It was a devastating blow to Dallas as 
Nieuwendyk had led the team in goals and points during the regular 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	This postseason, Nieuwendyk is making up for the lost time. His  
three game-winning goals are tied for the playoff lead, as are his 
two overtime goals. Over 10 games, he has six goals and three 
assists. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleury also is making the most of his chance to play in late  
May, scoring five goals and assisting on nine others. His 14 points 
tie teammate Joe Sakic for third in the playoffs. Another teammate, 
Peter Forsberg, leads the list with 17 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fleury is another threat for them, but he's not asked to carry  
the load like he was in Calgary the last few years,'' Nieuwendyk 
said. ``I think he's a real good fit for that team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since Nieuwendyk left the Flames in December 1995, Fleury has  
played in four playoff games -- all at the end of that season. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Fleury established himself as one of the league's top  
scorers and became an all-star for the sixth time this season, he 
was likely to leave Calgary as an unrestricted free agent this 
summer. The Flames made no secret of their desire to trade him, and 
on Feb. 28 he was sent to Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-foot-6, 160-pounder with the laser shot and quick skates  
scored in his first game for the Avalanche but also sprained his 
right knee. He missed seven games, then scored again in his first 
game back. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's really an opportunistic kind of guy,'' Nieuwendyk said.  
``He won't be overly aggressive on the forecheck, but he'll be the 
guy coming in late who seems to get the goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because Fleury is on a team loaded with scorers, opponents are  
hesitant to target him for fear of being hurt by someone else. 
Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock said his team's biggest challenge will 
be finding a way to handle Colorado's depth. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you know you have more firepower, you can almost play  
cocky at times,'' Hitchcock said. ``Fleury brings that cocky 
attitude that says, `We're going to beat you with the puck and beat 
you bad.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Stars center Mike Modano knows what to expect from Fleury  
because they've played against each other since they were juniors 
in Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	``He and Sakic went head-to-head in that league for a long time  
for the scoring championship and you could just sense back then 
that he had ability,'' Modano said. ``A lot of this game is speed, 
and if you can skate, you can play in this game.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
