<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nude Statue Returns to Library Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A nude statue banned a century ago -- not because  
of her nakedness, but because the figure was holding a bunch of 
grapes -- is reclaiming her rightful spot at the nation's oldest 
public library. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of a $60 million renovation at the Boston Public  
Library, the bronze ``Bacchante and Infant Faun's'' could be in 
place by next spring. 
</P>
<P>
	The statue, by Frederic Macmonnies, depicts a woman holding a  
naked infant in one hand and a bunch of grapes in the other. The 
child looks longingly toward the fruit. The statue's name is a 
derivation of Bacchus, the Roman god of wine. 
</P>
<P>
	Unveiled in 1895 at the height of Boston's temperance movement,  
it was branded a ``monument to inebriety.'' The Rev. James B. Brady 
attacked it as ``strumpetry'' and ``the worst type of harlotry with 
which the earth was ever afflicted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``No tipsy statue for the public library,'' shouted the Boston  
Post, which campaigned against the figure. 
</P>
<P>
	Other cities simply laughed. ``Too naughty for Boston Library,''  
read a headline in the New York Herald. 
</P>
<P>
	The fuss so outraged library architect Charles F. McKim, who had  
commissioned the work, that he bestowed the sculpture on New York's 
Metropolitan Museum. ``Removed from Puritan surroundings to this 
Metropolis, where she belongs,'' McKim wrote to the sculptor. 
</P>
<P>
	A replica was commissioned by the Boston library in 1993 and  
stands inside the building. That is the statue that is going to be 
moved to the courtyard. 
</P>
<P>
	The outrage was a precursor to the puritanical wrath that  
flourished in 1920s Boston, which banned Henry Miller novels, D.H. 
Lawrence's ``Lady Chatterley's Lover'' and dancer Isadora Duncan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
