<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Death Row Inmate To Go to Tenn. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- DNA evidence cleared Ronald Jones of murder and  
got him off death row in Illinois after eight years. But he won't 
be getting out from behind bars just yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones was convicted of a 1979 robbery in Tennessee and was  
serving five years in prison when he escaped from a community work 
crew in 1980, said Pam Hobbins, a spokeswoman for the Tennessee 
Department of Corrections. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, 49, appeared briefly in court Wednesday and waived his  
right to fight extradition to Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just waiting for authorities from Tennessee to come and  
pick him up; he's basically their prisoner,'' said Cook County 
sheriff's spokesman Bill Cunningham. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones was convicted of the March 1985 rape and killing of Debra  
Smith outside a Chicago hotel. He confessed to the crime but 
claimed that police had beaten the confession out of him. 
</P>
<P>
	The Illinois Supreme Court overturned the conviction in July  
1997 after DNA tests of semen showed that Jones was not the 
assailant. Prosecutors announced Monday that they would not retry 
him on the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones became the 12th condemned person in Illinois to be  
exonerated in the last 12 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
