<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Rise Modestly; Dow Up 30.97 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose modestly today amid fresh evidence  
that the U.S. economy is growing at a steady but not inflationary 
pace. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 30.97 at 10,918.36. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also posted slim gains. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was up 5.04 at 1,349.27, and the Nasdaq composite 
index was up 6.32 at 2,583.72. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good looking day,'' said Larry Wachtel, market analyst  
at Prudential Securities in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders took their cues from a Philadelphia Federal Reserve  
survey that indicated inflation remains in check. Stock and bond 
markets have been highly sensitive to signs of inflation since last 
Friday, when the government reported an unusually steep jump in the 
consumer price index. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Federal Reserve said that more signs of  
inflation could prompt an increase in interest rates some time this 
year. Since then, the market has struggled to break out of a narrow 
range as investors weigh the possibility of higher rates and the 
negative impact they would have on corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a sense of relief from the Philly meeting,'' Wachtel  
said. ``Things are calm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan maintained that sense of calm as he  
kept his remarks to the House Banking Committee today focused on 
the global economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The market took two government economic reports in stride. The  
Commerce Department said the nation's deficit rose to a record high 
in March, led by a widening gap with Japan. Meanwhile, the Labor 
Department said the number of Americans filing new claims for 
unemployment benefits fell by 12,000 last week to 299,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Mergers provided some extra activity in the market today.  
Healtheon soared for a second straight session as it announced it 
will merge with WebMD Inc. to create an Internet-based health care 
services company. It was up 28 3/4 to 109. 
</P>
<P>
	Merck was among the Dow's biggest advancers, rising 2 1/4 to 72 3/4 as  
analysts anticipated it will soon receive approval for a new 
painkiller. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's gains spanned most sectors. Paper and forest products  
stocks rose after Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised earnings 
estimates for the group. Georgia-Pacific jumped 2 to 91 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	EToys soared in its Nasdaq debut. Shares of the online toy store  
were priced at 20 and opened at 78 before settling back to 76 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Some major Internet businesses were weaker, though. Amazon.com  
Inc. dropped 3 7/8 to 135 11/16 after the company said it plans to 
sell $2 billion in securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 589.86 million 
shares, slightly behind Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 2.81 at 642.35, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 4.48 at 792.84. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
