<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Interest Rates Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The European Central Bank left its key  
interest rate unchanged at 2.5 percent at its regular meeting 
Thursday, as was widely expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank cut the rate by half a percentage point April 8, the  
first reduction since it took over monetary policy for the 11 
European Union nations that adopted the euro currency on Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	It said at the time that that cut, which was bigger than  
expected, would be the last for the foreseeable future, telling 
European capitals that it was their turn to do their part to revive 
lagging growth and cut unemployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 10:25:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: No Compromise on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton asserted today that NATO's  
bombing campaign is working and insisted the alliance will not 
compromise on its demands for the return of ethnic Albanians to 
Kosovo under allied protection. 
</P>
<P>
	``NATO is united in our determination to persist as long as it  
takes to achieve these goals,'' the president said in brief remarks 
in the Rose Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton made no mention of the most contentious issue facing the  
alliance as its bombing campaign entered its ninth week -- whether 
and when to introduce ground troops into Kosovo to get the 
displaced Albanians back home before winter. 
</P>
<P>
	``The refugees must go home with security and self-government,''  
Clinton said, with Defense Secretary William Cohen and Joint Chiefs 
Chairman Gen. Henry H. Shelton standing at his side. ``Serbian 
forces must leave Kosovo, an international security force with NATO 
at its core must deploy to protect people of every ethnicity and 
faith in Kosovo. On this, our country is speaking with a single 
voice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said NATO would not waver, even as public support for  
the bombing campaign has waned in some allied countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will also continue our military campaign until the  
conditions are met,'' he said. ``I believe the campaign is 
working.'' He cited recent NATO claims that signs of dissent within 
Serbia are beginning to mount, including reports of desertions by 
hundreds of Serb soldiers and protests in some Serb communities. 
</P>
<P>
	``President Milosevic should know that he cannot change the  
fundamental terms that we have outlined because they are simply 
what is required for the Kosovars to go home and live in peace,'' 
Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The president praised the House of Representatives for passing  
legislation Tuesday that would provide $12 billion for operations 
related to the bombing campaign, including about $1.1 billion in 
humanitarian aid to the Albanian refugees and the Macedonian and 
other ``front-line'' states that are hosting hundreds of thousands 
of refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is absolutely imperative that the Senate follow suit  
without delay,'' he said. Senate leaders were hoping the chamber 
would approve the measure today. Clinton said he would sign the 
measure as soon as it reaches his desk. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Justice Department, spokesman Myron Marlin said the FBI  
has agreed to send agents to Kosovo, as soon as conditions permit, 
to gather forensic evidence for any future war-crimes tribunal. 

</P>
<P>
	British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, who was due to meet with  
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright late today, said all the NATO 
allies had agreed not to send ground troops into Kosovo until ``the 
endgame'' to secure a cease-fire. 
</P>
<P>
	While Britain has advocated preparations for a ground war in  
case the air attacks fail to produce results, another NATO ally, 
Germany, is against it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am against any change in NATO strategy because I believe it  
is beginning to take effect,'' German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder 
said in Brussels, Belgium. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton stirred speculation about U.S. policy Tuesday when he  
said no option should be ruled out on the use of ground troops, 
although he also said NATO should continue on its present course of 
airstrikes. Previously, Clinton had said he had no intention of 
introducing ground troops into Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright, appearing before a Senate subcommittee before her  
meeting with Cook, conceded that NATO's ``objectives are not easily 
achieved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We all want this confrontation to end, but we must have the  
patience and the spine to make sure it does on the right terms,'' 
she told the Senate Appropriations subcommittee on foreign 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Discussing ``how you come to the end of this,'' Albright  
conceded the possibility that Milosevic would remain in power under 
an agreement she suggested might be negotiated by Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that Serbians would be better off without him, but  
we have to remain focused on what the objectives of this campaign 
are,'' she said. Albright said a NATO force including Americans 
would have to remain at the core of any international peacekeeping 
force. But she also raised the possibility that Serbia might be 
able to keep some of its forces ``around holy sites'' in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress is divided on the administration's strategy in the  
conflict, now in its ninth week. Some members question U.S. 
involvement, others would send in ground troops, and still others 
are critical of Clinton's tactics against the Serb-led Yugoslav 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	There is also considerable backing for the president.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
