<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft May Unseal Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. said Thursday it would  
make it easier for news organizations to get confidential documents 
filed in a lawsuit accusing the world's largest software maker of 
predatory business practices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Salt Lake Tribune, San Jose Mercury News and Bloomberg  
Business News on Thursday asked federal Magistrate Ronald Boyce to 
unseal as many as 40 pretrial exhibits and some 50 other sealed or 
heavily blacked-out documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Salt Lake lawyer James Jardine, representing Microsoft,  
agreed to provide a list specific enough for news organization to 
decide which documents they want to see. 
</P>
<P>
	If Microsoft refuses to turn over a document, Boyce will rule on  
whether it can be released after reviewing it for trade secrets or 
proprietary business information. 
</P>
<P>
	The disclosure request had the support of Caldera Inc. of Orem,  
which is suing Microsoft for pricing and marketing tactics it 
claims destroyed public demand for DR-DOS, an operating system that 
competed against Microsoft's MS-DOS. Both enable personal computers 
to perform basic functions. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft has managed to keep many documents, including  
deposition transcripts, sealed under a broad court order in the 
three-year-old case. Since February, however, the company has had 
to get Boyce's permission to file documents under a court seal. At 
issue are documents sealed before then and any future papers 
Microsoft may try to seal. 
</P>
<P>
	Boyce said federal court has four boxes of ``very boring''  
sealed documents and ``if a newspaper wants to print them, that's 
fine. It'll drive them right out of business.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
