<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Top Government Aide Killed in Rome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Gunmen waiting in ambush shot and killed a top  
government labor official as he left for work Thursday, in what 
Italian political leaders were quick to call an apparent act of 
terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
	The killers -- at least two young men -- lay in wait for Massimo  
D'Antona in a stolen van outside his home near the city center. 
They opened fire when he stepped outside, hitting him at least 
three times in the chest, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Interior Minister Rosa Russo Jervilino said police found two .38  
caliber guns at the scene of the crime. 
</P>
<P>
	``The circumstances of the killing have not yet been  
reconstructed in detail, but from what we know so far we can say 
that there is little doubt of the precise preparation of the ambush 
and of the cold and professional execution,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate word on a possible motive. Suggestions  
ranged from a protest against Italy's participation in NATO to 
D'Antona's standing as a reformer. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators were investigating a claim of responsibility to  
Rome's Il Messagero daily in the name of the feared leftist Red 
Brigades. Other claims came on behalf of the lesser-known Armed 
Communist Cells and the little-known right-wing Armed Phalanx. 
</P>
<P>
	Jervilino called an emergency meeting of the national security  
commission and Walter Veltroni, the leader of the center-left 
governing coalition's main party, urged a state of maximum alert. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have the plain sense of a return to the years of the darkest  
period of our country,'' said Veltroni, head of the Democrats of 
the Left. 
</P>
<P>
	Veltroni was one of many to liken the killing to those of the  
``Years of Lead'' -- the 1970s and 1980s, when Red Brigade bullets 
killed hundreds in Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	D'Antona, 51, was considered one of the country's most  
accomplished labor lawyers and served as Labor Minister Antonio 
Bassolino's top aide. He was Transport Ministry undersecretary in 
the 1995-96 government of then-Premier Lamberto Dini. 
</P>
<P>
	President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi and others went to the morgue to  
pay homage to D'Antona, and labor groups planned days of protests 
in cities across Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
