<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 15:51:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Griffey Jr. Still Having Fun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Whenever Ken Griffey Jr. is in Minneapolis, he  
goes to see his close friend, Kirby Puckett. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I first came into the league, he treated me like I was  
somebody and not a rookie,'' the Seattle Mariners' slugger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Puckett, former star for the Minnesota Twins who now is an  
executive vice president with the team, offered Griffey some good 
advice. Griffey still uses it. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said, `Smile and do what you've got to do,' '' Griffey  
said. '' `Just play hard and have some fun.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	The charismatic Griffey is still smiling and having fun 11  
seasons later. He's one of the most popular players in the game and 
perhaps the best. 
</P>
<P>
	He's an American League MVP, a three-time AL home run champion,  
a nine-time All-Star and a nine-time Gold Glove center fielder. 
He's led the majors in voting for the All-Star game the past three 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey is off to a fast start this season with 16 home runs in  
39 games to share the major league home run lead with Tampa Bay's 
Jose Canseco. He has homered in five of his last six games, and he 
has hit in nine straight games. 
</P>
<P>
	Next week, Seattle will be at Minnesota and Griffey plans to  
visit Puckett in his office. 
</P>
<P>
	Puckett led the Twins to World Series titles in 1987 and 1991,  
before being forced into early retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1989, Griffey's first season, Puckett told him to enjoy  
baseball as much as he could because it was a gift. Puckett's words 
were prophetic. He was forced out of the game in 1996 when an early 
form of glaucoma left him blind in his right eye. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey remembers Puckett's message fondly.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was towards the end of my rookie season and we were playing  
Minnesota and I didn't run out a ground ball,'' Griffey said. ``He 
said, `Show a little more effort. You ain't got to run under four 
seconds, but just do a little more. And smile.' That always 
stuck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another baseball elder whom Griffey has listened to is Chili  
Davis of the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``He always gives me calls during the season when I've done  
something wrong and when I've done something right,'' Griffey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's the late Jackie Robinson. He appreciates everything  
his father, former major leaguer Ken Griffey Sr., has done for him 
and he appreciates everything Robinson did for today's black 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	``He did everything you ask somebody to do and more,'' Griffey  
said. ``He endured the name-calling, the dirty play. If you're the 
only one, it's always hard. He's the one who did it for all of 
us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mariners have another star in Alex Rodriguez, a three-time  
All-Star shortstop. Last season, Rodriguez joined Canseco and Barry 
Bonds in the majors' 40-40 club with 42 homers and 46 stolen bases. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey enjoys watching young players develop into stars. He  
knows Rodriguez is a special talent. Rodriguez is good enough to 
play anywhere on the field, Griffey says. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at our shortstop,'' he said. ``He could play second base  
if he wanted. Third base. First base. The outfield positions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It doesn't matter if a player isn't a center fielder like  
Griffey. If he's got talent, Griffey likes him. He particularly 
enjoys watching Boston shortstop Nomar Garciaparra and Red Sox 
right-hander Pedro Martinez, whom he thinks might be the best 
pitcher in the game today. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that he enjoys hitting against Martinez.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's the one guy who's going to come after you,'' Griffey  
said. ``He's a skinny kid who gives you everything he's got.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Griffey with a smile: ``I don't like pitchers.''  
</P>
<P>
	Among his other favorite players:  
</P>
<P>
	Derek Jeter, Chuck Knoblauch, Bernie Williams and David Cone of  
the world champion Yankees; Frank Thomas of the Chicago White Sox; 
Mark McGwire of St. Louis; Roberto Alomar of Cleveland; Mo Vaughn 
of Anaheim; former teammate Randy Johnson of Arizona; Charles 
Johnson and Cal Ripken of Baltimore; Curt Schilling and Scott Rolen 
of Philadelphia; Ivan Rodriguez and Juan Gonzalez of Texas; Tony 
Gwynn of San Diego, and Wade Boggs of Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of ballplayers who do great things for their  
ballclubs,'' Griffey said. ``Whatever it takes to win. That's all 
that matters.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
