<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar edged higher against the yen early  
Friday following remarks from U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin 
that the United States had no intention to use its currency as a 
trade policy tool. Japanese stocks were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 124.52 yen in early trading, up 0.04 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 
124.40 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average slipped 47.29  
points, or 0.29 percent, to 16,152.70 in the first 30 minutes of 
trading. On Thursday, the average closed up 71.81 points, or 0.44 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar was supported by reassuring  
comments from Rubin that the United States was not about to use the 
greenback to reduce the country's trade deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin's remarks in Washington on Thursday came following news of  
a record-high U.S. trade deficit of $19.7 billion for March. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials in the past have used the currency as a trade  
policy measure in an attempt to pare the nation's ballooning trade 
deficits by pushing its trade partner's currencies, such as the 
yen, higher. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen makes Japan's exports more expensive aboard and  
thus less competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 131.98 yen, down  
from 132.44 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, some investors bought shares on dips after  
the Nikkei average closed below 17,000 points Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue chips were mixed. Sony, TDK and Honda Motor were slightly  
lower, while NEC, Toyota Motor and Fujitsu were among early 
gainers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section was up 1.25 points, or 0.09 percent, to 
1,303.12. The TOPIX closed up 1.26 points, or 0.10 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 20.65  
points to 10,866.74 at Thursday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.330 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.295 percent, driving 
its price down to 101.51 yen from 101.82 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
