<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest CEO's Health Made an Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A shareholder is worried about the longevity of  
Southwest Airline's leader, since Herb Kelleher is considered the 
brain trust of the low-cost carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	A proposal put forward by shareholder Michael Schaefer would  
have made chairman, CEO and president Kelleher choose between 
running either the board or day-to-day operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Schaefer's concern was with the airline founder's penchant for  
cigarettes, Wild Turkey liquor and frequently flying aboard an 
airline that routinely offers fat- and salt-laden peanuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Schaefer had warned in his proposal that ``Kelleher's longevity  
is speculative, since he is a chain smoker, 67, and a frequent 
flier. Unless nudged by the shareholders to divide his control and 
responsibility he simply won't do it,'' the document said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders didn't vote on the issue because Schaefer didn't  
attend Thursday's meeting. A Southwest spokeswoman said his flight 
on another airline was canceled. Schaefer was not immediately 
available for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelleher has always had a tongue-in-cheek style that has created  
a corporate culture at Southwest which is known as a casual airline 
with high customer satisfaction. Fortune magazine named it the 
country's most admired airline, and this year, the best place to 
work in the U.S. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelleher himself has become an icon as a personable and savvy  
leader. As for his personal habits, they're probably not that 
healthy, he and his staff admit. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelleher, who has been chairman of the carrier since 1978 and  
CEO and president since 1981, said he doesn't think he smokes too 
much. 
</P>
<P>
	He also pointed out that he gives up drinking every February and  
there will be a Leap Year in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thanks to Pope Gregory and the Gregorian calendar I now have  
to stop drinking for an extra day,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Boardmembers Travis Johnson and Walter Mischer said Kelleher's  
zany comments and spirited ribaldry are good for the airline. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great asset. It brings nourishment to the  
shareholders,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
