<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Approves TV License Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- EchoStar Communications Corp. was cleared by  
federal regulators Wednesday to acquire the last available U.S. 
license to beam TV shows and other services directly to pizza-sized 
dishes at people's homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Communications Commission's action should make  
Littleton, Colo.-based EchoStar a stronger competitor in the 
satellite TV business. 
</P>
<P>
	It also should help EchoStar better compete against cable TV  
companies, the FCC said. 
</P>
<P>
	EchoStar is acquiring the license and other assets from MCI  
WorldCom and Rupert Murdoch's News Corp.. Both MCI and News Corp. 
will be investors in EchoStar. 
</P>
<P>
	For consumers, the deal means more channels and services by  
early 2000. The company has said it will have the ability to 
provide more than 500 channels of programming, Internet access and 
other data services at that time. 
</P>
<P>
	It also helps EchoStar's technical efforts to provide satellite  
TV viewers with local broadcast channels -- a move that requires 
both extra channel space and federal legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	``By allowing companies like EchoStar to become stronger  
competitors to cable, the FCC is clearing the way for consumers to 
have more choices in how they get their television programming,'' 
said FCC Chairman Bill Kennard. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
