<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Georgia School Shooting Wounds 6  
</P>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- No one was killed today when a 15-year-old  
boy, apparently troubled by a broken romance, opened fire in a 
suburban Atlanta high school. Witnesses said the boy shot randomnly 
and fired at people below the waist, so as to injure but not kill. 
Six people were hit by the shots at Heritage High School, with none 
of the injuries being life-threatening. The student was carrying a 
.22-caliber rifle and a .22-caliber revolver. Authorities said the 
boy has been charged as a juvenile with aggravated assault, and may 
face other charges. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate OKs Gun-Show Restrictions  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With yet another school shooting occurring in  
the United States, the Senate today narrowly passed restrictions on 
firearms sales at gun shows and pawnshops. Vice President Al Gore 
broke a tie vote in order to pass the curbs opposed by most 
Republicans. The proposal would require background checks for all 
sales at gun shows. It also would close what gun control advocates 
said was a loophole that allows anyone to pawn his gun and reclaim 
it without undergoing a check. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds Approve Bankers Trust Merger  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve approved today the  
proposed $10.2 billion merger of Bankers Trust Corp. and Germany's 
Deutsche Bank AG, which would create the world's largest financial 
institution. The vote was 6-0 by the central bank's board of 
governors, who determined the merger of the nation's eighth-largest 
bank with Germany's largest would not threaten banking competition 
in this country. The merger, proposed last November, would create a 
financial powerhouse with $830 billion in assets. 

</P>
<P>
	House Approves Missile Defense Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is expected to sign  
legislation passed today that would commit the United States to an 
anti-missile national defense system. The legislation, passed 
345-71, states that it is the policy of the United States to 
deploy, as soon as technologically possible, an effective system 
capable of defending U.S. territory against limited ballistic 
missile attack. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Bombs Damage Belgrade Hospital  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Belgrade and its suburbs were  
heavily bombed by NATO jets today, leaving three patients dead at a 
hospital hit hard in the attacks. Homes of three European 
ambassadors were damaged, as was the Libyan embassy. There were new 
accounts of desertions in the Yugoslav army, and there was a fresh 
round of diplomacy in Moscow involving Russian, Finnish and 
American envoys. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Mission Arrives in Pristina  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A U.N. mission accompanied by two  
foreign journalists arrived today to investigate the humanitarian 
needs of Kosovo after eight weeks of NATO bombing and the expulsion 
of an estimated 800,000 ethnic Albanians by Serb forces. Among 
other things, the U.N. team will try to determine what is required 
to facilitate the return of hundreds of thousands of people whose 
homes, businesses and farms have been destroyed. 

</P>
<P>
	Sunken Cruise Ship Passengers Saved  
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- A cruise ship caught fire and sank  
off the western coast of Malaysia early Friday, and authorities 
rescued more than 1,000 passengers. The passengers, including 
Americans, Britons, Canadians and Japanese, were rescued from the 
Bahamian-registered Sun Vista, said a spokesman for the Marine 
Rescue and Coordination Center in Port Klang. There have been no 
reports of fatalities. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 20.65  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned lower in late trading today as  
lingering concerns about leading technology companies sapped the 
market's modest gains. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 20.65 
to close at 10,866.74. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,750-1,219. 
The Nasdaq composite index fell 34.98 to 2,542.42. 

</P>
<P>
	Indy Speedway Lifts Credential Ban  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indianapolis Motor Speedway today lifted  
the ban of a Sports Illustrated writer who had been denied a 
credential partly because the magazine ran a photo of fans killed 
at a race. The ban had raised concerns at several newspapers around 
the country, and the Chicago Tribune said it wasn't going to cover 
the May 30 race as a result. However, speedway president Tony 
George decided to reinstate the credential for SI's senior auto 
writer, Ed Hinton. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
