<HEADLINE> Veterans Finally Get H.S. Diplomas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GARDNER, Mass. (AP) -- Decades ago, Harding Mason left high  
school in his junior year to fight in the Pacific, learning his 
history lessons of World War II firsthand. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, he and 38 other veterans received what they  
abandoned long ago, their diplomas. 
</P>
<P>
	``It fills a void,'' said Mason, 75, waving his diploma aloft on  
the stage of Gardner High School as his grandchildren gave him a 
standing ovation. 
</P>
<P>
	The ceremony was the first held by Operation Recognition, a  
program developed by the Massachusetts Department of Veterans 
Services to award diplomas to honorably discharged veterans and 
those who earned high school equivalency degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	About 600 Gardner students, veterans' relatives and former  
teachers gathered with government officials to witness the 
graduation. Former President Bush, former Sen. Bob Dole and 
director Steven Spielberg sent letters of congratulation. 
</P>
<P>
	Amid cries of ``Grandpa, Grandpa!'' the veterans received  
diplomas on a stage draped with patriotic bunting. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine honorees were killed in combat and received diplomas  
posthumously. Mason accepted a second diploma for his older 
brother, Leslie, who was killed in the North Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	Students decorated the library with old yearbooks and student  
newspapers from the 1940s. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't have made it through what they did,'' said Chris  
Hancock, a senior at Gardner. His grandfather, Edward Misiewicz, 
and great uncle, Edward Gallant, were among Thursday's graduates. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernard Riley, who left for the Army Air Corps in 1944, the  
first month of his senior year, said the awarding of his degree 
carried a surprising significance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't realize how much that diploma would mean to me,'' he  
said, ``until now.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
