<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *Mary Jane Gallaher    	
</P>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Mary Jane Gallaher, a turf writer who also  
worked in advertising and public relations promoting the equine 
industry, died Monday. She was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	She died of a head injury suffered May 11 in a fall down a  
flight of stairs at her home, according to a coroner's report. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallaher wrote about horses and their owners for the Lexington  
Leader in the 1950s. She also wrote for the Thoroughbred Record and 
The Blood-Horse magazines. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallaher wrote about horses at a time when women weren't allowed  
in most racetrack press boxes. She reportedly was the first female 
reporter allowed in the Churchill Downs press box in Louisville. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallaher is survived by her husband, Fred R. Kissling; two  
stepdaughters; and a sister. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Gerald J. Lieberman    	
</P>
<P>
	STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- Gerald J. Lieberman, former Stanford  
University provost, died Tuesday of Lou Gehrig's disease. He was 
73. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning in August 1979, Lieberman served as either acting  
provost or provost during the tenures of three Stanford presidents. 
He retired in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Lieberman earned his doctorate in statistics from Stanford in  
1953 and never left, serving as a statistics and industrial 
engineering professor who focused on reliability theory and 
statistical quality control. 
</P>
<P>
	A textbook he co-authored set the stage for the widespread use  
of control charts in industry and alternative methods of sampling 
inspection. 

</P>
<P>
                           *A.J. Marineau    	
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW, Idaho (AP) -- A.J. ``Jack'' Marineau, longtime newspaper  
publisher and real estate developer, died Tuesday of cancer. He was 
67. 
</P>
<P>
	Marineau began working at News Review Publishing, putting out  
the Idahonian -- now The Moscow-Pullman Daily News -- where his 
father was minority owner and publisher. In 1959, he married Judy 
Stubbs, Idahonian society editor, and became editor-publisher in 
1970. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1980, the Lewiston Morning Tribune became the majority  
stockholder in News Review Publishing. Marineau sold his interest 
to the McClatchy Newspaper Group and retired from the news 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	He got involved with real estate development, founding Marineau  
Management in 1980. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Raymond Motley    	
</P>
<P>
	BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) -- Raymond Motley, a sportscaster and former  
member of the Ohio House of Representatives, died Monday. He was 
87. 
</P>
<P>
	Motley was elected to the Ohio House of Representatives in 1958  
and served one term. He worked for more than 30 years at WMOH radio 
in Hamilton, Ohio, where he was sports director and station 
manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Motley gave current Cincinnati Reds broadcaster Joe Nuxhall his  
first job in radio, hiring him to do color commentary for Miami 
University basketball games in the 1960s in Oxford, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Motley also covered Woody Hayes' final game as Miami's head  
football coach in 1950. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Stu Rider    	
</P>
<P>
	ELKO, Nev. (AP) -- Stu Rider, a veteran broadcaster who has been  
the morning voice of Elko radio for three decades, died Tuesday at 
age 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Rider began his career spinning records and had the job of  
waking up Elkoans in the 6 a.m. morning slot on 1240 KELK AM since 
1970. 
</P>
<P>
	Rider's talents as a broadcaster took him from California to New  
Jersey, with stops in Guam and Hawaii. He was the first television 
news anchor on Guam and broadcast evening news from a Quonset hut 
in the jungle. 
</P>
<P>
	Rider is to inducted into the Nevada Broadcasters Hall of Fame  
next month. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, Margaret, and a daughter.  

</P>
<P>
                          *Robert L. Turner    	
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, N.C. (AP) -- Robert L. Turner, who helped create the  
Eastern Airlines shuttle service between New York and Washington in 
1961, died Saturday. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner began working for Eastern in 1934 as a ticket agent in  
Atlanta. After service in the Air Transport Command during World 
War II, he joined Northeast Airlines and rose to vice president. He 
also worked for the Air Transport Association, where he became 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1959, he returned to Eastern and two years later the shuttle  
was introduced. The service was radical at the time because it 
guaranteed seating without reservations and its low fare. 
</P>
<P>
	After retiring from Eastern in 1969, Turner leased airliners to  
meet peak demand of Eastern and Air Canada. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Donald K. White    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Donald K. White, a former newspaper  
business writer and editor, died Tuesday of pulmonary disease. He 
was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	White, who had hoped to be a doctor, abandoned his premed  
studies at the University of San Francisco when he was asked to 
dissect a frog. 
</P>
<P>
	He quit school and worked for the El Paso Times, the Sacramento  
Union and the Humboldt Star in Winnemucca, Nev. 
</P>
<P>
	White returned to San Francisco as a business writer for the  
Wall Street Journal, San Francisco Chronicle and San Francisco 
Examiner. 
</P>
<P>
	After 13 years as business editor at the Examiner, he joined the  
Crocker Bank as vice president for advertising and public 
relations, then returned to the Chronicle in 1974 as business 
editor and columnist. 
</P>
<P>
	His columns often featured a middle-class San Francisco couple  
named George and Adele, who lived in the Marina with their poodle, 
Sir. White used the couple as a column device for more than 30 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	White retired in 1989. He is survived by his wife, Donna  
Balzarini; a son; and a brother. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Jerry Wunderlich    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Jerry Wunderlich, a Hollywood set decorator  
who received Oscar nominations for ``The Exorcist'' in 1973 and 
``The Last Tycoon'' in 1976, died Sunday of a heart attack. He was 
74. 
</P>
<P>
	His other film credits included ``The Singing Nun,'' ``Audrey  
Rose,'' ``The Entity,'' ``WarGames,'' ``Heat'' and ``The Two 
Jakes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For many years, he designed the decor for the Governors Ball  
following the Academy Awards ceremonies. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Henry Jones    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Tony Award-winning actor Henry Jones, whose  
career on Broadway and in movies and television spanned more than 
half a century, died Monday from injuries suffered in a fall at his 
home. He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	The character actor's bulldog face was familiar from dozens of  
Broadway plays and films and 350 television shows, where he played 
everything from judges to janitors and murderers to ministers. 
</P>
<P>
	When he began his career, ``the casting directors didn't know  
what to do with me,'' Jones once recalled. ``I was never tall 
enough or good looking enough to play juvenile leads.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did have several memorable roles.  
</P>
<P>
	In the 1950s, he was the handyman killed by deadly child Patty  
McCormack in the Broadway play ``The Bad Seed,'' a role he repeated 
in the film. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1958, he won a Tony Award for his portrayal of Louis Howe,  
confidante of Franklin D. Roosevelt, in ``Sunrise at Campobello.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His three dozen films included ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance  
Kid,'' ``Arachnophobia,'' ``The Grifters'' and Alfred Hitchock's 
``Vertigo,'' in which he played a coroner and delivered a 
four-minute monologue. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Philadelphia and educated at St. Joseph's College, Jones  
began his career with theater work in the 1930s and made his 
Broadway debut in 1938 as a gravedigger in ``Hamlet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His movie career started in 1943 with Irving Berlin's ``This Is  
the Army.'' He was an Army private at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	His TV roles began when the medium was in its infancy, with such  
classics as ``Playhouse 90.'' More recently, he was Sam in the 1994 
Hallmark Hall of Fame production of ``Breathing Lessons,'' and in 
1995 was the Assayer in ``Picture Windows.'' 

</P>
<P>
                         *Jerome Jay Wolken    	
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Jerome Jay Wolken, a Carnegie Mellon  
University biophysicist who invented a lens system that gave sight 
to some legally blind people, died May 10. He was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	People with cataracts were the main beneficiaries of his Light  
Concentrating Lens System, developed in the 1980s for use in 
eyeglasses. It reproduced the lenses in deep-sea creatures' eyes 
that allow them to see in almost total darkness. 
</P>
<P>
	One patent for the system involved a pear-shaped lens 10 times  
more sensitive to light than a standard camera lens. 
</P>
<P>
	To develop the system, Wolken researched deep-sea optics at the  
Marine Biological Laboratory and the Oceanographic Research 
Institute at Woods Hole on Cape Cod, Mass., as well as similar 
institutions in Miami, Bermuda, the Bahamas, Europe and Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolken earned bachelor's, master's and doctoral degrees from the  
University of Pittsburgh. He taught at his alma mater in the 1950s 
and was named a professor of biophysics biology in 1962. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years later, Carnegie Mellon appointed him a professor and  
head of the biological sciences department at Morrison Carnegie 
College. He wrote nine books in his field and edited two others in 
additions to contributing many papers to scientific journals. 

</P>
</TEXT>
