<DOCNO> APW19990520.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 05:43:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sculpture Garden Dedicated in D.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A sculpture garden first proposed 30 years ago  
for the National Mall was dedicated Wednesday by Hillary Rodham 
Clinton as a place to rest and romp among shady trees, water and 
modern works. 
</P>
<P>
	``This makes a powerful statement that art should be accessible  
to all people,'' the first lady said about the garden, which opens 
to the public Sunday as part of the National Gallery of Art. 
</P>
<P>
	After the dedication, she strolled through the garden past Barry  
Flanagan's ``Thinker on a Rock,'' a whimsical twist on Rodin's 
``The Thinker'' that shows a long-eared, pensive rabbit; and more 
austere works such as David Smith's pioneering 1965, welded steel 
``Cubi XXVI.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tucked in other corners amid the oak, magnolia and cedar trees,  
azalea bushes and pink geraniums, are a thin sheet of steel, 
``Stele II'' by Ellsworth Kelly; Roy Lichtenstein's ``House I,'' a 
stand-up version of his comic-strip style paintings; and a serene 
slab of stone by Isamu Noguchi called ``Great Rock of Inner 
Seeking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After years of delay and lack of money, the garden was built  
with a $10 million grant from the Morris and Gwendolyn Cafritz 
Foundation, a Washington philanthropy also buying many of the 10 
new works to be exhibited. Six other sculptures come from the 
gallery's present collection; the 17th, the bright-orange abstract 
Cheval Rouge'' (Red Horse) by Alexander Calder, is on loan. 
</P>
<P>
	Taxpayer money will go to maintain the garden, as it does the  
National Gallery next door. 
</P>
<P>
	Calvin Cafritz, the foundation's chairman, said his late  
parents, who established the foundation, would take ``great joy'' 
from seeing children ``romp through the garden'' or gawk at Louise 
Bourgeois' ``Spider,'' a 24-foot spindly bronze work. 
</P>
<P>
	The original 1960s' plans for the garden were abandoned long ago  
after a circular pond that doubled as a wintertime skating rink was 
finished. 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone thought it wasn't dignified to combine art with a  
skating rink, and we couldn't get money from Congress to do the 
garden,'' said J. Carter Brown, chairman of Washington's Fine Arts 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The garden will have no ``Keep Off the Grass'' signs, but five  
security guards will patrol the two-block area, in part to try to 
keep children from climbing the art works. Some, like Sol LeWitt's 
``Four-Sided Pyramid,'' may prove irresistible. 
</P>
<P>
	Exhibits will change periodically but be limited to 20th-century  
and 21st-century work. 
</P>
<P>
	The circular pool, newly enlarged and surrounded by benches,  
occupies the middle of the garden, with arching sprays of water. In 
the winter, it will again become a skating rink. A wrought-iron and 
glass enclosed pavilion with indoor and outdoor seating will open 
in the fall as a cafe and restaurant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
