<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Team Travels To Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NIS, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A U.N. humanitarian team touring  
Yugoslavia is trying to resist pressure to get dragged into public 
discussions about who is suffering more -- ethnic Albanians driven 
from their homes or Serb civilians battered by NATO bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	The mission traveled to Kosovo today to see firsthand the  
destruction caused by the Serb crackdown on ethnic Albanians and by 
the eight-week NATO air campaign. Yugoslav authorities allowed two 
foreign reporters to accompany the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Before a dinner Wednesday arranged by local officials here in  
Yugoslavia's third largest city, the head of the local civil 
defense agency, Jovan Zlatic, presented a grisly set of photographs 
from the autopsy of a pregnant woman killed here in a NATO attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the objections of Mayor Zoran Zivkovic, the official ended  
his presentation with a picture of the destroyed fetus. The head of 
the U.N. team, Sergio de Mello, was then asked by local Serb 
reporters to comment on what he had seen. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're deplorable,'' de Mello said. ``Some of them are  
shocking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But de Mello, a veteran diplomat, added: ``I've told you what I  
think you need to do to stop that,'' meaning reach a political 
solution to the Kosovo crisis, which led to the NATO attack. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO launched its air campaign March 24 after Yugoslav President  
Slobodan Milosevic refused to accept a Western-dictated peace plan 
for Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia's main republic, Serbia. 
Kosovo's population is overwhelming Albanian majority, and most 
favor independence. 
</P>
<P>
	The Western alliance has refused to call off the attacks until  
Milosevic halts ``repression'' in Kosovo, withdraws his forces and 
allows an armed international military force with NATO as its core 
to enter the province to supervise the return of refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	The plight of the ethnic Albanians is not unique in recent  
Balkan history. Since the breakup of Yugoslavia began in 1991, 
other ethnic groups have been driven from their homes or subjected 
to other atrocities by rival groups who had been their fellow 
countrymen. 
</P>
<P>
	The reporters asked de Mello to compare the plight of the ethnic  
Albanians with that of Serbs forced from their own homes in the 
former Yugoslav republics of Croatia and Bosnia-Herzegovina earlier 
in this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have never established any hierarchy between victims,'' de  
Mello replied. ``For me, there is no difference between a refugee 
from Kosovo and a refugee from Croatia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. team is traveling through Yugoslavia to assess the  
humanitarian needs caused by the Kosovo conflict and the NATO air 
campaign. Western officials have warned that unless a solution is 
found quickly, it will be difficult to return the nearly 800,000 
refugees before the harsh Balkan winter sets in. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the refugees have little to return to since their  
villages have been burned and their homes destroyed, either by 
marauding Serb forces or NATO airstrikes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
