<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Reaches 7-Month High Vs. Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose to another seven-month high  
against the yen Thursday as hopes for higher U.S. interest rates 
overshadowed a discouraging trade report. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also added to Wednesday's gains against the euro  
despite news that the U.S. trade deficit soared to a record high 
for the third straight month. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose to 124.40 yen from Wednesday's seven-month high  
of 124.21 yen even though the report showed that the trade gap with 
Japan shot up to the highest level in more than four years. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Thursday, the euro was quoted at $1.0623,  
falling from $1.0657 in Wednesday's late trading in New York. The 
British pound fell to $1.6075 from late Tuesday's $1.6173. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5090 Swiss Francs, up from  
1.5040; and 1.4662 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4673. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department reported early Thursday that the March  
deficit totaled $19.7 billion, up 2.9 percent from February. 
</P>
<P>
	Through the first three months of the year, the U.S. trade  
deficit was running at an annual rate of $222.6 billion, nearly 
one-third higher than last year's all-time high of $169.3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade gap, aggravated by the continuing troubles in foriegn  
economies, hurts the dollar because foreign exporters need to 
convert the dollars they get from U.S. buyers to their local 
currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dollar continued to draw support from Tuesday's  
announcement that the Federal Reserve is now leaning toward higher 
interest rates to keep inflation in check. Higher rates make U.S. 
assets more attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	The currencies of the 11 countries that have switched to the  
euro are no longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a 
fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the euro's latest exchange rate, the dollar was worth:  
1.8413 German marks, up from 1.8352; 6.1767 French francs, up from 
6.1538; and 1,821.49 Italian lire, up from 1,818.18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
