<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Katzenberg Goes After Disney Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``The little midget'' could be in for a giant  
amount of money. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge has ruled that the Walt Disney Co. owes former studio  
boss Jeffrey Katzenberg a piece of the profits, plus interest, from 
movie projects he worked on before he quit in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge didn't say how much interest Katzenberg will receive  
or when the clock should start ticking on the 10 percent-a-year 
rate. But if Katzenberg gets anything close to the $250 million to 
$500 million he says he's owed, the interest would be tens of 
millions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the judge must decide exactly how much money Katzenberg is  
owed. This phase, beginning Monday, is expected to feature the 
return of the central characters in the real-life melodrama of 
Hollywood infighting: Katzenberg and his former boss, Disney 
Chairman Michael Eisner. 
</P>
<P>
	In an unusual spectacle, Katzenberg is going to try to make the  
case that Disney will do tremendously well without him. 
</P>
<P>
	Eisner, Disney's top cheerleader, is in the even more awkward  
position of having to show that its future, while certainly not 
bleak, isn't as rosy as Katzenberg says it will be. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first part of the trial, Katzenberg's lawyer tried to  
show that Eisner had animosity toward his former employee. Under 
questioning, Eisner acknowledged he may have made embarrassingly 
disparaging remarks about Katzenberg, including, ``I think I hate 
the little midget.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eisner said that if he made the remark about Katzenberg, who at  
5-foot-4 is at least a half-foot shorter than Eisner, it was in 
temporary anger after Katzenberg left the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Katzenberg left when Disney wouldn't promote him to president to  
replace Frank Wells, who had died in a helicopter crash. Katzenberg 
went on to form DreamWorks with Steven Spielberg and David Geffen. 
</P>
<P>
	Katzenberg contends his contract guaranteed him a bonus of 2  
percent of his projects' future income if he ever left Disney. 
Disney says he forfeited that bonus by leaving with two years left 
in the six-year deal. 
</P>
<P>
	So now Katzenberg is suing for 2 percent of all profits Disney  
will ever make off nearly every product, including such 
blockbusters as ``The Lion King'' and ``The Little Mermaid,'' 
generated during the 10 years he headed the movie unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney settled with Katzenberg for $117 million, according to  
sources, and both sides agreed to an arbitration proceeding to hash 
out how much more money Katzenberg would get, which products would 
apply, and whether interest would be paid. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the retired judge hearing the dispute ruled Disney  
did in fact breach its contract with Katzenberg and therefore owes 
him interest payments on top of the bonus. Katzenberg also is 
entitled to a cut of profits from Disney products sold in theme 
parks and Disney Stores, Judge Paul Breckenridge said. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
