<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 10:13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Would Sign Kosovo-Aid Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today he would sign a  
compromise $15 billion bill paying for the assault on Yugoslavia, 
support for victims of Caribbean hurricanes and other items, and 
urged Congress to send it to him quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite some unhappiness among Republicans and Democrats alike,  
the Senate began debating the bill and final congressional approval 
was likely today. The House endorsed the legislation on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservatives were unhappy that most of the measure would be  
paid for out of the federal surplus, which comes from Social 
Security, and that the measure contained projects for some 
lawmakers' districts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the pork spending in this bill comes straight out of  
the Social Security trust fund,'' said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Senate Appropriations Committee chairman, Sen. Ted  
Stevens, R-Alaska, a chief author of the bill, said opposing the 
measure ``would send the wrong message for the young men and women 
who represent this country in uniform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at the White House, Clinton said the measure would rush  
badly needed help to Kosovar refugees and countries bordering on 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most important, it will give our military what it needs to see  
its mission through, while maintaining the readiness of our forces 
around the world,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	When GOP senators met privately Wednesday to discuss the  
measure, some complained that all but $2 billion of it would be 
paid for from the federal surplus, participants said. Others were 
upset that most of the claimed savings -- $1.3 billion -- came from 
cutting food stamp funds that would not be spent anyway because the 
healthy economy has reduced dependency on the program. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like'' parts of the bill either, Senate Majority  
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., told reporters. ``But it probably won't 
get better if it's defeated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said the bill should have cut spending  
more so it would eat away less of the budget surplus, which comes 
from Social Security. He said even though he would probably lose, 
he would use Senate procedures to force supporters to get 60 of the 
100 senators to support the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``We say we want to lock up the money from Social Security'' for  
the pension program, he said of Republicans. ``And then we sit idly 
by and watch it be spent. I'm not going to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a very difficult road. A lot of people in  
principle are against the bill, but I believe the bill will pass,'' 
said Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, 
R-Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest chunk of the package, $12 billion, is for the price  
tag of the U.S. aerial assault on Yugoslavia, aid to Kosovar 
refugees and the Balkan countries, and a general buildup of 
American armed forces worldwide. That is twice the sum Clinton 
originally requested, but the White House has abandoned its early 
insistence that defense spending not directly related to Kosovo 
should be dropped. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure has $1 billion for a recent spate of hard-hitting  
natural disasters, chiefly last autumn's Hurricane Mitch, which 
pummeled Honduras, El Salvador, Costa Rica and Nicaragua. Clinton 
originally requested that money in February and Congress approved 
early versions of it in March, but the legislation languished until 
lawmakers used it as a way to speed the military money to passage. 
</P>
<P>
	An additional $900 million would replenish the Federal Emergency  
Management Agency's coffers so it can address damage from this 
month's horrific tornadoes in Oklahoma and other natural disasters. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also has $574 million to help American farmers, mainly  
those facing low prices for hogs, wheat and other commodities. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprinkled throughout the bill are projects large and small that  
lawmakers won for home-state interests. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens made sure that $70 million in aid for livestock  
producers would include reindeer. 
</P>
<P>
	House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., and House Majority  
Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, each would be entitled to an additional 
$333,000 a year for office expenses. The Senate could spend $10 
million to bring 3,000 Russian political leaders to the United 
States for a month of observing the U.S. government and economy at 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also contains $6.5 million to monitor elections in East  
Timor, which is deciding whether to break free of Indonesia, and 
$1.5 million to add water to drought-stricken San Carlos Lake on an 
Indian reservation in Arizona. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
