<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Falls on Brazilian Forecasts  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Coffee futures fell sharply Thursday on the Board of Trade of  
the City of New York, ending a four-session rally, after 
forecasters predicted there will be virtually no chance for frost 
in Brazil over the next few days. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, crude edged higher, while palladium futures  
suffered a meltdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee futures had risen explosively in recent days amid belief  
that Brazil may be in for a harsh winter that could freeze blooms 
off coffee trees and sharply reduce the 2000-2001 harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	While forecasters never predicted temperatures would reach  
sustained freezing levels, they previously had said the thermometer 
could drop into the upper 30s over the next few days. The 
unexpectedly cold forecasts before winter officially begins had 
boosted speculation that the world's largest coffee producer this 
year may not escape a damaging freeze, as it has done for the past 
two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Some meteorologists now say, however, that temperatures will  
drop only into the 40s and that they will moderate next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil produces mainly robusta beans, which are not certified  
for delivery against New York futures contracts. But many roasters 
mix those beans with high-quality arabica beans for gourmet blends. 
</P>
<P>
	Arabica coffee for July delivery fell 3 cents to $1.20 a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil futures edged higher on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange as the United Nations became mired in debate over whether 
to approve another round of an oil-for-aid program for Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	Iraq is operating under an embargo imposed after its 1990  
invasion of Kuwait but is allowed to export 1.9 million barrels of 
oil, equal to $5.2 billion, over six months to buy food and medical 
supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	That period ends Monday, however, and the U.N. Security Council  
still is trying to determine how to reinstate weapons inspectors 
who were pulled out of the country after Iraq refused to cooperate 
with the program. Iraq also has not submitted a distribution plan 
for such a sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants said the current wrangling could take weeks,  
effectively keeping oil off the market at a time when other major 
oil producers are cutting back output. The two combined could cause 
prices to jump, although investors were cautious in light of recent 
refiner cutbacks that have limited demand for that reduced output. 
</P>
<P>
	June crude rose 15 cents to $17.03 a barrel.  
</P>
<P>
	Palladium futures prices tumbled on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange amid market talk that Russia, the world's largest 
supplier, was selling heavily onto London markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is the largest single producer of palladium, which is  
used in jewelry, electronics and the automobile industry. 
Large-scale shipments had been halted since December, however, amid 
bureaucratic delays that have taken place for three consecutive 
years at the same time. 
</P>
<P>
	The delays have forced auto manufacturers in particular to  
scramble for available supplies since many use the metal in the 
manufacture of emission-control devices required under clean-air 
laws in a number of countries. 
</P>
<P>
	September palladium fell $7.75 to $328.50 an ounce.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
