<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schilling Criticizes State of MLB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Curt Schilling has plenty of prospective  
employers. It sounds like the commissioner's office is one of them. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling is off to a 7-1 start with a major league-leading four  
complete games. Despite the low-budget Phillies' strong start, he 
is still unhappy in Philadelphia and would welcome a trade to a 
contender. 
</P>
<P>
	He had some other ideas on his mind Wednesday during a national  
conference call in which he ripped his team's ownership, baseball's 
leadership and lamented the state of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first thing I would get done if I were commissioner would  
be to have both sides' bargaining teams at the table to resolve the 
contract beyond 2001,'' Schilling said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would move the Montreal Expos. I would move them to a city I  
knew would support them financially and fan-base wise. I would find 
a spot other than a city where 4,000 people show up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would get rid of interleague play, realign baseball  
geographically,'' he continued. ``I can't get rid of the wild card. 
I hated it when it came in, but I think it's been a good thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oh, and one more thing: ``Get rid of the DH,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Schilling, the reigning NL strikeout leader and the league's  
first to win seven games this season, is just as outspoken off the 
mound as he is intimidating and dominating when standing atop it. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Phillies broke spring training camp with their $30.36  
million payroll -- fourth-lowest in the National League -- Schilling 
announced that he would waive his no-trade clause for a chance to 
play for a contender. 
</P>
<P>
	But a funny thing happened in the first few weeks of the season.  
The surprising Phillies are 21-17, trailing only the Atlanta Braves 
in the NL East. 
</P>
<P>
	After pitching his fourth complete game, more than any other  
TEAM in the majors, Schilling said Monday, ``I feel good about 
what's going on here. We're playing good ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Phillies president David Montgomery denied a  
recent report in Forbes Magazine that the Phillies were one of 16 
teams that made money in 1998. The city is deciding whether to kick 
in an extra $80 million that would be necessary if the Phillies get 
their preferred downtown site for a new stadium that will be 
partially funded by taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their estimate does not come close to accurately representing  
our 1998 results,'' Montgomery said. 
</P>
<P>
	When he won his last start in front of 5,104 fans in Montreal,  
Schilling saw it as another example of how the game he grew up 
adoring isn't the same. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't blame the fans for it, not for a minute,'' Schilling  
said. ``What happens is you have owners who are in the game that 
don't belong anymore, that don't fit in. And to fit in, they're 
asking for new stadiums funded by taxpayers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked how he would realign baseball's divisions, Schilling said,  
``Why wouldn't you want the New York Yankees and the New York Mets 
playing each other 18 times a year? Why wouldn't you want the 
Chicago Cubs and White Sox battling 18 times for a pennant? 
</P>
<P>
	``There are just too many ridiculous things that haven't been  
taken care of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling, 32, has two years left on a three-year contract that  
pays him $15.9 million with an option for 2001 at $6.5 million. 
Behind all this bluster, he is off to one of the best starts of his 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling has a 2.58 ERA, is second in the NL to Randy Johnson  
with 58 strikeouts and is tied with Houston's Jose Lima for the 
league lead in wins. The Phillies are averaging 8.7 runs in his 
seven victories -- five more than they averaged in his 35 starts 
last season. 
</P>
<P>
	He is a junky for big-game adrenaline, an intimidating throwback  
to days when pitchers would take the mound in the first inning and 
keep pitching until the game was over. He would make a mighty fine 
starter for Games 1, 4 and 7 of the World Series for any team lucky 
enough to get him. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I take the ball, I make the day I pitch an event in my  
mind,'' he said. ``Even if it isn't, it is to me. It's a major 
thing to me. I make it a major event in my mind, and I play it up 
for four days in my mind. I prepare myself to play a part in a 
major event.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Come July, when the trade deadline arrives, we'll see whether  
Schilling gets to pitch in a pennant race -- for real, or just in 
his own imagination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
