<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Economy Said To Be Recovering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The global economy is emerging from the  
financial crisis that began in Asia nearly two years ago, a key 
Clinton official said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are still at a delicate stage and we are not yet out of the  
woods,'' said Stuart E. Eizenstat, a State Department official who 
is awaiting Senate confirmation as Deputy Secretary of the 
Treasury. 
</P>
<P>
	Addressing the Committee for Economic Development, a private,  
nonprofit group, Eizenstat said that key stricken countries do 
``show clear signs of rebounding,'' however. 
</P>
<P>
	In Asia, where the crisis began with the devaluation of the Thai  
currency in July 1997 and spread to Japan, currencies have 
stabilized and stock markets are up. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Monetary Fund is predicting 2 percent growth  
for most Asian economies this year, and more than twice that in the 
newly industrialized Asian economies of South Korea, Taiwan, Hong 
Kong and Singapore, Eizenstat said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Brazil, interest rates have declined 18 percentage points  
since March, and Brazilian securities markets have recovered. The 
IMF predicts that positive growth in the second half of the year 
will offset declines in the first. 
</P>
<P>
	And Russia, which defaulted on some debts and devalued its  
currency last August, has taken some positive steps just in the 
past few days, Eizenstat said. 
</P>
<P>
	He praised the efforts earlier this week of acting Prime  
Minister Sergei Stepashin to get legislators to approve economic 
reforms required for a new loan from the International Monetary 
Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	On the domestic front, U.S. bank regulators must more  
aggressively monitor U.S. loans in developing countries, and banks 
must be clearer with regulators about the risks they are taking, 
Eizenstat warned. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, lenders should bear the most risk of such loans,  
Eizenstat said. They can't count on the IMF or any other 
organization to make them whole when the loans go bad. 
</P>
<P>
	Eizenstat, currently Undersecretary of State, was tapped for the  
Treasury post last week to succeed Deputy Secretary Lawrence 
Summers, who was nominated to succeeded departing Treasury 
Secretary Robert Rubin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
