<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Push Rural Internet Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farm-state Senate Democrats asked the Federal  
Communications Commission on Thursday to improve Internet access in 
rural areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC should consider setting a standard for high-speed  
Internet service and using federal subsidies to make sure it is 
available in remote areas, the senators said. Such subsidies come 
from fees imposed on telecommunications companies and typically 
passed on to their customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rural communities need the economic and social benefits that  
high-speed Internet access provides. For some of them, it's a 
matter of basic economic survival,'' Senate Minority Leader Tom 
Daschle, D-S.D., said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a 1996 law, rural areas are supposed to have  
telecommunications services that are ``reasonably comparable'' to 
those in cities, but it was left to the FCC to decide how to do 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	The government already is distributing nearly $1.7 billion in  
subsidies to schools and libraries -- including those in rural areas 
and inner cities -- for a variety of telecommunications needs, 
including Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC Chairman Bill Kennard recently called for $2.25 billion to  
fund the program in its second year. That's generating criticism 
primarily from Republicans on Capitol Hill because of fears that it 
could raise phone bills. 
</P>
<P>
	In their letter, the lawmakers said that farmers, rural  
businesses and small-town health-care facilities need access to 
high-speed Internet services for transmitting graphics and large 
amounts of data. Farmers, for example, often use satellite imaging 
to decide how much fertilizer and pesticide to use in their fields. 
</P>
<P>
	The senators also said the FCC should consider subsidizing  
high-speed Internet and data services via satellite and encourage 
cellular companies to serve remote areas and Indian reservations, 
where there is little phone service. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC officials did not return telephone calls seeking comment on  
the senators' request. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the senators are introducing legislation to create  
an office of rural advocacy at the FCC. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are determined not to end up with a country of haves and  
have-nots with respect to advanced telecommunications,'' said Sen. 
Byron Dorgan, D-N.D. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecommunications companies have been racing each other to  
provide high-speed Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	An alliance of computer makers and big telephone companies,  
including US West, want the FCC to ease regulations that they said 
discourage modernization. Rival long-distance companies, including 
AT&AMP;T, oppose the move. AT&AMP;T, meanwhile, is seeking to become a 
major provider of Internet service over cable TV lines. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter was signed by Daschle, Dorgan and, in alphabetical  
order by state, Iowa's Tom Harkin, Minnesota's Paul Wellstone, 
Montana's Max Baucus, Nebraska's Bob Kerrey, North Dakota's Kent 
Conrad, Oregon's Ron Wyden, South Dakota's Tim Johnson and 
Washington's Patty Murray. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 16:22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Armstrong Is NBA's Most Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Making history was the farthest thing from  
Darrell Armstrong's mind when he launched his comeback from a 
career-threatening shoulder injury. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orlando Magic guard added the NBA's Most Improved Player  
Award to his postseason haul Thursday, making him the first to win 
both that honor and the Sixth Man Award. 
</P>
<P>
	Last summer, Armstrong was in so much pain following rotator  
cuff surgery that he thought the hospital was making a mistake by 
releasing him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was ready to check back in. It was that much pain ... I  
couldn't sleep, I couldn't eat,'' he recalled. ``Things like that, 
it makes you appreciate life. It makes you appreciate basketball, 
and it makes you appreciate anything you do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong averaged career highs of 13.8 points, 6.7 assists, 3.6  
rebounds and 2.16 steals in 30 minutes a game while coming off the 
bench in 35 of 50 games this season. 
</P>
<P>
	He improved on his career averages in scoring by 6.9 points, in  
assists by 3.5 assists, in rebounds by 1.8 and in steals by 1.2. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are very few people in the world of basketball,  
particularly last summer, that worked harder on their game than he 
did, and he continues to work on it,'' Magic general manager John 
Gabriel said. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong received 54 of a possible 118 votes from a national  
panel of sports writers and broadcasters. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighteen players received votes. Eric Snow of Philadelphia was  
second with 15 votes and Gary Trent of Dallas was third with 14 
votes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Most Improved Player Award has been given since the 1985-86  
season. The Sixth Man Award began in the 1983-84 season. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Gastonia, N.C., Armstrong was not drafted in 1991  
after completing his college career at Fayetteville State. He 
played in the Global Basketball Association, the Continental 
Basketball Association, the United States Basketball League and in 
Cyprus and Spain before signing with the Magic on April 8, 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are times in our industry, in all sports industry, where  
evaluators of talent forget some basic principles, like does a guy 
compete each and every night ... competitiveness,'' Gabriel said. 
``We talk about it a lot, but it's probably not on a lot of our 
evaluation sheets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, honored last week as the league's top reserve, didn't  
expect to win both awards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people had me for most improved, some people had me for  
sixth man,'' he said. ``I have both of them sitting here in front 
of me. It's just a blessing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 14:53:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mich. Beating Death Raises Tensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The arrest of two gas station clerks in the  
slaying of a man who was beaten with a tire iron in front of his 
five children has heated up long-simmering tensions between 
Detroit's many Arab-American store owners and their black 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	The black community ``cries out for justice for this family and  
for our community,'' Detroit NAACP President Wendell Anthony said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kalvin Porter, a black 34-year-old electrician, was killed last  
Friday at a gasoline station in a poor neighborhood on the city's 
east side. Investigators said the clerks attacked Porter after he 
argued with them about comments they supposedly made to his 
12-year-old stepdaughter. 
</P>
<P>
	Fadhel Mazeb, 46, and Adel Altam, 26, were jailed without bail  
on murder charges. Both are immigrants from Yemen. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the beating, protests outside the Sunoco station have  
forced it to remain closed, and some blacks have called for a 
boycott of Arab-American businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Arab-Americans first began to dominate the grocery store, liquor  
store and gas station business in Detroit in the late 1960s and 
early 1970s as white business owners fled the city in the wake of 
the 1967 riots. 
</P>
<P>
	Metropolitan Detroit's more than 4 million people include about  
200,000 people of Arab descent, one of the largest Arab populations 
outside the Middle East. The city of Detroit has about 1 million 
people, about 80 percent of them black. 
</P>
<P>
	``The African-American community has too long been the victim of  
mistreatment and disrespect by some who operate and work in stores 
and gas stations in our neighborhood,'' the NAACP's Anthony said in 
a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Anthony said Porter's slaying ``is a tragic example of festering  
problems of ill will and ill feelings between African-Americans and 
some Arab-Chaldean store operators.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday afternoon, the two sides met at a church at a  
gathering sponsored by the civil rights group, Arab store owners 
and other community and religious groups. About 100 people 
attended. 
</P>
<P>
	``This situation was tragic, to say the least,'' Ed Deeb,  
president of the Michigan Food and Beverage Association, which 
represents 3,100 Arab-American merchants in metropolitan Detroit. 
``We feel this is not a racial incident but a crime issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several blacks at the meeting disagreed.  
</P>
<P>
	Ruth Williams said she has seen a pattern of racism by Arab  
store owners against black customers. ``We need to boycott these 
businesses,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's racism involved. There's prejudice involved,'' said  
Mary McClendon. ``An eye for an eye, a tooth for a tooth. It's been 
going on for 400 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ethnic tensions between inner-city residents and store owners  
from immigrant or minority groups are nothing new in America. 
</P>
<P>
	In cities like Los Angeles and Miami, it is between black  
customers and Korean, Vietnamese or Cuban merchants. A generation 
ago, it was Italian and Jewish store owners in black neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	In Cleveland, tensions between Arab-American shopkeepers and  
blacks ran high in the mid-1990s after several inner-city merchants 
were killed and a store clerk was arrested for killing a black 
teen-ager. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1995 study done by the Arab American Institute in Washington  
blamed tensions on a combination of crime, poverty and the presence 
in poor neighborhoods of recent immigrants with successful 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``The crisis is the same in every city. It's a crisis of the  
inner city, not enough employment, not enough hope,'' said James 
Zogby, head of the Arab American Institute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
