<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Telecom Italia Accuses Olivetti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- As Europe's biggest takeover battle nears a  
climax, Telecom Italia on Thursday accused hostile suitor Olivetti 
of rigging its offer and unsuccessfully urged regulators to suspend 
the bidding. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations came as Olivetti appeared poised to meet its  
goal for pressing ahead with its upstart bid for the former 
state-owned phone monopoly that is five times it size. Olivetti's 
$65 billion offer expires Friday, and analysts said most 
shareholders would wait until then to decide whether to accept it. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti, with interests in cellular phones, office equipment  
and communications technology, has said it needs at least 35 
percent of Telecom's ordinary shares to proceed with the takeover. 
As of Thursday it had just under 20 percent of Telecom's shares. It 
hopes to win 67 percent, enough to give it a controlling interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti's bold offer, which has convulsed the clubby world of  
Europe's former government-run phone companies, appears to be 
gaining support even as Telecom Italia's proposed defensive merger 
with Deutsche Telekom seems increasingly remote. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom and its German counterpart announced their plans for a  
friendly merger in April, but the deal has encountered resistance 
from the Italian government and skepticism from investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom accused Olivetti of leaking false information about the  
number of shares already tendered by Telecom shareholders and 
threatened legal action. It also asked Italy's stock market 
regulating agency to suspend the bidding, but was turned down. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom's move underscored the importance of public perception  
in determining the outcome of the struggle. As more people are seen 
to be tendering their shares to Olivetti, the offer gains popular 
acceptance and other shareholders may decide to follow suit. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Italian news agency Radiocor quoted an adviser  
to Olivetti chief executive Roberto Colaninno as saying Olivetti 
had already won more than 35 percent of Telecom's shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy's market regulator, Consob, warned Olivetti afterward to  
``abstain from spreading information about the bid which is not 
backed up by hard data, isn't verifiable, and is only based on the 
calculations of analysts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom's chief Franco Bernabe accused Olivetti officials of  
acting ``without any respect for authority or rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti denied releasing any such information. Calls seeking  
further comment were not immediately returned Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, some industry analysts said Thursday that they expected  
Olivetti to achieve its minimum targeted number of shares. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the consensus is that they're likely to get 35  
percent. Whether they'll get as much as 50 percent is difficult to 
tell,'' said Denis Gross of Williams De Broe, a London brokerage. 
</P>
<P>
	Gross noted rumors that Olivetti had already amassed more than  
42 percent of Telecom shares. However, the outcome was still 
unclear because many large shareholders were ``fence-sitting'' 
until Friday, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernabe made a last attempt to reassure investors on Wednesday,  
emphasizing his plan to spread Telecom's wealth by buying back 10 
percent of the company's shares at a premium to the price offered 
by Olivetti. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts, speaking on condition of anonymity, said they  
were not persuaded by Bernabe's pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernabe also tried to play down the effectiveness of Olivetti's  
offer, saying that Italian fund managers told him they were 
relinquishing no more than half of their Telecom shares to 
Olivetti, the Italian daily Corriere della Sera reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	A Telecom official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said  
this meant that Italian fund managers were giving up no more than 7 
percent of the total number of company shares. 
</P>
<P>
	If Olivetti garners more than 35 percent but fewer than 50  
percent of Telecom's shares, the outlook becomes cloudier still. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom officials say that under company bylaws, unless Olivetti  
gets at least half of Telecom's shares, it won't be able to control 
more than 3 percent of the voting stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti disputes this interpretation of Italian law, making a  
court battle a near certainty under this outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom ended trading Thursday in Milan down 2 percent at the  
equivalent of $10.32 a share, while Olivetti shares lost 2 percent 
to close at $3.51. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
