<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	6 Georgia High School Students Shot  
</P>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- A student with two guns opened fire at his  
high school today, shooting six schoolmates exactly one month after 
the Colorado massacre, authorities said. A suspect was quickly 
taken into custody. None of the injuries was believed to be 
life-threatening. The suspect was described as a 15-year-old 
sophomore at Heritage High School who according to a friend had 
recently broken up with his girlfriend. The gunman had two weapons, 
a .22-caliber rifle and a .22-caliber revolver, District Attorney 
Richard Read said. The shootings happened about 7:55 a.m., or about 
20 minutes before classes were to begin in this middle-class suburb 
20 miles east of Atlanta. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate OKs Gun-Show Restrictions  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With Vice President Al Gore casting a  
tie-breaking vote, the Senate today approved a Democratic proposal 
to slap fresh restrictions on gun transactions at gun shows and 
pawn shops. The proposal, which would require mandatory background 
checks for all transactions at gun shows, was tied, 50-50. Gore, 
who had come to the Capitol in case his vote was needed to break a 
tie, did so in favor of the Democratic provision. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Missile Hits Hospital  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO jets pounded Belgrade and its  
suburbs today, hitting a hospital and killing at least three 
people. The residences of the Spanish and Swedish ambassadors were 
also damaged. The bombings, the strongest in Belgrade since the 
Chinese Embassy was mistakenly hit May 7, came on the same day that 
diplomatic efforts intensified and thousands turned out to pray for 
peace in Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	G-8 Talks End Without Kosovo Action  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Negotiators from Russia and the Western  
nations met for nearly 12 hours today to discuss Kosovo, but broke 
up without agreeing on key elements of a joint peace plan. Foreign 
ministers from the Group of Eight nations drafted a seven-page 
working text of a resolution, but many parts of it were left open 
for further negotiation. The group will resume talks tomorrow. In 
Albania today, U.N. chief Kofi Annan called for the United Nations 
to play a key role in resolving the Kosovo conflict. 

</P>
<P>
	Gen. Shelton Renamed to Top Post  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton nominated Army Gen. Henry H.  
Shelton to serve a second two-year term as chairman of the Joint 
Chiefs of Staff, the nation's top military position. In a Rose 
Garden announcement today with Shelton in uniform at his side, 
Clinton praised the four-star general as ``critical to our efforts 
in Kosovo and indeed to our entire national security program.'' As 
chairman of the Joint Chiefs, Shelton is the senior military 
adviser to the president and to the secretary of defense. 

</P>
<P>
	German Court Convicts Ex-Nazi Agent  
</P>
<P>
	STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- Ending what could be Germany's last  
major war crimes trial, a court has convicted a 79-year-old former 
Nazi of assisting in the murders of 17,000 Jews at a concentration 
camp in Poland. The court sentenced Alfons Goetzfrid to 10 years in 
prison, but gave him credit for time served on similar charges in 
the Soviet Union. He will not be jailed in Germany. The conviction 
comes as Nazi hunters around the world race to press charges 
against suspected war criminals before they become too old or 
feeble to stand trial. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Prime Minister Begins New Job  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's prime minister slid confidently into his  
new job today, rebuking former Cabinet members for ``running around 
like scalded cats'' instead of soberly repairing the economy. 
Sergei Stepashin, easily approved as prime minister yesterday, has 
no economic background and has said little about his own plans for 
Russia's finances. Today, he proposed increased defense spending 
and ordered the government to submit next year's budget by August. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 30 to 10,917  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was up 30.08 to 10,917.47. Advancers lead decliners on the 
NYSE 1,771 to 1,077. The Nasdaq Composite Index was up 4.97 to 
2,582.37. 

</P>
<P>
	Armstrong Is NBA's Most Improved  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Guard Darrell Armstrong of the Orlando Magic  
today won the NBA's Most Improved Player Award, making him the 
first to win both that honor and the Sixth Man Award. Armstrong 
received 54 of a possible 118 votes from a national panel of sports 
writers and broadcasters. Eric Snow of Philadelphia was second with 
15 votes, and Gary Trent of Dallas was third with 14 votes. 
Armstrong averaged career highs of 13.8 points, 6.7 rebounds and 
2.16 steals in 30 minutes a game while coming off the bench in 35 
of 50 games. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  
</P>
