<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gateway To Build Low-Cost Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Computer maker Gateway Inc. will  
continue to turn its focus to high-profit services such as 
financing, Internet service and computer training, Chief Executive 
Officer Ted Waitt told shareholders at the company's annual meeting 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The North Sioux City, S.D.-based company also plans to introduce  
more low-cost computers, which represent the fastest growing 
segment of the personal computer market, Waitt said. ``The days of 
everyone buying a $2,500 PC are over,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gateway currently sells a $999 personal computer, but Waitt  
declined to say how much lower the company would go in the next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now to say we'll be at $499, or $599, or $399, we're  
still working that out,'' he told reporters after the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Services and software account for 8 percent of the company's  
revenues today, Waitt said at the meeting. That could rise to 20 
percent in the future, he said, and added that since those 
businesses carry lower overhead, the portion of profit they bring 
would be even greater. 
</P>
<P>
	Financing packages offered with personal computers totaled $1  
billion last year and next year should top $2 billion, said Jeff 
Weitzen, president and chief operating officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will also focus more on small businesses, currently  
the fastest-growing segment of Gateway's market, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gateway will also increase its efforts to sell to schools, and  
will expand its line of servers, computers that send information 
over the Internet, Weitzen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Home computers remain the company's mainstay, and will still be  
heavily targeted, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time, shareholders could watch the meeting live on  
the Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
