<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wineries Make Comeback in Kentucky / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIDWAY, Ky. (AP) -- Grape-growing and wineries are making a  
comeback in central Kentucky, where the industry flourished for 
years before it was uprooted by Prohibition. 
</P>
<P>
	There are now six licensed wineries, and tobacco farmers looking  
for alternative crops are showing more interest in grapes. 
</P>
<P>
	Cynthia Bohn, a full-time IBM employee who grew up on a tobacco  
farm near Elizabethtown, said she hopes Equus Run Vineyards -- a 
``boutique winery'' -- will become a tourist destination along with 
the horse farms. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Chris and Denise Nelson of Nicholasville, the owners of  
Chrisman Mill Vineyards in Jessamine County, are looking to make 
their operation the seventh licensed commercial winery in Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	They want to pick up the horticulture begun by Swiss/French  
settler Jean Jacques Dufour, who planted a vineyard in Jessamine 
County 200 years ago and who organized the Kentucky Vineyard 
Society. 
</P>
<P>
	``Actually, in the late 1800s, Kentucky was the third-largest  
grape and wine producer in the United States,'' said Chris Nelson, 
president of the Kentucky Vineyard Society, resurrected in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jessamine and Woodford county vineyards will harvest their  
first light crops in September. Equus Run near Midway has a tasting 
room for customers to sample wines. 
</P>
<P>
	The wines were made from grapes grown in California and Indiana,  
where the Woodford winery's product is made until it can get its 
own winery equipment installed in a former tobacco barn this 
summer. 
</P>
<P>
	An acre of wine grapes can yield gross income of $6,000 to  
$11,000, Bohn said. Tobacco ranges from $4,000 to $5,000 an acre. 
</P>
<P>
	State viticulturist Garth Vinson of Murray State University, who  
advises growers, recommends grapes as a companion crop to tobacco, 
rather than a replacement. Vinson said the peak labor times for 
each crop don't overlap. 
</P>
<P>
	``The two work well hand in hand,'' Vinson said.  
</P>
<P>
	The industry is still in its infancy. There were only 250 acres  
of grapes planted in the state last year, according to the Kentucky 
Horticulture Council, and they produced $798,000 in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	But interest is growing because the state offers incentives,  
such as matching grants to help those planting vineyards. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new variety of wheat developed by government  
scientists will slow the spread of a fungus that has plagued 
farmers in the upper Midwest over the past decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers lost an estimated $2.6 billion between 1991 and 1997  
because of scab, or Fusarium head blight, that shrivels kernels of 
wheat and barley. The disease also produces toxins that can make 
the grain unsuitable for food and animal feed. 
</P>
<P>
	``This new wheat variety, our most scab-tolerant ever, will be  
available to farmers for the spring 2000 planting season, 
preventing more damage by this costly disease,'' Agriculture 
Secretary Dan Glickman said this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The new variety, McVey hard red spring wheat, slows the spread  
of the disease in the seedhead so fewer kernels are destroyed. The 
Agriculture Department last year accelerated its research on the 
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The new variety is named for Donald McVey, a plant pathologist  
at the USDA's Cereal Disease Laboratory in St. Paul, Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	The Minnesota Crop Improvement Association, based in St. Paul,  
is distributing seed to certified seed growers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 05:43:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel OKs D.C. Scholarships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- District of Columbia residents would be able  
to attend public colleges or universities nationwide and pay the 
cheaper tuition charged to state residents under a bill that a 
House committee approved Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure, approved by the House Government Reform Committee  
by voice vote and without debate, advanced to the full House for 
consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar legislation is pending in the Senate, but it would limit  
attendance to state-supported colleges and universities in Maryland 
and Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters on the House committee said the bill would improve  
educational opportunities for residents of the city, which has just 
one publicly funded institution of higher education, the University 
of the District of Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're going to bring this city back, we've got to make sure  
kids in this city have the same opportunities for higher education 
that they have everywhere else,'' said Rep. Thomas Davis, R-Va., a 
sponsor of the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The House bill would create a program, to be run by the District  
of Columbia mayor, that would award scholarships to residents to 
attend college at lower rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Public colleges and universities require students who are not  
residents of the state that funds them to pay higher tuition fees 
than those who live there. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton's fiscal 2000 budget requests $17 million for  
higher education in the city, including the new program, said Del. 
Eleanor Holmes Norton, the city's nonvoting representative in the 
House and co-sponsor of the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	She predicted the program would encourage residents to remain in  
the city instead of moving out so they can spend less to send their 
children to college. 
</P>
<P>
	``The incentive to leave (Washington) just to get your kid an  
education you can afford is very great,'' said Norton, a Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, the bill would designate the University of the  
District of Columbia as a historically black college, making it 
eligible for federal funding set aside for those schools. A $15 
billion emergency spending bill nearing completion in Congress 
includes $1.5 million in such funding for the university. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
