<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A nephew of Pablo Escobar, the late  
Medellin cocaine cartel boss, was shot to death in a health club 
Thursday by five gunmen. 
</P>
<P>
	Jorge Roberto Escobar, a 20-year-old computer student, was  
killed in the gym where he exercised every morning in the upscale 
El Poblado neighborhood of Medellin, Colombia's second largest 
city, said Gen. Alfredo Salgado, operations director for the 
National Police. 
</P>
<P>
	The killers fled in a car, police said.  
</P>
<P>
	Salgado said there was no clear motive for the killing of  
Escobar, whose uncle was boss one of Colombia's most feared 
criminal mafias and died in a December 1993 gunfight with police. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- A Sao Paulo court Wednesday convicted  
two former police officers for their involvement in the torture, 
extortion and shooting of slum residents at a roadblock two years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack -- captured on videotape in March 1997 -- involved 10  
policemen. They were seen on the video beating a man on the feet 
and back with nightsticks for three minutes before letting him and 
two others return to their car. As the car pulled away, a policeman 
fired a shot that killed one of the passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson Soares da Silva was sentenced to 13 years in jail for  
attempted murder and abuse of power. Jose dos Santos, who has been 
under arrest for eight months, had his sentence increased by 
another 10 days for abuse of power. 
</P>
<P>
	The policeman seen firing the shot on the video, Otavio Lourenco  
Gambra, is awaiting a new trial after a court threw out an October 
verdict sentencing him to 59 years in prison for one count murder 
and three counts attempted murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Six officers involved in the case received jail terms of up to  
six years, but have been released because they completed one sixth 
of their sentence. One officer was found not guilty. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- Torrential rains washed out highways  
and bridges in northern Nicaragua, where infrastructure is still 
being rebuilt from Hurricane Mitch in November. 
</P>
<P>
	A temporary bridge built to replace one destroyed by the  
hurricane was washed out in the Wednesday storm, cutting traffic in 
the province of Nuevo Segovia. 
</P>
<P>
	The provincial capital of Ocotal, 12 miles south of the border  
with Honduras, was cut off from land links with the rest of the 
country by the storm. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of Nicaragua's highway system is still undergoing repair  
from the damage caused by Hurricane Mitch, which killed more than 
9,000 people in Central America, left 2 million homeless and caused 
damage estimated at $10 billion in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- Honduras has sent an official  
delegation to neighboring El Salvador to bring back about 100 
children who left their flood-damaged Honduran town to beg on the 
streets of San Salvador. 
</P>
<P>
	Honduras dispatched a government bus Wednesday to bring the kids  
back, the federal prosecutor's office said in a press statement. 
The children, most between the ages of six and 12, left the town of 
Marcovia, on the Salvadoran border, after Hurricane Mitch 
devastated the area in October. 
</P>
<P>
	The children are expected to be returned to Honduras Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Mitch hit Honduras in late October and early November,  
killing more than 5,000 people and causing heavy damage to 
Marcovia, 90 miles south of the capital, Tegucigalpa. El Salvador 
suffered less damage in the hurricane. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela's largest union said  
Thursday that the jobless rate has jumped by four percentage points 
this year, leaving 20 percent of workers unemployed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Confederation of Venezuelan Workers blamed low prices for  
oil, the country's main export, for the jump. It said hundreds of 
thousands of workers have been laid off since January in the 
construction, manufacturing, petroleum, agricultural and banking 
sectors, among others. 
</P>
<P>
	The government estimates unemployment at 15 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	Prices for Venezuelan oil hit a 12-year low last year and  
provoked one of the country's worst recessions in years. However, 
prices have rebounded in recent weeks, prompting hopes that the 
economy may rebound later this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
