<DOCNO> APW19990520.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 17:49:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indy Boss Makes a U-Turn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Death is something nobody in auto racing likes to discuss.  
</P>
<P>
	Tony George is no exception. But the Indianapolis Motor Speedway  
boss learned an important lesson the hard way: Ignoring the subject 
won't make it go away. 
</P>
<P>
	He was so unhappy with Sports Illustrated's story on the death  
of three spectators at an Indy Racing League event May 1, that he 
barred writer Ed Hinton from covering next weekend's Indy 500. 
</P>
<P>
	But after one newspaper said it would boycott the race and  
several others considered doing so, George made a U-turn -- 
reluctantly. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not right to allow Ed Hinton to have a forum and take  
away what's really important with this event. And that's for the 
media to cover the event and not some sideshow,'' George said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He should know, because the Indy 500 has looked more and more  
like a sideshow the past three years, ever since George chased away 
drivers and owners from the Championship Auto Racing Teams circuit 
and brought in replacements under the IRL banner. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was fooled. Today, the circuit George founded and funded  
with his family fortune is struggling for attention in a congested 
sport. So is CART. The popularity of NASCAR, meanwhile, has zoomed. 
Stock-car racing has reached the point, in terms of TV ratings and 
live audience, where the Indy-car rivals are fighting over fumes. 
</P>
<P>
	When George picked up the May 10 issue of SI and read Hinton's  
article, headlined ``Fatal Attractions,'' he was ready to fight 
about something else. 
</P>
<P>
	Hinton recounted how three spectators were killed, a 9-year-old  
girl critically injured, and eight other fans hurt when a three-car 
collision during the VisionAire 500 sent debris hurtling over a 
15-foot fence at Lowe's Motor Speedway in Concord, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	His article also mentioned a similar accident at a CART race in  
Michigan last July that claimed three lives and injured six. It was 
accompanied by an Associated Press photograph showing two 
sheet-covered bodies on bloody grandstand steps. 
</P>
<P>
	Hinton suggested that ``at the very least,'' racetrack officials  
consider raising the catch fences in front of the grandstands to 25 
feet. But, he concluded, ``The surest solution is simple but 
unlikely to happen: The IRL and CART should stop racing open-wheel 
cars on high-speed oval tracks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since the IRL races exclusively on ovals, Hinton might as well  
have suggested George and his IRL friends back their race cars into 
garages, pull down the doors and throw away the keys. Small wonder 
that George referred to Hinton twice as ``dangerous'' during 
Thursday's news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked to elaborate, he said, ``I'm not preventing him from  
writing, and I'm sure there will be worse stuff to come as a result 
of this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	George can't have it both ways.  
</P>
<P>
	The sad truth is that death -- of drivers, mechanics and  
spectators -- has been part of racing since the Indy 500 first came 
on the scene in 1911. It's also true that George has added some 
lucrative events to the speedway calendar, but he's also taken some 
of the luster off what used to be ``The Greatest Spectacle in 
Racing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	People have slammed it before.  
</P>
<P>
	Jim Murray, the late Pulitzer Prize-winning columnist of The Los  
Angeles Times, was so upset by the death of a friend, driver Eddie 
Sachs, in the 1964 race that he penned one of the best-known lines 
in sports writing -- ``Gentlemen, start your coffins!'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 500 not only survived that sting, it continued to thrive.  
Back then, the race owned Memorial Day weekend and no other sport 
dared scheduled an event near it. Back then, it seemed that Indy, 
like the Super Bowl, Kentucky Derby, Wimbledon and Masters, was one 
of those events that would forever own the pinnacle of its sport. 
</P>
<P>
	But a funny thing happened while George and CART feuded.  
NASCAR's crown jewel, the Daytona 500, supplanted the Indy 500 at 
the top. 
</P>
<P>
	There was, however, one promising development on the racing  
front Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine-year-old Haley McGee, who suffered bruises to the brain and  
lungs in the May 1 crash, has already begun her comeback. She's 
undergoing daily physical and speech therapy. 
</P>
<P>
	She's doing fine.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
