<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin Pop Star Making Big Splash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The first all-English album by Puerto Rican  
heartthrob Ricky Martin was No. 1 in its debut on the nation's pop 
music charts. 
</P>
<P>
	By selling 661,000 copies, the ``Ricky Martin'' album became the  
best-ever album debut by a Hispanic artist on the mainstream 
Billboard charts. It was released May 11. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not for a very long time have we seen a new artist with the  
star power of Ricky Martin. We played his video and the next day it 
was among the most requested,'' MTV programming chief Tom Calderone 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The album's first single, ``Livin' La Vida Loca,'' is also the  
top pop and Latin music single. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 07:12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Confident in Federal Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The Justice Department will have to prove that  
American Airlines' fight against low-cost competition was more than 
just business, chairman Donald J. Carty says. 
</P>
<P>
	In a federal civil lawsuit filed last week in Wichita, Kan., the  
government accused American of monopolizing and attempting to 
monopolize passenger service to and from Dallas-Fort Worth 
International Airport, the nation's third largest airport. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department alleged that Fort Worth-based American,  
the nation's second largest carrier, cut fares and added flights 
temporarily to drive low-cost competitors out of its giant hub 
airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Carty said Wednesday after the annual shareholders meeting of  
American parent AMR Corp. that the company was confident it abided 
by antitrust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``What Justice has to do is go in and somehow argue that past  
precedent and past court cases somehow don't apply to the airline 
industry,'' Carty said. ``I think that's a very tough thing for 
them to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	American was charged with repeatedly trying to drive small,  
startup airlines out of the DFW airport by saturating their routes 
with additional flights and cutting fares. After the competitors 
withdrew or drastically reduced their service, American 
re-established high fares and reduced its service, the government 
alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	Carty said that new airlines don't require federal protection if  
they are ``properly capitalized'' in a way ``consistent with the 
capital required to compete in this or any other industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his remarks, Carty said that the airline was ``very  
comfortable'' with its stand that American had complied with the 
law ``as it is written and as it has been interpreted in the 
past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is the first predatory pricing case brought in the industry  
since airline deregulation in 1978. At that time, major carriers 
established hubs to concentrate their traffic through one or more 
airports. 
</P>
<P>
	While hubs provide some conveniences for passengers, hub  
carriers frequently charge higher fares on hub routes with little 
competition. Low-cost carriers often can provide competitive 
alternatives to the hub carrier, generally offering fare cuts of 50 
percent or more. A 1996 study by the Department of Transportation 
estimated that low-cost carriers were saving consumers $6.3 billion 
a year. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to targeting Vanguard's routes to Wichita, Kan., and  
Kansas City, Mo., American's actions were aimed at Sun Jet's routes 
to Long Beach, Calif., and Western Pacific's to Colorado Springs, 
Colo., the lawsuit said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
