<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	6 Wounded in Ga. School Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- Exactly one month after the bloodbath in a  
Colorado high school, a 15-year-old sophomore, armed with two guns, 
opened fire this morning at suburban Atlanta's Heritage High 
School. The boy, upset over a broken romance, shot and wounded six 
students. Witnesses said the gunman was running and shooting at no 
one in particular and firing at students below the waist so as not 
to kill them. Authorities did not identify the suspect or suggest a 
motive. He was charged as a juvenile with aggravated assault, and 
more charges may be pending. 

</P>
<P>
	Stiffer Gun Restrictions Approved  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Propelled by a shocking outbreak of school  
violence, the Senate passed legislation tonight to require the sale 
of safety devices with handguns and expand a system of background 
checks for firearms purchasers. The vote was 73-25, and came a few 
hours after Vice President Al Gore eagerly broke a 50-50 tie in 
favor of a politically popular gun control amendment that most 
Republicans opposed. Passage sent the measure to the House, where 
there appears to be support for the legislation. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Talks to Littleton Families  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- On a day of more school bloodshed,  
President Clinton consoled grief-stricken families in the town 
where a murder-suicide rampage by two teen-agers a month ago left 
15 dead and shocked the nation. ``What happened to you has pierced 
the soul of America,'' the president said. Nearly 2,000 people 
packed Dakota Ridge High School gymnasium to hear the president. In 
remarks later at the high school, Hillary Rodham Clinton said she 
was impressed by the community's strength and ``your refusal to let 
violence and hatred win.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Belgrade, Hospital Hit by NATO  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO jets hit Belgrade harder  
Thursday than they have since the Chinese embassy was mistakenly 
bombed by NATO on May 7. Today's attacks left a hospital in 
smoldering ruins, three patients dead and eight foreign diplomatic 
missions damaged. One attack hit a fuel depot in a busy capital 
street, damaging the nearby home of the Swiss ambassador, who was 
hosting a diplomatic reception at the time, the private Beta news 
agency said. There were no reports of injury. 

</P>
<P>
	All Saved on Sunken Cruise  
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- A cruise ship caught fire and sank  
off the western coast of Malaysia early Friday but the more than 
1,100 passengers have been accounted for, authorities said. The 
passengers were rescued from the Bahamian-registered Sun Vista, 
said a spokesman for the Marine Rescue and Coordination Center in 
Port Klang. 

</P>
<P>
	Auction House Pulls Malcolm X Diary  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A bloodied diary of Malcolm X was taken off  
the auction block today after the family of the slain civil rights 
leader charged it had been stolen and threatened to sue to halt the 
sale. An auction house said it will hold on to the diary until 
attorneys for the city of New York or the person who consigned the 
book direct them to send it elsewhere. The red, 146-page diary, 
pierced by three bullet holes, was found in the left breast pocket 
of the suit Malcolm X was wearing when he was assassinated Feb. 21, 
1965, in New York. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft May Unseal Documents  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Microsoft said today it would make it  
easier for news organizations to get confidential documents filed 
in a lawsuit accusing the company of predatory business practices. 
Three newspapers today asked a federal judge to unseal some 90 
documents. Instead, Microsoft agreed to provide a list specific 
enough for news organization to decide which documents they want to 
see. 

</P>
<P>
	eToys' Stock Soars in IPO  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Shares of eToys more than quadrupled on their  
first day of trading today after the Internet toy merchant raised 
$166 million in a much-anticipated initial public offering. The new 
stock was priced at $20 a share, but soared as high as $85 on the 
Nasdaq. Founded in 1997, eToys has quickly become the leading toy 
retailer on the Internet. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks were mixed in early trading Friday.  
The Nikkei Stock Average slipped 47.29 points to 16,152.70. On 
Thursday, the average closed up 71.81 points. On Wall Street 
Thursday, the Dow fell 20.65 to close at 10,866.74. 

</P>
<P>
	Knicks Beat Hawks  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Latrell Sprewell scored 31 points for the second  
game in a row as the New York Knicks grabbed command of their 
second-round series with Atlanta, beating the Hawks 77-70 tonight 
for a 2-0 lead in the best-of-7 matchup. After winning both games 
at the Georgia Dome, the Knicks put themselves in position to wrap 
up the series at Madison Square Garden. Game 3 is Sunday afternoon 
in New York, with Game 4 the following night. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
</TEXT>
