<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Down; Dow Off 20.65 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned lower in late trading today as  
lingering concerns about leading technology companies sapped the 
market's modest gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average was down 20.65 at 10,866.74.  
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators, particularly the technology-dominated  
Nasdaq composite index, were lower. It was down 34.98 at 2,542.42. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 5.40 to 1,338.83.  
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-5 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, with 1,750 up, 1,219 down and 578 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 774.00 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.  
767.74 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 0.12 to 639.42. The American Stock  
Exchange composite index eked out the only gain, rising 3.67 to 
792.03. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.89 to 448.03.  
</P>
<P>
	For several days, stocks have traded in a narrow band as  
investors struggled to determine whether a recent rise in inflation 
will prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates in an 
effort to slow the runaway economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the Philadelphia Federal Reserve offered fresh evidence  
of steady but not inflationary economic growth. The group reported 
that manufacturing growth eased slightly in April, which calmed an 
anxious market and set the stage for some mild, broad-based gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan maintained that sense of calm with a  
morning address to the House Banking Committee. The influential 
policymaker focused solely on the global economy. 
</P>
<P>
	By late afternoon, traders had grown comfortable enough with  
U.S. economic policy to cast their eyes back toward corporate 
America. Dell Computer, which disappointed analysts earlier this 
week with a profit report that merely matched expectations, sank in 
late trading, depressing the Nasdaq and dragging many technology 
stocks with it. 
</P>
<P>
	Major Internet businesses also tumbled today. Amazon.com dropped  
3 7/8 to 135 11/16 after the company said it plans to sell $2 billion 
in stocks and bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Mergers set the stage for some gains today. Healtheon soared for  
a second straight session as it announced it will merge with WebMD 
Inc. to create an Internet-based health care services company. 
</P>
<P>
	In other corporate news, Merck was among the Dow's biggest  
advancers as it nears approval for a new painkiller. 
</P>
<P>
	Paper and forest products stocks including Georgia-Pacific rose  
after Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised earnings estimates for the 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	And there was plenty of room for at least one successful new  
issue. EToys soared in its Nasdaq debut. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 12:42:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ABC Extends Indy 500 Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Howard Katz made keeping the Indianapolis  
500 on ABC Sports his No. 1 priority when he became president of 
that department eight weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Katz joined Dick Glover, executive vice president of programming  
for ESPN, and Tony George, president of the Indianapolis Motor 
Speedway and founder of the Indy Racing League, in announcing 
Thursday a five-year extension of the contract that would have 
expired after ABC's 35th consecutive Indy 500 May 30. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were two major reasons why this was my No. 1 priority,''  
Katz said. ``No. 1, the Indy 500 is an American institution. There 
are only certain sports events that rise above everything, and the 
Indy 500 is one of those. 
</P>
<P>
	``Second, this is the 35th year that ABC has had this event.  
There's a tradition here. I think it's far worse to lose something 
you've had than to not have something. And I'm trying to turn this 
department around, emotionally as well as strategically. It was 
important to make this happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No dollar amounts were revealed for the extension through 2004,  
but TV sources, who asked not to be identified, said published 
reports of $13 million to $14 million per year were accurate. The 
previous contract paid the speedway was between $9 million and $10 
million per year. 
</P>
<P>
	Katz said ABC will continue to broadcast the 500 and also will  
air five other IRL events in 2000, with ESPN broadcasting the other 
five races on the schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, ABC showed the IRL season-opener at Orlando, Fla.,  
but the Fox Networks are doing the rest of the schedule, excluding 
Indy. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to the arrival of Katz, ABC was reluctant to bid on  
extending the contract because ratings have slipped 35 percent in 
the three years since the IRL was formed and the established CART 
series began boycotting the race. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, the last year the CART teams and drivers were here, the  
rating was 8.4. Last May, it slipped to 5.5. 
</P>
<P>
	``Special credit needs to be given to Howard Katz, who made this  
agreement his personal priority,'' George said. ``Without Howard's 
enthusiasm and commitment, we would not be here making this 
announcement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a lot invested here,'' Katz said. ``We've made a  
commitment and we're going to get it done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, both the IRL and CART have drawn minuscule TV ratings  
since the split. But Katz said that just means there's work to be 
done. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you've got to build stars,'' he said. ``You've got to  
have a reason to root for or even against people. If you look at 
it, a lot of big names have retired from open-wheel racing in 
recent years. And there's been a general deterioration of TV 
ratings in a lot of platforms, with a greater fragmentation of 
audiences and more things to do, more things to watch. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we're hoping we can do things that will create excitement  
and interest and grow this audience. We think it can be done or we 
wouldn't be here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glover, whose cable network has the contract with CART -- which  
runs through 2001 -- said, ``The Indy Racing League rounds out the 
best motorsports lineup on television. ABC and ESPN provide the 
best cross-promotional platform in sports ...' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 14:53:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Trade Group Pulls Ad Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A gun industry trade group dropped a fledgling  
magazine advertising campaign aimed at changing perceptions about 
firearms soon after last month's Colorado high school slayings. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Shooting Sports Foundation had launched the  
campaign in late March with plans to spend $1 million a year 
running it for three years. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign was aimed at letting opinion leaders know that  
millions of Americans use rifles and guns responsibly for hunting 
and target shooting despite widespread associations of guns with 
crimes and violence. 
</P>
<P>
	But the foundation's executive director, Doug Painter, said  
Thursday the campaign was pulled a few days after the April 20 
shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., left 15 
people dead. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a difficult decision, but we felt that after Littleton,  
the messages in these ads might not be as appropriate, might not be 
as relevant in the context of this moment,'' he said. ``There is so 
much emotion surrounding this issue, we felt our message would be 
lost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Painter said foundation officials also didn't want to offend  
readers. ``There was an understandably emotional reaction against 
everything that has to do with firearms,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, authorities said a student at a school in Georgia  
shot six classmates before surrendering. In Washington, the Senate 
approved fresh restrictions on firearms sales at gun shows and 
pawnshops. 
</P>
<P>
	Clive Chajet, who heads his own corporate image consultancy in  
New York, said the gun industry group had no alternative to ending 
the ads. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anybody who attempts to promote the use of guns at this point  
in history is, pun intended, shooting themselves in the foot,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting sports foundation, based in Newtown, Conn.,  
represents 16,000 manufacturers, distributors and retailers of 
firearms and ammunition. It had never before advertised in 
magazines outside those intended for sportsmen and hunters. 
</P>
<P>
	But the industry has been under attack in recent years and  
several municipalities have sued gun makers over the public costs 
of violence caused by people using guns. 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation hired the public relations firm Porter Novelli,  
which has represented antitobacco forces in a similar campaign 
against cigarette makers, in August 1998 to develop a campaign to 
get out its message about the safety and popularity of hunting and 
target shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	Painter said Porter Novelli's research indicated ``opinion  
leaders in this country were not so much against the shooting 
sports but were not aware of them. That was a side of the story 
they didn't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The firm prepared three ads. One showed a rifle below the  
headline ``The very fact that it can be dangerous is what makes it 
safe.'' The ad called the shooting sports ``the safest of all 
sports. 
</P>
<P>
	Another ad showed a handgun and a target. ``Ever shoot a wad of  
paper into a wastebasket? Then you already understand target 
shooting,'' the ad headline said. It noted there are 21 Olympic 
shooting events. 
</P>
<P>
	The ads were slated to appear in magazines like the Atlantic  
Monthly, The Economist and the Columbia Journalism Review. 
</P>
<P>
	Painter said he didn't know how much of the first year's $1  
million media budget was spent before the ads were discontinued. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it was too soon to tell whether the ad campaign would  
ever be revived. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Rifle Association, an organization of gun owners,  
has been running a campaign for more than a year featuring 
celebrity NRA members like author Tom Clancy, former baseball star 
Nolan Ryan and actor Tom Selleck. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the group, Bill Powers, declined to say whether  
the NRA had adjusted its ad plans in the wake of the Colorado 
shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an ongoing periodic campaign. It doesn't have anything to  
do with'' the shooting in Colorado, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 08:43:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Deficit Hits Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's trade deficit soared to a record  
high for the third straight month in March as the politically 
sensitive deficit with Japan shot up to the highest level in more 
than four years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department said today that the March deficit of  
$19.7 billion was 2.9 percent higher than the previous record of 
$19.1 billion in February. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, the U.S. trade deficit is running at an annual  
rate of $222.6 billion, nearly one-third higher than the all-time 
high of $169.3 billion set last year as the global financial crisis 
continues to wreck havoc with America's trade performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``The trade data released today confirm the continuing strength  
of the American economy. These data also show the continuing 
weakness of much of the rest of the world,'' said Commerce 
Secretary William M. Daley. ``To improve our trade balance, we will 
have to continue to focust on improving economic conditions abroad 
and ensuring that foreign markets are open to American firms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were some glimmers of hope in the March report. U.S.  
exports, which had fallen for four straight months, staged a small 
rebound in March, climbing by 0.9 percent to $77.5 billion as 
exports of farm goods were up 2.5 percent, led by rising sales of 
soybeans and corn. 
</P>
<P>
	But strong consumer demand in the United States caused imports  
to rise even faster, climbing 1.3 percent to a record $97.2 
billion. Imports of foreign cars and parts hit an all-time high of 
$14.9 billion, a 2.5 percent increase over the previous month. 
</P>
<P>
	But a separate report on steel imports showed that they fell by  
14 percent in April, based on preliminary data, a good sign for the 
country's beleaguered steel industry, which has been battered by a 
flood of cheap imports the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Labor Department issued a report showing that  
America's strong economy was continuing. The number of Americans 
filing new claims for unemployment benefits fell by 12,000 last 
week to 299,000, a sign that tight labor market conditions were 
continuing. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration argues that the overall deficit  
represents a sign of American strength. As the only major world 
economy doing well at the present, the United States is playing a 
valuable role by providing a market for crisis countries who are 
struggling to emerge from deep recessions triggered by the currency 
crisis that began in July 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	But the administration is also worried that if the deficit rises  
too high, it will spawn unstoppable protectionist pressures in 
Congress from industries who have been severely hurt by the 
competition from cheaper imports. 
</P>
<P>
	The steel industry has already won a lopsided vote in the House  
to impose global quotas on steel imports into the United States 
despite a threatened presidential veto. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration claims the measure is blatantly in violation  
of World Trade Organization rules and would put the country's 
exporters at risk of copy-cat retaliation by other nations. 
</P>
<P>
	On steel, the government released a separate report today  
showing that steel imports in April fell by 14 percent to 2.24 
million metric tons, with steel imports from Japan down an even 
larger 26 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has warned Japan that unless its shipments to  
the United States return to pre-1997 levels quickly, the 
administration will bring its own trade sanction case against 
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	For March, America's overall deficit with Japan shot up 23.2  
percent to $6.5 billion as Japanese imports to the United States 
climbed to an all-time high. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has warned Japan that it should not try to  
export its way out of its worst recession in 50 years. Instead, the 
United States, with rising urgency, has been pushing Japan to do 
more to jump-start domestic demand. 
</P>
<P>
	America's deficit with China declined by 10.5 percent in March  
to $4.1 billion, but was still the second largest for any nation. 
China has been negotiating a trade agreement to lower barriers to 
American goods in hopes it will clear the way for China's entry 
into the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the mistaken bombing of the Chinese Embassy in  
Yugoslavia and tensions over human rights have called into question 
whether a deal can be reached soon. 
</P>
<P>
	America's deficit with the 15-nation European Union shot up 30  
percent in March to $2.6 billion while America's deficit with 
Mexico, its partner in the North American Free Trade Agreement, hit 
a record $2.5 billion, up 26 percent from the previous month. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has been arguing that the United States  
cannot sustain such high deficits and that other economic powers, 
specifically Japan and Europe, must do their part by boosting 
growth at home so that they can serve as markets for countries in 
economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
