<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Candidates Debate Over Gun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Democrats seeking the White House are  
jousting over who is toughest on gun control, even as many 
Republicans with the same goal are making it clear they also favor 
some restrictions in the wake of yet another school shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	A fresh round of polling showed voters ever more in favor of  
restrictions, and congressional actions on gun control are likely 
to keep the debate going. 
</P>
<P>
	One GOP candidate took credit for being miles ahead on gun  
control during a hectic day of fighting after a shooting at a 
school outside Atlanta rekindled the debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Within hours, Vice President Al Gore voted to break a Senate tie  
and approve an amendment to require background checks for all 
firearms transactions at all gun shows and pawn shops. ``This is a 
turning point for our country,'' Gore said in touting his vote, 
which drew a congratulatory call from President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	But former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's only announced  
rival for the Democratic nomination, scornfully said White House 
gun control initiatives ``are minimums'' and much stronger actions 
must be taken. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before this is over, we are going to have to do something much  
stronger,'' Bradley said at a news conference while campaigning in 
Iowa. He said he was formulating a proposal on the issue and would 
offer it ``sooner rather than later.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said Gore believes ``there's no one  
answer to helping to protect our kids,'' but the new restrictions 
will help. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to do everything we possibly can from availability of  
guns and today's tie-breaking vote in the Senate is a good step in 
that direction,'' Lehane said. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation the Senate passed, 73-25, Thursday night would  
require the sale of safety devices with handguns and expand a 
system of background checks for firearms purchasers. The House has 
not yet considered the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Republican contenders took care to note they do not flatly  
oppose gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since I first started running for office, I've been for  
background checks, instant background checks,'' said Texas Gov. 
George W. Bush. ``I think background checks are important to make 
sure that guns don't get in the hands of felons and-or people who 
shouldn't be carrying guns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aides to Elizabeth Dole noted that she began calling for gun  
control three weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``She did it first,'' said spokesman Ari Fleischer. ``She did it  
when it wasn't popular.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Kasich of Ohio noted that he voted for a ban on  
assault-style weapons and ``there's some legitimate tightening we 
can do.'' He urged caution, however. 
</P>
<P>
	``We look at gun control as a way to pass three laws and think  
we've fixed the problem,'' Kasich said. ``I'm going to look at 
additional restrictions that make sense, but I'm going to be very 
careful about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aides to former Vice President Dan Quayle said he preferred to  
focus on what he sees as declining cultural values that are the 
root cause of school violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dan Quayle believes there's one issue, and that's the  
culture,'' said spokesman Jonathan Baron. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Schmidt, a spokesman for former Education Secretary Lamar  
Alexander, said Alexander favored some restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	``He would sign legislation requiring background checks at gun  
shows,'' but he opposes ``unreasonable'' restrictions, Schmidt 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The candidates spoke hours after the latest school shooting, at  
a suburban Atlanta high school, where six students were wounded, 
and after the Senate approved new gun restrictions it had rejected 
just last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``It adds another impetus for doing something very significant  
on gun control,'' said Bradley. ``The things that have been 
proposed by the White House are minimums.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Publisher Steve Forbes, seeking the GOP nomination, said he  
would focus on the school shooting issue during a speech Saturday 
to the Georgia Republican Convention. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe there are some real and important steps local, state  
and national leaders can and must take to keep our kids safe and 
bring real discipline and values back into our classrooms,'' Forbes 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush announced a $420,000 grant to create a Texas School Safety  
Center to examine ways of curbing violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is obviously a part of the American tragedy that children  
are coming to school and shooting people, and our society has got 
to do everything we can to figure out ways to prohibit violence,'' 
Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a new poll released by the Pew Research Center for  
the People &AMP; the Press indicated that large majorities of Democrats 
and of Republican women were more inclined to say it was more 
important to control gun ownership than to protect the rights of 
gun owners. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll was taken before the Georgia shootings. Other surveys  
taken after the deadly shooting spree in Littleton, Colo., showed 
public support for gun control elevated by the school incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
