<DOCNO> APW19990520.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 11:11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mortgage Rates Climb / National Mortgage Survey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The average interest rate on 30-year  
fixed-rate mortgages has jumped to its highest level since November 
1997, an expected reaction to a Federal Reserve warning it might 
raise a key interest rate. 
</P>
<P>
	The average this week was 7.23 percent, up from 7.10 percent the  
previous week, the mortgage company Freddie Mac said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve officials said Tuesday if signs of inflation  
continue to show up in the U.S. economy, they were leaning toward 
raising, later this year, the interest rate banks charge each 
other. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the government reported consumer prices rose by 0.7  
percent in April, the biggest monthly jump in nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	``With ... the Fed's announcement of its bias toward higher  
interest rates, mortgage rates began to climb,'' said Frank 
Nothaft, deputy chief economist for Freddie Mac. 
</P>
<P>
	Mortgage rates, along with other interest rates set by financial  
markets, are extremely sensitive to the disposition of Fed 
policy-makers. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, analysts say central bank officials may have anticipated  
their warning alone would be enough to boost some interest rates 
that affect consumers, therefore helping to put a gentle brake on 
the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Low mortgage rates have helped bring about a record home-buying  
boom, accompanied by spending on new furniture, appliances and 
other household items. That activity has kept the U.S. economy 
strong amid widespread financial troubles abroad during the past 
two years. 
</P>
<P>
	But now that some demand for American products overseas is  
recovering, continued low unemployment in the United States and 
robust consumer spending make inflation a bigger worry. 
</P>
<P>
	Before March, mortgage rates had held below 7.0 percent since  
last summer. This week's rise -- the sharpest of five straight -- 
brought the 30-year mortgage rate to its highest level since the 
first week in November 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing,  
averaged 6.83 percent this week, up from 6.71 percent. That is the 
highest since 15-year rates were at 6.85 percent during the last 
week of April 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an  
average initial rate of 5.76 percent this week, up from 5.71 the 
week before. 
</P>
<P>
	The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which  
averaged at or just over 1 percent of the loan amount for all three 
types of mortgages. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 17:06:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Sweden Goes to World Tennis Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- Jonas Bjorkman breezed to a  
straight-set victory over an impatient Greg Rusedski Thursday as 
Sweden swept Britain to reach its fifth final at the World Team 
Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden won the Red Group match 3-0, wrapping it up early by  
taking both singles as Bjorkman rolled past Rusedski 6-2, 6-2, and 
Thomas Enqvist outlasted Tim Henmann 7-6 (7-4), 6-4. 
</P>
<P>
	Bjorkman and Niklas Kulti then beat Rusedski and Henman 6-3,  
5-7, 6-1 in a meaningless doubles at the $1.65 million event, which 
pits eight top tennis countries against each other. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Group winner will be decided in a showdown of unbeatens  
Friday with Pat Rafter-led Australia facing the United States and 
its top player, Pete Sampras. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care who we play -- both countries have excellent  
individual players,'' said Enqvist. 
</P>
<P>
	The hard-serving Rusedski, still trying to prove his power game  
functions on the slow clay, made numerous errors while gambling on 
winners. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went into the match with a lot of self-confidence since I  
had already beaten Rusedski five times,'' said Bjorkman, a former 
top player who has slipped to No. 37 in the world rankings. 
</P>
<P>
	``He didn't play badly, but I made it hard for him with my  
return of serve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden, a three-time winner under Stefan Edberg, advanced to  
Saturday's final on the strength of its 2-1 record and a victory 
over Spain, which also finished 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Spain finished second in the Red Group after beating Germany  
2-1, with defending French Open champion Carlos Moya and Alex 
Corretja wrapping up the match with singles wins. 
</P>
<P>
	Moya beat Tommy Haas 7-6 (7-3), 6-4 and Corretja struggled for  
two hours, 20 minutes before putting away Nicolas Kiefer, 6-3, 4-6, 
6-4 
</P>
<P>
	Boris Becker and David Prinosil gave Germany its point, beating  
Albert Costa and Jairo Velasco, 7-5, 6-4. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain finished third in the Red Group with a 1-2 record, while  
1-2 Germany was fourth after losing the head-to-head tie between 
the two teams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 17:06:04 </DATE_TIME>
