<DOCNO> APW19990520.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 06:05:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wartime Camps Exhibit at Pentagon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It was an odd but moving sight:  
Japanese-American veterans marching into the State Department with 
fife and drum to mark the opening of an exhibit on World War II 
concentration camps. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit on facilities for Jews in Europe and  
Japanese-Americans in the United States calls them both 
``concentration camps'' that were ``rooted in bigotry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an ironic twist, Japanese-American units that fought in  
Europe were among those who liberated Nazi concentration camps in 
Dachau, Germany, while their own families were forced to live in 
what the U.S. government calls ``internment camps'' in the Western 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit, which opened Wednesday, is a departure from U.S.  
policy, which refuses to apply the words ``concentration camp'' to 
the U.S. camps. It also chronicles anti-Semitism and anti-Asian 
sentiment in the United States before World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Five decades after they fought for their government -- the U.S.  
government -- the veterans joined with Jewish Americans to tell the 
horror stories of the wartime camps. 
</P>
<P>
	A disclaimer on the exhibit says: ``The use of the words  
'concentration camp' is not intended to equate the American camps 
with the Holocaust camps. The events were differently motivated and 
on different scales, though both were rooted in bigotry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The series of photographs, maps and posters greeting visitors at  
the main State Department entrance is sponsored by the 
Japanese-American National Museum in Los Angeles and the National 
Museum of American Jewish Military History in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Irene Hirano, executive director of the Japanese-American  
museum, said the exhibit pointedly does not use official language 
to describe the plight of 120,000 loyal Japanese-Americans, 
avoiding euphemisms like ``relocation'' and ``evacuation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Jewish and Japanese-Americans had a particularly poignant role  
in World War II,'' she said, noting that both were victims of 
prejudice and persecution. To make amends, the U.S. government has 
made $20,000 payments and apologized to more than 82,000 
Japanese-Americans for the World War II internments. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit also focuses on American bigotry in the 1920s and  
1930s. A re-election poster for Sen. James D. Phelan declares: 
``Keep California White.'' Another from a New York judicial race 
says: ``Don't vote for Pike. He's a kike.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the display features photos taken by Japanese-American  
soldiers in Europe, including George Oiye of San Jose, Calif., who 
was among those attending the opening. Oiye, 77, said his unit 
liberated several Nazi slave labor camps. His photos show Jewish 
prisoners in black and white concentration camp uniforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Another veteran, Eddie Ichiyama of Honolulu, also in his 70s,  
said memories of liberating Dachau are still with him. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing I remember most is the gaunt, white faces, and the  
stench,'' he said. ``I don't think we have learned the lessons of 
history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit comes as the government considers paying $5,000 each  
in reparations to other Japanese-Americans, most of them from Latin 
America, who also spent time in the camps. The measure is part of 
$15 billion spending bill passed by the House on Tuesday and 
scheduled for a vote today in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	About 3,000 ethnic Japanese were rounded up from 13 Latin  
American countries during World War II and forcibly brought to the 
United States. The government had hoped to exchange the group for 
U.S. prisoners of war held by Japan. The exchange program never 
developed and the Japanese Latin Americans were instead housed in 
the camps with Japanese-Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has agreed to pay $5,000 to each of them of the  
Latin American Japanese, but only 145 have received payments so 
far. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the reparations bill, the Justice Department would  
allocate: 
</P>
<P>
	--$1.58 million for up to 79 eligible Japanese-American cases at  
$20,000 each. 
</P>
<P>
	--$1.98 million for 395 eligible Japanese Latin American cases at  
$5,000 each. 
</P>
<P>
	--$665,000 for 133 additional Japanese Latin American cases  
expected to qualify, at $5,000 each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
