<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.M. Lab Integrity Shattered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- The director of the Los Alamos National  
Laboratory says the facility has been devastated by allegations of 
espionage and will take years to regain the nation's trust. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's certainly not going to happen in a year,'' Jon Browne  
said in today's Albuquerque Journal. ``I think you're talking about 
time frames in the three- to five-year range of sustained 
performance in security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lab has been the subject of intense scrutiny this year. The  
apparent theft of nuclear secrets at Los Alamos -- in the 1980s, but 
possibly as recently as 1995 -- has put pressure on officials to 
increase security. 
</P>
<P>
	The University of California operates the lab for the Department  
of Energy. Browne, who has led the lab since 1996, set up a new 
counterintelligence office last year and shut down classified 
computing. 
</P>
<P>
	But critics remain worried over allegations that former Los  
Alamos scientist Wen Ho Lee downloaded hundreds of classified 
files. And they're particularly angry that Lee -- who remains under 
an espionage investigation -- remained on the job as long as he did. 
</P>
<P>
	Browne fired Lee in March for alleged security violations.  
</P>
<P>
	Lee has not been charged with a crime and through a lawyer has  
denied spying or providing secrets to China. China also has denied 
it stole U.S. nuclear secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	Browne said investigators and DOE officials failed to keep Los  
Alamos executives apprised of their findings and did not clear the 
lab to move Lee out of his job. He described communications as 
``inadequate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't just take action because someone's a suspect in a  
criminal investigation. That would be a terrible situation,'' 
Browne said. ``If at any time someone had said the information is 
good enough to take somebody out of their job, we would have done 
it right away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He blamed current problems on such things as ``underestimating  
the (espionage) threat, a nationwide lowering of the guard after 
the end of the Cold War and an attitude that failed to recognize 
small infractions as a harbinger of bigger problems.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
