<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Tribune Won't Cover Indy 500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Tribune will not cover the  
Indianapolis 500 because race officials barred a Sports Illustrated 
writer from the event, and the Los Angeles Times also is 
considering a boycott. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indy Racing League denied credentials for the May 30 race to  
Ed Hinton, SI's senior auto racing writer. IRL officials were upset 
by a photo of a sheet-covered body and an article that appeared in 
the magazine's May 10 issue after three fans were killed May 1 at 
the VisionAire 500 in Concord, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Hinton wrote in the article, titled ``Fatal Attractions,'' that  
such accidents could be avoided. 
</P>
<P>
	John Cherwa, the Tribune's associate managing editor for sports,  
said the newspaper will not cover the event because it believes the 
IRL's decision is wrong and ``shows a complete lack of 
understanding of the role of the press.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not exactly standing with Sports Illustrated. But we are  
standing up against the kind of censorship the IRL is trying to 
impose -- telling us who is acceptable to them to cover their 
event,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tribune plans to use wire services to report on the race.  
</P>
<P>
	Other newspapers also are mulling over coverage plans.  
</P>
<P>
	Rick Jaffe, executive sports editor at the Los Angeles Times,  
said the newspaper was trying to reach IRL officials Wednesday 
evening to discuss the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't think it's right what they're doing,'' he said. ``We  
are considering not covering the Indy 500 and want to talk to them 
to get their side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The speedway offered to provide credentials for a different SI  
writer, but the magazine declined. 
</P>
<P>
	Mai Lindstrom, an IRL spokeswoman, said race officials had no  
comment on the Tribune's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Editors at other newspapers said they will cover the race, even  
if they don't support the IRL action. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think what Indy has done with SI is a very bad thing, but  
right now our position is that we need to look out for our readers, 
and our readers are looking for coverage of the race,'' said Greg 
Gibson, sports editor of The Orange County Register, the 
second-largest newspaper in the Los Angeles area. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indianapolis Star's sports editor said she understands why  
SI and the Tribune backed out of covering the race, but her 
newspaper won't follow suit. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of the biggest events that occurs in our hometown,  
and we intend to cover it,'' said Nancy Winkley, The Star's 
assistant managing editor for sports. 
</P>
<P>
	The photograph at the center of the controversy was taken by The  
Associated Press. It showed one victim lying on blood-covered 
grandstand steps with a leg protruding from beneath a sheet and 
another sheet-covered body. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Horton, AP's senior photo editor for sports, said photo  
editors were sensitive to the graphic nature of the photographs and 
took steps to edit them carefully. He said there had been no 
complaints from AP members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
