<HEADLINE> Ford Finance Chief Is Retiring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. chief financial officer  
John M. Devine has decided to retire at the end of September, the 
nation's second biggest automaker announced Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice Chairman W. Wayne Booker will assume the additional role of  
chief financial officer on July 1, Ford said. It said Devine will 
remain on to help with the transition. 
</P>
<P>
	Devine, a 31-year veteran of Ford, had also held the title of  
executive vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he wanted ``to explore other opportunities involving  
wider responsibilities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Devine became chief financial officer in 1994. Before that, he  
spent six years as president, and later as chairman, of First 
Nationwide Bank, which then was a Ford subsidiary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
