<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed OKs BT, Deutsche Bank Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bankers Trust Corp. and Germany's Deutsche  
Bank AG have cleared a major hurdle on their way to creating the 
world's largest financial institution, securing the Federal 
Reserve's approval for their $10.2 billion merger. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was 6-0 Thursday by the central bank's board of  
governors, who determined the acquisition of the nation's 
eighth-largest bank by Germany's largest would not threaten banking 
competition in this country. 
</P>
<P>
	New York-based Bankers Trust concentrates on banking for big  
corporations and does no retail consumer business. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger would create a transnational financial powerhouse  
with $830 billion in assets. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition of Bankers Trust would be the biggest takeover  
of a U.S. financial institution by a foreign bank. The institution 
would be larger than UBS AG of Switzerland, currently the largest 
bank, and the recently formed Citigroup Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Pushing through regulatory channels on two continents since they  
announced the deal last November, the two banks have surmounted 
concerns over competition, the mixing of banking and commerce, and 
the claims of Holocaust survivors and heirs. 
</P>
<P>
	The regulators apparently were not troubled by Deutsche Bank's  
12 percent stake in the newly-formed automaker DaimlerChrysler AG. 
According to U.S. laws that separate banks from other kinds of 
corporations, banks in this country are prohibited from owning more 
than 5 percent of a nonfinancial company. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve's approval was the latest in a series of  
hurdles cleared by the merger recently, leaving only approval from 
authorities in Canada and New Jersey to be secured. 
</P>
<P>
	The two banks said in a statement Thursday they expected the  
merger might be completed as early as next month. They called the 
Fed's approval ``a further decisive step'' towards completion. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, under pressure from the U.S. State  
Department, New York City Comptroller Alan Hevesi withdrew his 
opposition to the deal, acknowledging that the two banks had made 
progress in resolving Holocaust claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Holocaust survivors and heirs have been seeking restitution for  
millions of dollars in Jewish property and financial holdings 
stolen by the Nazis in the World War II era and hidden in various 
European banks. 
</P>
<P>
	A State Department official had warned that opposition to the  
merger on political grounds could chill the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed noted in its decision that it had received written  
comments from people and groups expressing concern about Deutsche 
Bank's activities during the war and urging it to investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently discovered files from eastern Europe showed that loans  
from a Deutsche Bank branch in Nazi-occupied Poland helped finance 
the Auschwitz death camp. 
</P>
<P>
	After a careful review, the Fed said it had concluded that  
Holocaust-related issues ``do not warrant denial'' of the proposed 
merger. The Fed noted that Deutsche Bank had recently joined with 
other German banks, insurers and other companies to set up a 
humanitarian fund to benefit Holocaust victims and compensate slave 
laborers from the wartime era. 
</P>
<P>
	New York state's banking regulators and European Union  
authorities have also approved the merger. 
</P>
<P>
	In the resolution of another matter, Bankers Trust agreed in  
March to pay $63.5 million in fines to settle federal prosecutors' 
charges that it boosted its financial performance by unlawfully 
diverting millions of dollars from unclaimed customer accounts into 
its own coffers. 
</P>
<P>
	The plea entered in a federal court brought a speedy resolution  
to accusations that the bank made false entries in its books to 
conceal the true source of $19.1 million its employees diverted. 
</P>
<P>
	Bankers Trust has some $133 billion in assets. Deutsche Bank has  
assets of $734 billion. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
