<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Leaves To Work for NASD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Edward S. Knight, general counsel of the  
Treasury Department since September 1994, is leaving the government 
to become executive vice president and chief legal officer of the 
National Association of Securities Dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	The NASD, a self-policing trade group for the securities  
brokerage industry, announced Wednesday that Knight would begin his 
new position July 5. 
</P>
<P>
	The move comes a week after Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin  
announced he was stepping down, also in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight, 48, will provide legal advice to the NASD's senior  
managers and will oversee the association's legal services. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Treasury, Knight gave legal and policy advice to Rubin  
and other top officials and oversaw the department's 2,200 
attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight played a key role last fall in arranging a $5 billion  
U.S. contribution to the International Monetary Fund's $41.5 
billion rescue package for Brazil. The American contribution is in 
the form of U.S. government guarantees for loans to Brazil from the 
Switzerland-based Bank for International Settlements. 
</P>
<P>
	Before entering the government, Knight was a partner with the  
Washington law firm Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer and Feld. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight, a native of Amarillo, Texas, has a bachelor's degree in  
Latin American studies and a law degree from the University of 
Texas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
