<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Bill Kills Gore Space Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore's vision of putting an  
Earth-viewing satellite in orbit has been brought down to Earth by 
House Republicans who say the idea is wasteful and unnecessary. 
</P>
<P>
	The House on Wednesday approved a three-year $42 billion NASA  
authorization bill that, over the protests of Democrats, 
effectively kills a Gore-inspired plan to launch a satellite that 
would put 24-hour views of the Earth on television and the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The $32 million originally set aside for the Triana project is  
less than 1 percent of the proposed National Aeronautics and Space 
Administration budget, but Democrats and the White House suggested 
the legislation might be subject to a presidential veto if the 
money is not restored when the Senate takes up the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said it was part of the GOP campaign to trip up Gore's  
run for the presidency next year. ``I can think of no reason for 
the elimination of this particular program except partisan 
politics,'' said Rep. Joe Moakley, D-Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	The Triana spacecraft, named for the sailor who first spotted  
the New World on the journey with Christopher Columbus, was to have 
been launched by NASA in December next year. 
</P>
<P>
	But the House Science Committee, on a party-line 21-18 vote last  
Thursday, transferred all the money for the program to life and 
microgravity research. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. David Weldon, R-Fla., chief sponsor of the amendment,  
argued that views of the Earth are already available on the Weather 
Channel and NASA-TV and he considered it an ``insult'' that some 
600 people were being laid off at the Kennedy Space Center at the 
same time the agency was ``finding tens of millions of dollars to 
fulfill a vision for the vice president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Just because the new Star Wars movie is opening today doesn't  
mean we have to spend $30 million on a far-out boondoggle,'' said 
House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	But NASA and the White House argued that the satellite would  
transmit an image twice as clear as new high-resolution television 
sets and would be unique in presenting a full-Earth view. 
</P>
<P>
	Triana was subject to rigorous peer review, the White House  
said, and would provide the scientific community with valuable data 
on the Earth's climate and solar flares. 
</P>
<P>
	The ranking Democrat on the Science panel, Rep. Bart Gordon of  
Tennessee, said NASA had already spent $40 million on the $75 
million project, and the government would lose more by killing it 
than by completing it. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats did not propose an amendment to revive the program,  
saying they would press the Senate to do so when it takes up the 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope they will change their mind,'' said Dave Steitz,  
spokesman for NASA. ``We would like them to base their decision on 
the science of the mission.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also provides $7 billion for the U.S. portion of the  
international space station, $7.8 billion for space shuttle 
operations and $4.2 billion for earth science programs. 
</P>
<P>
	As in past years, Rep. Tim Roemer, D-Ind., led a move against  
the space station, but with that program moving into the 
construction phase he got little support for amendments that would 
have capped funding, killed the program altogether or removed 
Russia as a partner. 
</P>
<P>
	The House defeated, 313-117, Roemer's amendment that would have  
ended Russian participation, relegating the Russians to 
subcontractors in future work on the 16-nation project. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians repeatedly have been behind schedule in completing  
their work, driving up U.S. costs by as much as $5 billion. Rep. 
James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., chairman of the Science Committee, 
said the Russians were ``a miserable failure in being a partner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But others warned the amendment could undermine fragile  
U.S.-Russian relations and kill a project that is finally making 
headway. The first component of the station, the U.S.-funded, 
Russian-built Zarya module, was launched last November. NASA 
followed in December with its Unity module. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the House by voice vote accepted an amendment by Rep. John  
Sweeney, R-N.Y., requiring NASA to certify within 15 days that any 
proposed future agreements with China would not improve the missile 
or space launch capabilities of China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
