<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibit Honors Furniture Designers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Anyone who ever looked for a way to relax  
after a hard day at work has reason to know about Charles and Ray 
Eames. 
</P>
<P>
	The husband and wife team designed the fiberglass stacked chair  
and the laid-back lounger-with-ottoman that makes even a crowded 
furniture ad look restful. The lounger still retails for as much as 
$2,500. Knock-offs in a variety of materials and varying levels of 
comfort can be had for less than $100. 
</P>
<P>
	A Library of Congress exhibit opens today for a three-month  
showing of more than a million items of the Eameses' work. The 
couple created a variety of things, from children's toys to the 
film ``Powers of 10,'' shown at the Air and Space Museum, that 
gives viewers an idea of the universe's vastness. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall theme: something can be useful and beautiful at the  
same time. 
</P>
<P>
	They worked together for more than 35 years until Charles' death  
in 1978. Ray Eames, a designer and sculptor, lived for another 
decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``They combined work and play,'' Lucia Eames, Charles' daughter  
from an earlier marriage, said at a news conference this week. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1940s, the Eames put together a wood-molding machine from  
bicycle parts and scraps of wood. When the house electricity did 
not furnish enough current to generate the heat required to run the 
machine, Charles Eames climbed a pole with a big piece of insulated 
cable to bypass the fuses, according to his grandson, Eames 
Demetrios. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy during World War II gave them a contract to mold leg  
splints for wounded servicemen. The glues used and techniques they 
learned helped later with furniture design. Ray, who had trained as 
an artist with German-American painter Hans Hofmann, also based an 
abstract sculpture on the splint design. 
</P>
<P>
	Eames made the film ``Glimpses of the U.S.A.'' for a 1959 Moscow  
exhibit, which later became known for the ``kitchen debate'' 
between then Vice President Richard Nixon and Soviet leader Nikita 
Khruschev on the merits of the Soviet and American systems. 
</P>
<P>
	The film was shown on seven screens stretched about 250 feet  
around a dome, Demetrios estimated. It impressed Khruschev and he 
asked Eames to make one like it for the Soviet Union. Eames 
suggested diplomatically that Russians could do it better, and 
turned him down. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides their heavily padded lounger, the Eames designed many  
more metal, fiber glass and plastic chairs, rounded to the human 
form to make a lack of padding less noticeable to the sitter. That 
design feature has been supported by recent criticism. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Work of Charles and Ray Eames'' leaves the Library of  
Congress Sept. 20 and will be seen at the Cooper-Newitt National 
Design Museum in New York, Oct. 12, 1999 to Jan. 9, 2000; St. Louis 
Art Museum, Feb. 19, 2000-May 14; and the Los Angeles County Art 
Museum, June 25, 2000-Sept. 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 06:17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Roy, Forsberg Help Avs Advance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- For two years, Colorado languished in the shadow  
of the Detroit Red Wings, watching enviously as they supplanted the 
Avalanche as Stanley Cup champions and then won back-to-back 
titles. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be no three-peat for the Red Wings, however, as the  
Avalanche finally vanquished their bitter rivals in six games in 
the Western Conference semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	After spotting Detroit a 2-0 series lead, the Avalanche won four  
in a row. Now, they face the team with the best regular-season 
record in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado will meet the Dallas Stars in Game 1 of the conference  
finals on Saturday night in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a long couple of years for us,'' Avalanche  
defenseman Adam Foote said, ``but that's over for us against that 
team now. It's just very, very sweet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Forsberg scored two goals as the Avalanche beat Detroit  
5-2 Tuesday night to advance. 
</P>
<P>
	But while Forsberg clearly justified his new $30 million  
contract with his all-around play in the last four games, it was 
goalie Patrick Roy who was the catalyst for Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Roy, whose 12th career playoff shutout led Colorado to a 3-0  
victory in Game 5 in Denver on Sunday, made 35 saves Tuesday night, 
many of them brilliant when the game was close. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an awesome feeling, coming back from 0-2,'' Forsberg  
said. ``Everybody's been stepping up, from the last guy to the 
first guy. And Patrick's been great in net.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Avs coach Bob Hartley agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Patrick is Patrick,'' Hartley said. ``He was outstanding. I'm  
not surprised with the way he played. I grew up around Montreal and 
I saw him win with the Canadiens (Stanley Cup titles in 1986 and 
1993). I saw him win a Stanley Cup with the Avalanche (1996). He's 
rock solid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Colorado lost the first two games of the series at home  
and appeared on the verge of being swept, Roy stopped 146 of 153 
shots as Colorado won four in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	``To win four straight against Detroit -- I didn't think it was  
possible, to be honest,'' Roy said. ``But we had no choice. We put 
ourselves in a really bad position, losing those two games in 
Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a great comeback for us, being down 2-0. We took it one  
game at a time and played some great hockey. We won three games in 
Detroit, and it's not every team that can do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blessed with talented skaters and puck-handlers, the Avalanche  
faltered early in the series with Detroit when they tried to get 
fancy, making too many passes or attempting the highlight-video 
shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``We played simple hockey,'' Roy said. ``That's how we won this  
series. It was a good series, and great for us to beat that team. 
They were the Stanley Cup champions, and we beat them. It feels 
good, but now we've got another series against another very tough 
team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hartley called the Stars ``a great hockey club. They are the  
regular-season champions and they're going to be a great challenge 
for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the bad blood that has defined Colorado-Detroit meetings  
since 1996, the Red Wings were gracious in defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you lose four straight like we did, you can't say the other  
team was lucky,'' Detroit coach Scotty Bowman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can look at it as we underachieved,'' Red Wings captain  
Steve Yzerman said. ``Or you can look at it as we got beat by a 
great team. I choose to look at it as Colorado played fantastic. 
</P>
<P>
	``They made great adjustments from the first two games to the  
last four. Their top players played very well at both ends of the 
rink. Joe Sakic was excellent on penalty killing, on faceoffs, and 
he did all the little things well. 
</P>
<P>
	``They got production from all four lines, their defense is good  
and their goaltender was very solid. They did all the things 
through the last four games that are necessary, not just to beat 
good teams, but to win the Stanley Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While only 2-4 at home during the postseason this year, the Avs  
can take comfort in the fact they're 6-0 on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the Stars' 51-19-12 regular-season record, Colorado  
compiled a 2-1-1 record against them. Dallas defeated St. Louis in 
six games to advance to the next round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
