<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Veterans Ask for Cemetery Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With World War II servicemen dying at the rate  
of 1,000 a day, the nation's veterans groups are delivering a 
pre-Memorial Day plea for new and expanded national cemeteries. 
</P>
<P>
	It takes five to seven years to plan and build national  
cemeteries, and work must begin now before available space is used 
up, the organizations are telling a House Veterans Affairs 
subcommittee today. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the Department of Veterans Affairs, Ken  
McKinnon, said most of the burial grounds the agency runs would 
last until 2030 -- even if there is no expansion. 
</P>
<P>
	Arlington National Cemetery, maintained by the Army, would run  
out of space by 2025 without an expansion. However, Army officials 
are looking at 14 parcels of land that could enlarge the burial 
ground and keep it operating into the 22nd century. 
</P>
<P>
	McKinnon said the Veterans Administration will ``continue to  
evaluate the need to establish new national cemeteries based on 
veteran demographics, and we are currently building four new 
ones.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Terry Everett, R-Ala., chairman of the House Veterans  
Affairs investigations subcommittee, said, ``We're losing more than 
a thousand World War II veterans a day, more than 377,000 a year. 
Funding is millions of dollars short to meet their needs. We're 
going to run out of space early in the 21st century unless 
something is done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Linda Ricci, spokeswoman for the Office of Management and  
Budget, said federal agencies operate on five-year budgeting and 
strategic planning cycles. But she added, ``This is not to say that 
agencies wouldn't be expected to be thinking ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The government estimates that annual veterans' deaths will  
increase from 550,000 in 1998 to a peak of 620,000 in 2008. About 
10 percent of all veterans are buried in national cemeteries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our main concern is beyond the year 2000,'' said John  
Vitikacs, the national cemeteries expert for the American Legion. 
``The VA cannot gear up fast enough. Even if they're given a 
go-ahead tomorrow to create the next five national cemeteries, it 
will be 2007 before any of them are going to be open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four new national cemeteries will open this year in Albany,  
N.Y.; Chicago; Dallas; and Cleveland. Major construction projects 
are planned at a number of existing sites. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Legion said areas with the greatest need for new  
national cemeteries include Oklahoma City; Atlanta; Sacramento, 
Calif.; Miami; St. Louis; Pittsburgh; and Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	In testimony prepared for the hearing, Sidney Daniels, a  
Veterans of Foreign Wars official, said expansion of the cemetery 
system ``over the next 10 years will be crucial to meeting the 
burial demands that will be placed on this system as the veteran 
population ages.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Except for the national scope of the country's most hallowed  
burial ground, Arlington National Cemetery, other cemeteries are 
designed to handle burials within a 75-mile radius. The Veterans 
Administration also provides states with 100 percent funding for 
construction and initial equipment costs of new state veterans' 
cemeteries. However, many states are reluctant to commit to the 
long-term costs associated with maintaining the grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside of Arlington, those eligible for burial in national  
cemeteries include active duty personnel and veterans who completed 
their service requirements. Spouses and minor children also are 
eligible. 
</P>
<P>
	In Arlington, regulations are more restrictive. Besides those on  
active duty, veterans must be on a retired list and eligible to 
receive retirement pay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
