<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How Young Murder Witness Was Killed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Screaming ``Mommy, Mommy,'' an  
8-year-old boy was fatally shot after a gunman burst into his house 
and chased him up the stairs to prevent him from testifying in a 
murder trial, a witness said. 
</P>
<P>
	The final moments of Leroy ``B.J.'' Brown Jr.'s life were  
detailed in court papers that were released Thursday in which 
Josephine Lee admitted acting as a lookout for the boy's killer. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee told police the gunman chased the boy and his mother up the  
stairs, firing at them as they ran for their lives. B.J. was still 
yelling for his mother when the gunman shot him in the back of the 
head, Lee told police. The mother, Karen Clarke, 29, was also 
killed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jan. 8 slayings horrified the community and prompted sharp  
criticism of Connecticut's witness protection program. 
</P>
<P>
	Leroy had been scheduled to testify against Russell Peeler in  
the 1998 slaying of Ms. Clarke's fiance. The boy had witnessed an 
earlier drive-by shooting in which Peeler allegedly attempted to 
kill the man. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee told police that Peeler's brother, Adrian Peeler, was the  
killer. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee lived across from B.J. and his mother, and had been asked to  
page Russell Peeler when Clarke returned home, according to the 
affidavit. She said he also asked her to serve as lookout. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee paged Russell Peeler when Clarke arrived home and his  
brother arrived within minutes. Lee said she rang Clarke's doorbell 
and Adrian Peeler pushed his way in when she answered. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard the shot and the little boy was reaching out for his  
mother,'' Lee said. ``He was yelling, `Mommy, Mommy, Mommy, 
Mommy.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Adrian Peeler chased Clarke into a bedroom. Lee heard a shot,  
and then saw Adrian Peeler came out of the bedroom, where B.J. was 
still screaming for his mother. He then shot B.J. in the head, Lee 
told police. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors arrested the Peelers last month. Lee pleaded guilty  
to conspiracy to commit murder and prosecutors have agreed to ask 
for a maximum sentence of seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	Both brothers pleaded innocent Thursday to murder and  
conspiracy. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell Peeler's lawyer, John T. Walkley, called Lee's account  
``preposterous'' and said she had changed her story several times. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each statement seems to be a little more incredible than the  
next,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
