<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report Says US Secrets Helped China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- China has been able to make substantial gains  
in modernizing its nuclear weapons program because of U.S. secrets 
obtained in a pervasive campaign of espionage and misuse of legally 
obtained technology, a long-awaited congressional report says. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, according to officials familiar with it, concludes  
that there is little question that China has obtained critical 
information about an array of U.S. warheads through theft from U.S. 
nuclear weapons labs as well as meticulous scanning of publicly 
available information. 
</P>
<P>
	The 700-page report by a special House committee was ready to be  
released, possibly as early as today, after months of negotiations 
with the Clinton administration over how much of it should remain 
classified. 
</P>
<P>
	Many details of the report, which has been a year in the making,  
have been leaked in recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, its formal findings are certain to add to the growing  
turmoil over charges of lax security at the government's 
prestigious nuclear weapons research labs. 
</P>
<P>
	Under pressure from a string of embarrassing revelations in the  
news media, President Clinton and Energy Secretary Bill Richardson 
have said steps were being taken to improve security at the labs. 
And congressional Republicans said they would make sure 
improvements took place. 
</P>
<P>
	Security at weapons labs has been the subject of intense  
scrutiny since early March when a scientist at the Los Alamos 
National Laboratory in New Mexico was fired after being suspected 
since 1996 of having provided China with warhead secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	The scientist, Wen Ho Lee, has not been charged with a crime and  
through his lawyer has denied providing nuclear secrets to China or 
anyone else. Chinese officials also have denied that the country 
stole secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	The special House committee, headed by Rep. Christopher Cox,  
R-Calif., heard extensive testimony concerning the investigation 
surrounding Lee. But the declassified version of the panel's report 
provides little additional information about the Los Alamos 
investigation, said officials familiar with the document. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, the report sharply criticizes security and  
counterintelligence activities at three weapons research labs -- Los 
Alamos and Sandia in New Mexico, and Lawrence Livermore in 
California -- saying it has led to the loss of secrets to China 
under both Republican and Democratic administrations, spanning more 
than two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	And the report maintains the security problems persist today and  
adequate counterintelligence measures are unlikely to be in place 
before 2000, according to officials who summarized the findings. 
They spoke only on condition of not being further identified. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the Energy Department and White House declined comment late  
Wednesday on the report in advance of its formal release. 
</P>
<P>
	But senior administration officials have raised concerns  
privately -- as negotiations dragged on over how much of the report 
to make public -- that the document does not adequately take into 
account security and counterintelligence improvements made in 
recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	And, they have complained, the bipartisan committee's findings --  
approved unanimously last December -- is based largely on 
conjecture, taking too pessimistic of a view on the extent to which 
China may have actually benefited from its espionage, citing a 
recent CIA finding that expressed less certain conclusions. 
</P>
<P>
	The report assumes a ``worst case'' scenario while there remain  
sharp disagreements within the U.S. intelligence community on how 
much China actually benefited, one official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, officials familiar with the massive report said  
the document describes a pervasive and determined campaign by China 
to use both America's nuclear secrets and unclassified 
technological information to advance its weapons program. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee of five Republicans and four Democrats, found  
that:	   --There is clear evidence that China obtained highly secret 
information about a sophisticated nuclear warhead, the W-88, in the 
1980s as a result of secrets stolen from Los Alamos. Other 
information, some available from public sources, was obtained on a 
half-dozen other weapons systems 
</P>
<P>
	--Chinese espionage encompasses a wide array of activities from  
targeting scientists at the weapons labs to ferreting out both 
classified and unclassified information from public sources. 
</P>
<P>
	--America's national security has been compromised by China's  
legal acquisitions of satellite and missile technology, 
supercomputers, jet engines, telecommunications equipment and 
sophisticated machine tools because they have been used in part for 
military purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	--While most of the espionage cases cited by the report date back  
to 1980s, one case involving the suspected theft of secrets about 
the neutron bomb is believed to have occurred as recently as 1995 
during Clinton administration. The FBI never had enough evidence to 
prosecute that case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
