<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Sets Social Security Hearings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chairman of the House Ways and Means  
Committee is planning summer hearings on ways to strengthen Social 
Security even though other Republican leaders have said final 
congressional action is unlikely this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there are areas where there can be an ultimate  
reconciliation,'' Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, said late Wednesday 
after a meeting with President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Archer said he and Clinton did not ``attempt to try to negotiate  
any sort of compromise'' between competing rescue plans they have 
put forth, but rather talked about how they could help other 
lawmakers overcome reluctance to negotiate changes in the popular 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that we have developed a working relationship that if  
we both worked our sides we would have an opportunity'' for 
compromise, Archer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss, said several weeks  
ago he does not expect any significant changes in Social Security 
to be enacted this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's top economic adviser, Gene Sperling, said that at the  
meeting with Archer the president brought up ``the need to have 
processes like hearings and consultations that allowed Democrats 
and Republicans to participate, express views and suggestions and 
give an opportunity for bipartisan consensus to form.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear, however, whether Archer's offer to hold hearings  
in June, after Congress returns from its traditional Memorial Day 
break, will provide such a forum. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ways and Means chairman said he will limit discussion to  
proposals that meet a test of providing 75 years of financial 
health for Social Security. Clinton's plan, by the administration's 
own estimate, would assure only about 60 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it is in some way added to so that it will meet that  
standard, it will be subject to the hearing and I think the 
president understands that,'' Archer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Clinton's and Archer's plans would invest some of Social  
Security's cash reserves in the stock market in an effort to 
increase their worth enough to help close a financing shortfall 
expected after baby boomers retire and begin to collect benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Clinton would have the government handle the  
investments while Archer would set up a new system of accounts that 
individual Americans would control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
