<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teammate: Glover Staying at Ga. Tech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Dion Glover has decided to remain at Georgia  
Tech, a teammate said, and an announcement probably will be made 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yellow Jackets guard met Thursday with his coach, Bobby  
Cremins, to discuss his options. Neither commented on whether he 
would stay at Tech instead of entering the NBA draft. 
</P>
<P>
	But Tony Akins, a sophomore guard and Glover's roommate, said  
the decision has been made. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to stay,'' Akins said. ``I feel better now. We have  
a better team. We're getting our leader back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glover was the third-leading freshman scorer in the nation in  
1997-98, averaging 18.4 points. He did not play last season after 
severely injuring his knee in the opening practice. 
</P>
<P>
	School spokesman Mike Finn said an announcement on Glover's  
future was expected Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dion has not had a chance to talk to his parents, and he wants  
to do that first,'' Finn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Glover announced last week he was making himself eligible for  
the draft. But he left open the possibility of returning to Tech 
for what would be his redshirt sophomore season. 
</P>
<P>
	Apparently, the 6-foot-5 guard changed his mind after  
considering the physical demands that would be required prior to 
the June 30 draft. He was cleared to run only two weeks ago after 
tearing the anterior cruciate and medial collateral ligaments in 
his left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Glover planned to attend a pre-draft camp in Chicago -- paying  
his own way -- and also work out individually for NBA teams. He did 
not sign with an agent so he could keep his college eligibility 
intact if he decided to pull out before the draft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
