<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Bill Targets Oil Tankers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A bill approved by the California  
Assembly would prohibit oil companies from using tankers to 
transport oil in California's coastal waters. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the bill approved Thursday by a 43-26, would require  
companies to move oil by pipeline. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill by Assemblywoman Hannah-Beth Jackson, D-Santa Barbara,  
now moves to the Senate for a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The California Coastal Commission has said that oil moved  
through pipelines is safer for the environment, but the commission 
has yet to mandate pipeline usage. 
</P>
<P>
	``The major accidents occur when we transport by tanker,''  
Jackson said. ``This bill will help put an end to that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The oil industry has not expressed an objection to such  
requirements, Jackson added. 
</P>
<P>
	But opponents said the state cannot make oil transportation  
completely safe and that such efforts would amount to futile 
micromanaging. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does a disservice to the oil industry, and the people who  
will pay for it are the consumers at the pumps,'' said Sam 
Aanestad, R-Grass Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson's bill would apply only to oil transported through  
California's coastal waters, which extend three miles off the 
state's coast. The bill would not affect oil transportation in 
federal or international waters, said Janice Rocco, a spokeswoman 
for Jackson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
