<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *William Alfred    	
</P>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- William Alfred, a playwright and Harvard  
professor, died Thursday in his sleep. He was 76. 
</P>
<P>
	Known to students as ``The Professor,'' Alfred specialized in  
early English literature and taught courses on ``Beowulf'' and 
playwriting. 
</P>
<P>
	His play, ``Hogan's Goat,'' had a long and successful  
off-Broadway run in 1966 and gave Faye Dunaway her first starring 
role. The play earned him the New York Drama Desk Award in 1966. 
</P>
<P>
	Other works included ``Agamemnon,'' 1982's ``The Curse of an  
Aching Heart'' (also starring Dunaway); ``Nothing Doing,'' and 
``Who to Love,'' a musical adaptation of ``Hogan's Goat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was credited with influencing a number of Harvard students  
who went on to theatrical careers, including Stockard Channing, 
John Lithgow and Tommy Lee Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	His social circle included several writers and poets, among  
them, Gertrude Stein, Archibald MacLeish, Robert Lowell and Seamus 
Heaney. 
</P>
<P>
	Alfred served on the poetry panels of the Pulitzer Prize and  
National Book Award committees and also authored a book of poems, 
``The Annunciation Rosary,'' and a translation of ``Beowulf.'' 

</P>
<P>
                            *Henry Jones    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Tony Award-winning actor Henry Jones, whose  
career on Broadway and in movies and television spanned more than 
half a century, died Monday from injuries suffered in a fall at his 
home. He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	His bulldog face was familiar from dozens of Broadway plays and  
films and 350 television shows. His mild manner and steely scowl 
were put to use playing everything from judges to janitors, 
murderers to ministers. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1950s, he was the handyman killed by deadly child Patty  
McCormack in the Broadway play ``The Bad Seed,'' a role he would 
later repeat in the film version. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1958, he won a Tony Award for his portrayal of Louis Howe,  
confident of Franklin D. Roosevelt, in ``Sunrise at Campobello.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His three dozen films included ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance  
Kid,'' ``Arachnophobia,'' ``The Grifters'' and Alfred Hitchock's 
``Vertigo,'' in which he played a coroner and delivered a 
four-minute monologue. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones began his career with theater work in the 1930s and made  
his Broadway debut in 1938 in a version of ``Hamlet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, he was Sam in the Hallmark Hall of Fame production of  
``Breathing Lessons,'' and in 1995 was the Assayer in ``Picture 
Windows.'' 

</P>
<P>
                          *Augustos Pablo    	
</P>
<P>
	KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) -- Jamaican musician Augustos Pablo,  
popular in Europe and known for his plastic melodica, died 
Wednesday after being in a coma for several days. He was 46. 
</P>
<P>
	He was suffering from a muscle disease.  
</P>
<P>
	His most popular works include ``East of the River Nile,''  
``Java,'' and ``Baby, I Love You.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pablo, whose real name was Horace Swaby, recently released his  
latest album, Valley of Jehosophat. 

</P>
<P>
                        *William Munn Rawland    	
</P>
<P>
	CLEBURNE, Texas (AP) -- William Munn Rawland, the owner and  
publisher of the Cleburne Times-Review for three decades, died 
Wednesday. He was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawland was president of the Texas Press Association in 1952-53  
and a committee chairman for the Texas Daily Newspaper Association 
and the Southern Newspaper Publishers Association. 
</P>
<P>
	He began his newspaper career as a bookkeeper for Waco-based  
Newspapers Inc. After just two months, he transferred to the 
Cleburne Times-Review as a cashier and bookkeeper in 1933. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1940, he and his father-in-law, Walter Murray, bought the  
paper. Rawland bought his father-in-law's share in 1947. 
</P>
<P>
	He remained as sole owner, publisher and general manager until  
he sold the paper to the Donrey Media Group in 1976 and became 
publisher emeritus. 
</P>
<P>
	He and Murray also bought controlling stock of the Cleburne  
National Bank, where Rawland was a director until selling shares 
back to his father-in-law. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawland was president of the Cleburne Chamber of Commerce in  
1942 and a city alderman in 1958-1964, serving for a time as mayor 
pro-tem. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawland is survived by his wife, Peggy; three daughters, three  
stepchildren, 13 grandchildren and 12 great-grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Laurence E. Richardson    	
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) -- Laurence E. Richardson, founder of  
the Virginia News Network and president of Charlottesville 
Broadcasting Corp., died Wednesday at age 79. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson began working for WTOP-TV in Washington in 1948. He  
became president of the station in 1964. In 1970 he bought WINA and 
WQMZ-FM, which with WKAV-AM make up Charlottesville Broadcasting. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson was inducted into the Virginia Communications Hall of  
Fame in 1991. He received the George Mason Award from the Society 
of Professional Journalists and the Robert S. Gallimore 
Distinguished Service Award from the Virginia Associated Press 
Broadcasters. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, Catharine, and four children.  

</P>
<P>
                          *Donald K. White    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Donald K. White, a former newspaper  
business writer and editor, died Tuesday of pulmonary disease. He 
was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	White, who had hoped to be a doctor, abandoned his premed  
studies at the University of San Francisco when he was asked to 
dissect a frog. 
</P>
<P>
	He quit school and worked for the El Paso Times, the Sacramento  
Union and the Humboldt Star in Winnemucca, Nev. 
</P>
<P>
	White returned to San Francisco as a business writer for the  
Wall Street Journal, San Francisco Chronicle and San Francisco 
Examiner. 
</P>
<P>
	After 13 years as business editor at the Examiner, he joined the  
Crocker Bank as vice president for advertising and public 
relations, then returned to the Chronicle in 1974 as business 
editor and columnist. 
</P>
<P>
	His columns often featured a middle-class San Francisco couple  
named George and Adele, who lived in the Marina with their poodle, 
Sir. White used the couple as a column device for more than 30 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	White retired in 1989. He is survived by his wife, Donna  
Balzarini; a son; and a brother. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Jerome Jay Wolken    	
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Jerome Jay Wolken, a Carnegie Mellon  
University biophysicist who invented a lens system that gave sight 
to some legally blind people, died May 10 at age 82. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Wolken's patents for his Light Concentrating Lens System  
involved a pear-shaped lens 10 times more sensitive to light than a 
standard camera lens. 
</P>
<P>
	The lens system developed in the 1980s is used in eyeglasses. It  
reproduced the lenses in deep-sea creatures' eyes that they use to 
see at depths of up to 1,500 feet in almost total darkness. People 
with cataracts were the main beneficiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolken researched deep-sea optics at the Marine Biological  
Laboratory and the Oceanographic Research Institute at Woods Hole 
on Cape Cod, Mass., as well as similar institutions in Miami, 
Bermuda, the Bahamas, Europe and Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolken taught at the University of Pittsburgh in the 1950s and  
was named a professor of biophysics biology in 1962. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years later, Carnegie Mellon appointed him a professor and  
head of the biological sciences department at Morrison Carnegie 
College. He wrote nine books in his field and edited two others in 
additions to contributing many papers to scientific journals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
