<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Finish Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar edged higher against the yen Thursday  
following the release of a central bank report showing the nation's 
economy remains weak. Japanese stocks finished higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 124.44 yen at midafternoon, up 0.74 yen from  
late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 
124.21 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 71.81 points,  
or 0.44 percent, closing at 16,199.99. On Wednesday, the index fell 
250.44 points, or 1.53 percent. Before Thursday's rise, the Nikkei 
had lost 819.19 points over the previous five full trading days. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar's strength was boosted by the  
Bank of Japan's latest monthly report saying that the economy 
appears to have stopped deteriorating, but that no signs of 
recovery can yet be seen. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Japanese companies are still struggling to bail out of the  
nation's worst recession in 50 years, mostly through restructuring 
efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also noted that the yen has weakened recently on the  
back of the interest rate differential between the United States 
and Japan. U.S. rates are higher. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the dollar rose to a seven-month high against the  
yen, trading above 124 yen. Higher interest rates make a nation's 
currency more attractive to investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar stayed in a narrow range in afternoon trading as  
market participants were taking a rest after somewhat volatile 
trading in the morning. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 132.90 yen, up from  
131.60 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices opened moderately higher on buying  
of shares in technology companies but turned lower at midday as 
investors sold shares of companies whose earnings are linked to 
strength in domestic demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said investors turned bearish on worries that Japan's  
economy is not gaining momentum and frustration that the government 
appears reluctant to push new stimulus measures anytime soon. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Nikkei average moved into positive territory within 30  
minutes of the closing bell as institutional investors picked up 
selective shares on dips. 
</P>
<P>
	Overnight in New York, the Dow Jones industrial average gained  
50.44 points to close at 10,887.39 on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 1.26 points, or 0.10 percent, to 1,301.87. The 
TOPIX fell 23.54 points, or 1.78 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.295 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.325 
percent, driving its price up to 101.82 yen from 101.55 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
