<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Mostly Mixed in Quiet Trading / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bonds were mixed in quiet trading Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 5/16  
point, or $3.13 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in 
the opposite direction, rose to 5.83 percent from 5.80 percent late 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Other parts of the Treasury market fared better Thursday, ending  
little changed from the levels of late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The long-term Treasury has been gyrating following a report  
Friday of a surprisingly big increase in inflation at the consumer 
level during April. Yields Friday rose to 5.92 percent, the highest 
level in a year, amid worries that rising prices would lead the 
Federal Reserve to push up interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Inflation eats into the value of investments, such as bonds,  
that promise periodic fixed payments to investors. Rising interest 
rates make returns less attractive on existing bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices of short-term Treasury securities ranged from a drop of  
1/32 point to a gain of 1/32 point, and intermediate maturities 
ranged from a rise of 1/32 point to a decline of 1/16 point, 
reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.60 percent as the  
discount was unchanged from Wednesday at 4.48 percent. Six-month 
yields were 4.75 percent, as the discount fell 0.01 percentage 
point to 4.57 percent. One-year yields were 4.85 percent as the 
discount fell by 0.01 percentage point to 4.62 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.75 percent from 4.50 percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds ended at 122 1/32, unchanged from late 
Wednesday. The average yield to maturity was flat at 5.36 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 12:42:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Set To OK Kosovo-Aid Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite conservatives' discontent, the Senate  
moved Thursday toward final congressional approval of a $15 billion 
package financing the fighting in the Balkans, aid to hurricane 
victims and a stew of projects for lawmakers' home districts. 
</P>
<P>
	At the White House, President Clinton said he would sign the  
legislation ``as soon as it gets here'' and urged lawmakers to rush 
it to him. Until last week, administration officials had threatened 
a veto because Congress doubled the defense spending Clinton sought 
and included provisions on mining, fishing and tobacco that he 
opposed. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some things in the bill that I did not support,''  
the president said. ``But it is terribly important that this aid be 
released as soon as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House approved the compromise measure Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Conservatives lambasted the package because it is stuffed with  
local provisions that they said were hardly the emergencies the 
bill proclaims them to be. These included $250,000 to help 
revitalize a downtown Los Angeles neighborhood; $2 million to 
intensify security at the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum in 
Washington, D.C.; and increased federal payments to some 
northwestern wheat farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The freight train has stowaways hidden all the way through,''  
said Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark. 
</P>
<P>
	They also complained that all but $2 billion of the measure's  
price tag would come from this year's federal surplus, which comes 
completely from Social Security -- money Republicans have pledged to 
leave alone. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should not use Social Security to pay for a war in the  
Balkans,'' said Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash. 
</P>
<P>
	Defenders focused on the bill's $12 billion -- twice Clinton's  
request -- for the conflict with Yugoslavia, the Kosovar refugees, 
Balkan countries near the fighting and U.S. forces around the 
globe. They said rejecting the package would hurt American troops 
in combat -- something few lawmakers want to be accused of doing. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to watch how you vote on this bill, and they  
should,'' said Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted 
Stevens, R-Alaska, referring to members of the U.S. armed forces. 
``This is not the time for petty differences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The reluctance of senators to block the package was underscored  
when an effort by Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, to pay for more of the 
bill by cutting most domestic programs failed, 70-30. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's Senate debate marked the culmination of a process  
that began in February, when Clinton asked Congress for nearly $1 
billion to help Central American and Caribbean nations recover from 
last fall's two deadly hurricanes, Mitch and Georges. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislation providing that aid was passed by the House and  
Senate in March. But it languished until congressional leaders 
decided to use it to rush Clinton defense money and a host of other 
items the measure collected in its sojourn through Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Along the way, the measure picked up $900 million so the  
government could help victims of this month's killer tornadoes in 
the Midwest and be prepared for other natural disasters yet to 
come. The bill also has $574 million to help American farmers, 
mainly those facing low prices for hogs, wheat and other 
commodities. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan, one of America's Middle East allies, would get $100  
million for its role in helping to arrange the Wye River peace 
accord between Israel and the Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	Backed by all 50 governors, Republicans won a provision barring  
the federal government from claiming any of the $246 billion the 
states have won from tobacco companies in a legal settlement. 
Clinton wanted to use some of that money for health care and 
anti-smoking initiatives. 
</P>
<P>
	In defeats for the environmental lobby, the measure also has  
language delaying tighter restrictions on mining companies using 
government lands. Higher royalties on oil companies that drill on 
federal property would also be postponed. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would allow House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt,  
D-Mo., and House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, an additional 
$333,000 a year each for office expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens successfully inserted language making reindeer ranchers  
eligible for a $70 million program helping livestock producers. And 
there is $2.3 million for the government to temporarily house in 
Calverton, N.Y., the wreckage of TWA Flight 800, which crashed off 
Long Island in July 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
