<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibit Traces Watercolors' Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- From the rain-soaked battlefields of the Civil  
War where he worked as an illustrator for Harper's Weekly, Winslow 
Homer created the foundation of an art career that spanned 50 years 
and led some to declare him America's ``national'' painter. 
</P>
<P>
	He painted first in oils, then in watercolors, and it's the  
latter for which he is best-known today. ``You will see, in the 
future I will live by my watercolors,'' he once said. 
</P>
<P>
	A New Englander with a panache for depicting coastal life, Homer  
shares the walls of the Terra Museum of American Art with a host of 
other watercolorists, including famed portraitist John Singer 
Sargent, in the museum's newest exhibit, ``Masters of Color and 
Light: Homer, Sargent and the American Watercolor Movement.'' It 
runs through July 4. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is literally a once-in-a-generation exhibition,'' John  
Hallmark Neff, the museum's curator and director, said as he 
explained the watercolors' extreme sensitivity to light. ``After 
this, they'll go back into their boxes in deep storage, and they 
won't come out for a very long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many of these 140 paintings were briefly displayed at the  
Brooklyn Museum of Art last year where they were a surprise 
blockbuster hit with art patrons. This showing, a mere eight weeks, 
is the second and last before the collection is locked away for 
another decade or more, museum officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibition, which covers more than 200 years, is a study in  
contrasts -- from Homer's ``The Turtle Pound'' to Sargent's ``Arab 
Gypsies in a Tent'' through Georgia O'Keeffe's abstract ``Blue 1.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Naturalists were some of the first painters to use watercolor  
because its transparent and translucent nature makes it effective 
at capturing the subtleties of outdoor light and atmosphere. Their 
works fill a small corner of the gallery and pay tribute to 
America's natural wonders from the Catskills to Virginia's Natural 
Bridge. 
</P>
<P>
	Couched among pictures of delicate apple blossoms and a dancing  
Isadora Duncan are a few heavily gilded frames. Their thick, dark 
colors seem out of place on the Terra Museum's walls. 
</P>
<P>
	Called ``exhibition watercolors,'' these works of art were  
painted when watercolor, which was considered secondary to oil, was 
fighting for its place in the world of art and commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	Claude Raguet Hirst's ``The Bookworm's Table'' is one such  
showpiece. The details -- the rich mahogany wood, the glint of light 
bouncing off a blue vase -- are clear and precise. Edwin Austin 
Abbey's ``Stony Ground'' is another. 
</P>
<P>
	Watercolor, once considered the domain of women, eventually  
triumphed over its American naysayers. With the help of the 
American Watercolor Society, it was elevated from a sketching tool 
to being declared the ``American medium'' by some art lovers. 
</P>
<P>
	But even those who mastered its techniques didn't always share  
their enthusiasm. Sargent didn't show his watercolors publicly 
until about 1900, and then only to distance himself from his 
previous work as a society portraitist. 
</P>
<P>
	Art historians counter that Sargent's tight control on the sale  
of his watercolors -- requiring them to be kept together for public 
exhibition -- proves he valued them. It also explains how 83 of his 
86 watercolors ended up in the hands of the Brooklyn Museum of Art, 
the organizer of the Terra exhibit. 
</P>
<P>
	``His watercolors were mostly for himself,'' Neff said. ``He got  
very sick of doing those portraits. The joy in his watercolors is 
quite amazing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
