<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Woman Taken Off Life Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Paralyzed by a bullet to her spine and  
barely able to speak, Georgette Smith nevertheless was able to make 
her point unmistakably: She didn't want to live this way. 
</P>
<P>
	She died Wednesday, one day after a court granted her wish and  
gave her permission to disconnect the ventilator that was keeping 
her alive. 
</P>
<P>
	For her family, the ordeal is far from over. Her frail and aging  
mother, already charged with shooting Ms. Smith, now may be charged 
with her murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Smith, 42, was shot in March, the bullet tearing through her  
neck and spinal cord and leaving her unable to speak without 
effort, incapable of swallowing and unable to control her bladder. 
She was fed through a tube and ran a high risk of pneumonia, 
infections, ulcers and bedsores. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I can do is wink my eyes and wiggle my nose, wiggle my  
tongue. I can't move any other part of my body,'' she said in court 
papers. ``I can't live like this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The judge ruled in her favor Tuesday and said she could have  
life support removed after 5 p.m. Wednesday. She died at 5:46 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	A Lucerne Medical Center spokeswoman would not say what time the  
ventilator was disconnected, but said Ms. Smith was sedated 
beforehand. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Smith's daughters, Candace Smith, 22, and Joeleen Hill, 19,  
had supported their mother's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's prepared herself,'' Candace Smith said in court last  
week, ``because she knows she's lived a good life and she doesn't 
want to finish her life in this way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before her death, Ms. Smith gave prosecutors a videotaped  
deposition from her hospital bed. It will be among the evidence 
against her 68-year-old mother, Shirley Egan, who is already jailed 
on an attempted murder charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though Ms. Smith made the decision to die, prosecutors were  
likely to charge Ms. Egan with murder, creating a highly unusual -- 
and perhaps unprecedented -- case. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan, an 85-pound woman who is blind in one eye, allegedly  
shot her daughter after overhearing her and her boyfriend talking 
about putting Ms. Egan in a nursing home. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan's attorney has said she did not mean to shoot her  
daughter and didn't want to see her suffer. But he argued against 
removing Ms. Smith from the ventilator because prosecutors had said 
they would seek a murder indictment against Ms. Egan. 
</P>
<P>
	Legal experts said the prosecutors were within their duties to  
upgrade the charge. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that's sound law,'' said Milwaukee County District  
Attorney E. Michael McCann, who prosecuted serial killer Jeffrey 
Dahmer. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors have upgraded charges to murder when comatose  
victims have died after family members decided to take them off 
life support. But Robert Moffat, a law professor at the University 
of Florida, said this case is unique because Ms. Smith made the 
choice herself. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong case could be made that the cause of Ms. Smith's death  
was the removal of life support, not being shot, said Andrew 
Kayton, legal director of the American Civil Liberties Union of 
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be an important legal issue -- whether the mother's  
shooting was the legal cause of death,'' Kayton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 14:53:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Candidates Debate Over Gun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- The gun control debate among  
presidential candidates was fueled by the latest school shooting 
episode Thursday, with demands for tough new restrictions mixed 
with calls for caution. 
</P>
<P>
	New polling showing increased support for gun control  
initiatives was certain to warm that debate even further. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore voted to break a Senate tie and approve  
fresh restrictions on gun transactions. ``This is a turning point 
for our country,'' Gore said in touting his vote, which drew a 
congratulatory call from President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	But former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's only announced  
rival for the Democratic nomination, scornfully said White House 
gun control initiatives ``are minimums'' and much stronger actions 
must be taken. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before this is over, we are going to have to do something much  
stronger,'' said Bradley, at a news conference while campaigning in 
Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley said he was formulating a proposal on the issue and  
would offer that ``sooner rather than later.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Stay tuned,'' said Bradley. ``I have some ideas but not for  
this morning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley declined reporters' invitations to take a direct shot at  
Gore for not being aggressive enough on the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think all of us should be more aggressive,'' said Bradley.  
``It isn't a matter of one person.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said Gore believes ``there's no one  
answer to helping to protect our kids'' but the new restrictions 
will help. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to do everything we possible can from availability of  
guns and today's tie-breaking vote in the Senate is a good step in 
that direction,'' Lehane said. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side of the aisle, some Republican contenders took  
care to note they do not flatly oppose gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since I first started running for office, I've been for  
background checks, instant background checks,'' said Texas Gov. 
George W. Bush. ``I think background checks are important to make 
sure that guns don't get in the hands of felons and-or people who 
shouldn't be carrying guns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aides to Elizabeth Dole noted that she began calling for gun  
control three weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``She did it first,'' said spokesman Ari Fleischer. ``She did it  
when it wasn't popular.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Kasich of Ohio noted that he voted for a ban on  
assault weapons and ``there's some legitimate tightening we can 
do.'' He urged caution, however. 
</P>
<P>
	``We look at gun control as a way to pass three laws and think  
we've fixed the problem,'' Kasich said. ``I'm going to look at 
additional restrictions that make sense, but I'm going to be very 
careful about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aides to former Dan Quayle said the former vice president  
preferred to focus on what he sees as declining cultural values 
that are the root cause of school violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dan Quayle believes there's one issue and that's the  
culture,'' said spokesman Jonathan Baron. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Schmidt, a spokesman for former Education Secretary Lamar  
Alexander, said Alexander favored some restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	``He would sign legislation requiring background checks at gun  
shows,'' said Schmidt, who said Alexander opposes ``unreasonable'' 
restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	The candidates spoke hours after the latest school shooting  
episode at a suburban Atlanta high school, where six students were 
wounded, and after the Senate approved new gun restrictions it had 
rejected just last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``It adds another impetus for doing something very significant  
on gun control,'' said Bradley. ``The things that have been 
proposed by the White House are minimums.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Publisher Steve Forbes, seeking the GOP nomination, said he  
would focus on the school shooting issue during a speech Saturday 
to the Georgia Republican Convention. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe there are some real and important steps local, state  
and national leaders can and must take to keep our kids safe and 
bring real discipline and values back into our classrooms,'' Forbes 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Bush announced a $420,000 grant to create a Texas  
School Safety Center to examine ways of curbing violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is obviously a part of the American tragedy that children  
are coming to school and shooting people and our society has got to 
do everything we can to figure out ways to prohibit violence,'' 
Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a new poll released by the Pew Research Center for  
the People &AMP; Press indicated that large majorities of Democrats and 
of Republican women were more inclined to say it was more important 
to control gun ownership than to protect the rights of gun owners. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll was taken before the Georgia shootings. Other surveys  
taken after the deadly shooting spree in Littleton, Colo., showed 
public support for gun control elevated by the school incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
