<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Says Dole Supports Wife's Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful John McCain  
wants to thank his old friend Bob Dole for his offer of support 
this week, but he has not been able to get in touch with him. 
</P>
<P>
	``They haven't installed a phone in his woodshed,'' McCain  
deadpanned in speech Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole raised eyebrows in the political world this week when he  
said he was not sure his wife, Elizabeth Dole, would continue her 
pursuit of the Republican nomination, and that he was considering 
donating to McCain's campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain said he thought Dole's comments were taken ``out of  
context'' and that there was no lack of support for his wife's bid 
for the GOP nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``I in no way interpreted that as any erosion of his leadership,  
his advocacy, or his desire to see Elizabeth Dole as the nominee of 
our party,'' McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	And despite his several runs for the presidency, McCain noted  
that, Dole still had ``his desire to be 'First Man'.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
