<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Trade Deficit Hits Record High  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States monthly trade deficit soared  
to a record high for the third straight month in March as the 
politically sensitive deficit with Japan shot up to the highest 
level in more than four years. The Commerce Department said today 
that the March deficit of $19.7 billion was 2.9 percent higher than 
the previous record of $19.1 billion in February. So far this year, 
the U.S. trade deficit is running at an annual rate of $222.6 
billion, nearly one-third higher than the all-time high of $169.3 
billion set last year as the global financial crisis continues to 
wreck havoc with America's trade performance. 

</P>
<P>
	Jobless Claims Fall by 12,000  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New claims for unemployment insurance fell by  
12,000 to 299,000 last week, according to numbers released this 
morning by the Labor Department. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Move Higher; Dow Up 38.34  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved higher today as the market weighed  
the meaning of two new economic reports. Just before 11 a.m. EDT, 
the Dow Jones industrial average was up 38.34 at 10,925.73. Broader 
stock indicators also posted slim gains. The Nasdaq composite index 
was up 4.06 at 2,581.46. A rising trade deficit may have turned 
some investors away from the market. The Commerce Department said 
today the nation's monthly deficit rose to a record high in March, 
led by a widening gap with Japan. However, the Labor Department's 
report on weekly jobless claims indicated the U.S. economy remains 
strong. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 11 a.m. EDT:  
Dow Industrials:        10925.73  + 38.34
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1667  Declines  809  Unchgd  572
NYSE Volume:         178,812,730
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online 134 7/16  -   1/16
S&AMP;P 500:         1347.93  + 3.70
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          793.58  + 5.22
Nasdaq Composite Index:       2581.46  + 4.06
Gold(final) -    $274.60    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan Backs U.S. Reform Efforts  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told  
Congress today that Fed policy-makers support Clinton 
administration efforts to make the global financial system less 
susceptible to future Asian-style currency crises. Greenspan and 
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin sounded the same reform themes in a 
joint appearance before the House Banking Committee. They outlined 
steps policy-makers have taken to deal with the 22-month-long 
crisis that has plunged one-third of the global economy into 
recession. Rubin mentioned steps to strengthen rules to encourage 
greater financial disclosure by developing countries and to put 
into place guidelines that will discourage these countries from 
taking too many risks when they borrow money. 

</P>
<P>
	Barclays To Cut 6,000 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Barclays Bank PLC plans to slash 6,000 jobs,  
almost 10 percent of its work force, in a cost-cutting move aimed 
at countering sagging profits and widespread doubts about the 
future of Britain's third-largest bank. Barclays said today it 
hopes the job cuts will help it save more than $320 million a year. 
The cuts will come mostly in the form of voluntary resignations and 
retirements by workers in its retail branches and corporate lending 
areas, the bank said. At the same time, Barclays plans to 
computerize and centralize more of its operations in a 
restructuring program set to cost almost $650 million. 

</P>
<P>
	European Interest Rates Unchanged  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The European Central Bank left its key  
interest rate unchanged at 2.5 percent at its regular meeting 
today, as was widely expected. The bank cut the rate by half a 
percentage point April 8, the first reduction since it took over 
monetary policy for the 11 European Union nations that adopted the 
euro currency on Jan. 1. 

</P>
<P>
	$725M Deal Reached in Vitamin Probe  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two major drug and chemical companies have  
reached an agreement with federal prosecutors to pay a record $725 
million settlement of allegations that they engaged in a worldwide 
conspiracy to raise and fix the prices of vitamins, according to 
lawyers familiar with the case. The total settlement will top the 
$100 million paid in 1997 by Archer Daniels Midland Co., the U.S. 
agribusiness giant, for its role in fixing prices for two food 
additives, lysine and citric acid, according to a Justice 
Department official who requested anonymity. In the settlement, 
Roche Holding AG of Switzerland agreed to pay $500 million, and 
BASF AG of Germany agreed to pay $225 million, officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	Arbitrator Rules Against Disney  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Walt Disney Co. breached its contract  
with former film boss Jeffrey Katzenberg in 1994 and owes him a 
potentially huge interest payment on top of what could be a sizable 
bonus, an arbitrator ruled yesterday. The case now moves to another 
phase in which the referee, retired Superior Court Judge Paul G. 
Breckenridge, considers more testimony to determine exactly how 
much money Disney should pay Katzenberg, who has contended he's due 
at least $250 million in an incentive bonus. If Katzenberg's final 
bonus ends up being close to what he wants, the compounded interest 
could be worth tens of millions of dollars. Disney stock was up 
1/16 at 30 this morning. 

</P>
<P>
	Survey: Microsoft Browser Winning  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new survey purports to show that Microsoft  
is winning the Internet browser war in the nation's offices, 
traditionally the domain of its software rival, Netscape. Zona 
Research Inc. said almost 60 percent of 308 companies in its new 
survey now use Microsoft's Internet browser, an important trend 
that could be a Pyrrhic victory for the software giant. Microsoft 
Corp.'s aggressive push to persuade consumers to use its Internet 
software rather than one from Netscape Communications Corp. is at 
the core of the government's antitrust case against Microsoft, 
scheduled to resume June 1. 

</P>
<P>
	Cablevision, Devils Join Forces  
</P>
<P>
	HOBOKEN, N.J. (AP) -- The New Jersey Devils have a partner in  
their plan to build a new arena in Hoboken: Cablevision. The cable 
television company, which already owns Madison Square Garden as 
well as the New York Knicks and Rangers, has agreed to bear half of 
the $206 million cost to construct the new venue above the Hoboken 
commuter rail station, Devils president John McMullen said 
Wednesday night. The plan would still need some public subsidies, 
and Hoboken officials are worried about crowded streets and a 
parking shortage. Still, McMullen called the plan ``an outstanding 
opportunity'' for the state. 

</P>
<P>
	Taiwan Chemical Giant To Make Cars  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Formosa Plastics Group, Taiwan's largest  
business conglomerate, said Thursday it will invest $2 billion to 
make electric cars and auto parts, primarily for export. Chairman 
Wang Yung-ching said the chemical giant hopes to capitalize on 
lower tariffs on Taiwanese cars following Taiwan's admission by the 
World Trade Organization, which is expected late this year. The 
group chose to make electric cars because Taiwan's conventional car 
production has fallen too far behind other countries for it to 
catch up, Wang said. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Trade deficit: up 2.9 percent to $19.7 billion  
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims: down 12,000 to 299,000  

</P>
