<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arbitrator Rules Against Disney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Walt Disney Co. owes former film division  
chief Jeffrey Katzenberg a potentially huge incentive bonus, plus 
interest, for his role in creating smash hits like ``The Lion 
King,'' an arbitrator ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	Retired Superior Court Judge Paul Breckenridge issued his  
decision Wednesday and will next hear testimony to determine 
exactly how much money Disney should pay. 
</P>
<P>
	Katzenberg, who left Disney in 1994 after he was denied a  
promotion, is suing Disney for what he says is at least $250 
million from an incentive bonus promised in his contract. 
</P>
<P>
	He claims the bonus is worth 2 percent of all future profits  
from every Disney product -- from such blockbuster movies as ``The 
Lion King'' and ``Aladdin'' to T-shirts and games -- generated 
during his decade with the company. 
</P>
<P>
	If the bonus ends up being close to what Katzenberg wants, the  
compounded interest could be worth tens of millions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	In his ruling, Breckenridge found that Disney breached  
Katzenberg's contract on Oct. 1, 1994, and ``was obligated to pay a 
post-termination bonus'' with interest. In addition to the amount 
of the bonus, the judge left undecided the date from which the 
interest should start accruing. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge also decided that Katzenberg's bonus should include  
profits from merchandise sold in Disney stores and at theme parks. 
</P>
<P>
	In rulings for Disney, the judge found that Katzenberg was not  
entitled to any bonus money from profits at the three Club Disney 
play centers, and restricted the amount of money that could come 
from Disney's on-line service. 
</P>
<P>
	Katzenberg's lawyers declined to comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Disney had argued that Katzenberg forfeited his bonus because he  
left two years before the end of his six-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	The parties reached a partial settlement, but most of the terms  
have been placed under seal. What is known is that Disney has 
already paid Katzenberg some money -- more than $100 million, 
according to sources. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement authorized Breckenridge to resolve disputes on  
whether certain products fall under the bonus, and the exact value 
of that bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	The proceeding has been portrayed as the messy aftermath of the  
disintegration of a Hollywood power marriage, with the trial 
turning into a bitter personal battle between Katzenberg and his 
former boss, Disney Chairman Michael Eisner. 
</P>
<P>
	In an extraordinarily unusual airing of Hollywood grievances,  
Katzenberg argued the dispute boiled down to Eisner's animosity 
toward him. 
</P>
<P>
	Eisner, under questioning by Katzenberg's lawyer, acknowledged  
he may have once said of Katzenberg, ``I think I hate the little 
midget.'' But he said that remark and other statements were 
probably made in anger after Katzenberg left the company. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 00:51:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Microsoft Browser Winning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new survey purports to show that Microsoft  
is winning the Internet browser war in the nation's offices, 
traditionally the domain of its software rival, Netscape. 
</P>
<P>
	Zona Research Inc. said almost 60 percent of 308 companies in  
its new survey now use Microsoft's Internet browser, an important 
trend that could be a Pyrrhic victory for the software giant. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Corp.'s aggressive push to persuade consumers to use  
its Internet software rather than one from Netscape Communications 
Corp. is at the core of the government's antitrust case against 
Microsoft, scheduled to resume June 1. 
</P>
<P>
	A Zona survey in October -- which was cited as evidence in the  
trial -- indicated that 60 percent of companies used Netscape's 
software. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft lawyer John Warden told the judge that the earlier  
survey ``completely undermines the government's case.'' Lawyers 
also cited the earlier results two other times as they challenged 
government witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	But the new survey of 308 corporate technology professionals  
showed that 59 percent identified Microsoft's browser as the one 
they ``personally use the most at work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The results put Microsoft in the awkward position of playing  
down a survey that trumpets the company's own success. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft spokesman Jim Cullinan argued that the results show  
only which browser the professionals used personally, not 
necessarily which browser was used by all employees. 
</P>
<P>
	But the survey also said more than two-thirds of the companies  
encourage or require all employees to use specific Internet 
software, and that of those, 62 percent encourage or require the 
use of Microsoft's browser over Netscape's. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is simply offering choice, and the best product  
winning,'' Cullinan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics said the results support the government's allegations.  
</P>
<P>
	``It reconfirms the underlying facts of the case, and the  
problems and the tactics shown,'' said Ed Black, president of the 
Computer and Communications Industry Association, a trade group 
that has been critical of Microsoft. ``Microsoft has always made 
the point, you have to have real damage (to Netscape). Here's 
obviously real damage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Netscape early on targeted companies as its prime market for  
browser sales. Companies' software managers recognized Netscape as 
an Internet pioneer, and a 1996 Zona survey found more than 70 
percent of companies used Navigator. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's Internet Explorer generally has been more popular  
among consumers at home, especially since the company began 
bundling its browser within Windows, the operating system used to 
run most of the world's personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, which released a new version of its browser in March,  
also enjoys unusual popularity for its browser among home consumers 
because America Online distributes Microsoft's Web software to all 
its more than 18 million subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL recently purchased Netscape, but is contractually obligated  
to continue distributing Microsoft's browser until January 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Zona said its survey was taken of 308 randomly selected  
technology professionals who have software purchasing 
responsibilities, and whose companies have at least 20 employees 
and $1 million in revenues. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 21:11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Intel Develops Portable Computer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HILLSBORO, Ore. (AP) -- You may not be able to take a moon  
shuttle or spend a night in space like characters in the movie 
``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' but the kind of thin computer pad they 
carried could be on shelves by the real 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel Corp., the world's largest chip maker, is testing a device  
about the size of an Etch-a-Sketch that taps into the Internet 
without a wire and can be passed around the house from husband to 
wife to kid to check the latest headlines, e-mail, stock quotes and 
even the school lunch menu. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'll have to come out here and pry it out of my hands,''  
said Katherine Cowan, whose suburban Portland family recently 
tested a prototype that designers based loosely on the ``newspad'' 
in the classic 1968 movie. 
</P>
<P>
	She praised the convenience of a computer that can be carried  
from room to room and ``held in your lap like a book or a 
newspaper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Rather than having to go upstairs, start the computer, log  
onto the provider and do a search, I could be on the Internet 
anywhere in the house,'' she said. ``I could do it on the phone, I 
could do it while I was cooking, I could sit on the patio and have 
a glass of wine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Intel Web Pad, which will sell for about $500, has a completely  
different audience than the newspads portrayed in the Stanley 
Kubrick film. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you think about 2001, you have these cute little devices,  
but who's using them? It's the scientists, it's the engineers,'' 
said Walter Bender, assistant director of the Massachusetts 
Institute of Technology media lab. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just the fact that these devices are consumer products now is  
so different from the vision of 2001, and it's so different from 
what people's expectations were even a decade ago,'' Bender said. 
``The computer has way outstripped the imagination of people in the 
'60s, even people like Kubrick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The leader of the Intel development team that created the Web  
Pad says it was designed to be simple as possible to use, yet fast, 
durable with plenty of advanced features that match a desktop 
computer -- without being stuck in one room. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's how people live in their homes, how they communicate,''  
said Ed Arrington of the Intel Architecture Lab, one of the Oregon 
divisions of the Santa Clara, Calif.-based chip maker. 
</P>
<P>
	``We try not to position ourselves as too `out there,'''  
Arrington said. ``This is more real.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analysts doubt the Web Pad will replace the desktop  
computer, noting the test homes had to be wired for a radio 
connection between the pad and a desktop machine with a dedicated 
phone line that gave it round-the-clock access to the Internet. 
Also, there is no keyboard, but users can call up an image of a 
keyboard to type with a special pen. 
</P>
<P>
	``People talk about the age of the conventional PC being over,  
but I don't think that's true,'' said Kurt Scherf, a home network 
analyst for Parks Associates in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	The popularity of the device will depend as much on Internet  
access and security as the technology that goes into the Web Pad, 
added Alexis Gerard, publisher of The Future Image Report, in San 
Mateo, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	If Internet speed and capacity improves as fast, Gerard says  
people will buy something that can call up a digital photo of their 
grandchildren as quickly it can find a recipe for pesto sauce. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were still trying to figure out how to use the computer  
before the Web came along,'' Gerard said. ``But that changed the 
way people looked at the computer, and the way they communicated 
with each other.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 11:22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Monitors Inspect N.Korea Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A 14-member team began inspection of an  
underground facility in North Korea today as the White House 
announced that former Defense Secretary William Perry will lead a 
team of U.S. officials next week to assess progress in the 
communist nation. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department officials confirmed that inspections had begun  
and would be ``open-ended,'' but said results of the inspection -- 
to determine if the facility was being used for nuclear weapons 
development -- would have to be analyzed. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House announcement on the visit by Perry, a  
presidential adviser on North Korean issues, said he would be 
accompanied by Ambassador Wendy R. Sherman, counselor of the State 
Department, and a ``small team of U.S. officials.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The visit is intended to assess views of the communist regime  
first-hand, the announcement said. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James P. Rubin, talking about the  
inspections Wednesday, said, ``The U.S. will have satisfactory 
access to the site in order to remove fully our concerns about the 
nature of the site and the activities of the site.'' He declined to 
identify members of the team, described as technical specialists, 
and said there is no time limit for them to do their work. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately clear whether Perry and his group would  
have any contact with the inspectors. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Rubin criticized new legislation in Congress aimed at  
getting more out of North Korea in exchange for oil shipments and 
food aid under the agreement designed to halt any North Korean 
nuclear weapons development. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the fact that we're getting access ... should take the  
steam out of some of those ill-advised ideas to throw away an 
agreement that has helped us prevent North Korea from becoming a 
major nuclear power threatening our vital national interests ...'' 
Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., chairman of the House  
International Relations Committee, said, ``We should be getting 
more for our money.'' His legislation would limit Clinton's 
discretion in providing aid under the program and impose new 
requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a 1994 agreement, North Korea agreed to curtail its  
nuclear weapons program in exchange for fuel oil for its 
conventional power plants and international assistance for 
developing new nuclear power generators, mostly from Japan and 
South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton requested $55 million in his budget for fiscal year 2000  
for the oil program, up from $35 million last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilman and other congressional critics of the program contend  
North Korea has not lived up to its end, citing concerns over the 
underground facility and other indications that North Korea may be 
developing nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	They have also criticized North Korea's 1998 launch of a  
multistage rocket over Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation it would permit humanitarian food shipments to  
North Korea only if food ``is not diverted to the North Korean 
military and that North Korea is taking steps to regain 
self-sufficiency in food production.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House last year voted to block the oil payments, but they  
were restored in later negotiations with the Senate and the White 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	Reflecting another concern of some Americans, a Massachusetts  
man called The Associated Press on Wednesday to register his 
objection to deals with North Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	Alfred Gregori of Longmeadow, Mass., said his brother, Joseph,  
has been missing in North Korea since he was a 19-year-old soldier 
serving in the Korean War. 
</P>
<P>
	Gregori said his 86-year-old mother, Lena, who lives in West  
Pittston, Pa., is still waiting for word of her son. She still has 
his wardrobe, Purple Heart medal and an American flag given by the 
military, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before she passes away, she would love to know whatever  
happened to my brother,'' Gregori said. He said no aid -- oil or 
food -- should go to North Korea until it accounts for all Americans 
missing from the war. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials say North Korea has been cooperating in efforts  
to account for American soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
