<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lots of Series Finales, but... </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- You and that TV series have had a long, happy  
relationship. But it's clear, the end is near. Which means: series 
finale. 
</P>
<P>
	On a night you greet with wistful resignation, there's the long  
goodbye (last shows are usually fluffed up) ... that parting glance 
through glistening eyes ... then, over and out. 
</P>
<P>
	And then?  
</P>
<P>
	And then the show proceeds to mock you forever in reruns! Old  
series don't die. They don't even fade away! 
</P>
<P>
	Consider CBS' ``The Nanny,'' which recently concluded six  
seasons of sitcom twaddle with the birth of twins and a tearful 
curtain call. But wait! Besides its eternal afterlife in 
syndication, ``The Nanny'' lives on at CBS with several unaired 
episodes (the twins presumably still in the womb) scheduled for 
this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	What else?  
</P>
<P>
	--''Melrose Place,'' which premiered on Fox in July 1992, airs  
its finale Monday at 8 p.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	--''Mad About You,'' which NBC launched two months later, wraps  
with a one-hour special Monday at 9 p.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	--''Home Improvement,'' which debuted on ABC in September 1991,  
has a one-hour conclusion Tuesday at 8 p.m. EDT, followed by a 
half-hour of interviews and outtakes. 
</P>
<P>
	You're not choked up by their imminent leave-taking? You're not  
alone. According to Electronic Media magazine, this season has been 
the ratings nadir for these shows, which ``find themselves limping 
toward the finish line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Far more poignant is the departure of ``Homicide: Life on the  
Street,'' thanks to a death warrant NBC signed only last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Its end wasn't wholly unexpected. Since its beginning in January  
1993, ``Homicide'' has stubbornly resisted hit status, while 
stumbling creatively this season, to boot. 
</P>
<P>
	But what has set ``Homicide'' apart, year in and year out, has  
been its bottomless capacity to surprise, and surprise in the most 
meaningful ways. Prime-time's reigning drama laboratory, 
``Homicide'' never stopped investigating ways to move its audience 
-- and to do TV proud. That should have been enough to win renewal. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's episode, airing at 10 p.m. EDT, now stands as the  
series finale. There's a dark Baltimore street, a shooting death, 
and a closing exchange that hangs in the air long after fadeout: 
</P>
<P>
	``Life is a mystery,'' Detective Sheppard (Michael Michele)  
tells her partner. ``Just accept it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, well,'' grunts Detective Lewis (Clark Johnson), ``that's  
what's wrong with this job: Ain't got nothin' to do with life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, ``Homicide'' had everything to do with life. Now it  
leaves you with this mystery: What new places would the show have 
taken you next season? 
</P>
<P>
	``Melrose Place'' had everything to do with life as it exists in  
a stucco-finished pleasure dome. In that Los Angeles apartment 
complex, the diabolical cohabited with the clueless, and residents 
were oversexed, fabulous and young. 
</P>
<P>
	In its day, ``Melrose Place'' was obligatory viewing, but in  
recent years? Hey, who knew it was even still on? 
</P>
<P>
	While you wait for visual proof in the form of Monday's finale  
(not available for preview), you can see how much ``Melrose'' 
minutiae you recall by entering the ``Win a Piece of the Place'' 
Sweepstakes (www.fox.com). 
</P>
<P>
	Sample questions: Sydney's stage name as a stripper was (a) Sexy  
Syd, (b) Jungle Jane, (c) Loose Laura? Kimberly planted the bombs 
that blew up the Melrose complex (a) on the roof, (b) in the 
laundry room, (c) in Amanda's apartment? 
</P>
<P>
	Win, and you might get a vial of water from the Melrose Place  
pool. It will keep you young forever. 
</P>
<P>
	But the conclusion of ``Mad About You'' may make you feel old.  
</P>
<P>
	A typical finale ties up loose ends and then, with the audience  
duly reassured, fondly sends its heroes off to a graceful tomorrow. 
</P>
<P>
	Not ``Mad.'' Here, a young woman (played by Janeane Garofalo)  
introduces herself as Mabel -- the daughter of Jamie and Paul 
Buchman who, last time you checked, was just a year old. Then, from 
her futuristic vantage point, circa 2030, Mabel recounts what 
happened to her parents in a personal film she calls ``The Reason 
I'm Like This.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to this ambitious but uneven finale, some of what the  
graying Buchmans faced after 1999 is sitcom-silly. Some is -- well, 
disillusioning and maybe more than you really wanted to know. 
</P>
<P>
	Say what you will about the Buchmans, played so richly by Helen  
Hunt and Paul Reiser: They are no fairy-tale couple (apart from 
their Fifth Avenue co-op). When, at hour's end, Mabel declares that 
her parents ``lived happily ever after,'' her assessment rings 
false. After what she has shown you, it's a warm-and-fuzzy 
contradiction. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, ``Mad About You'' goes out echoing the premise with  
which ``Home Improvement'' came in: Men and women should never ever 
live together, because they are two different animals. But inasmuch 
as they do ... how? 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Home'' hour-long finale, a reminiscence clip-job, vividly  
displays the show's nuts and bolts -- power-tools slapstick 
interspersed with marital sparring: 
</P>
<P>
	``You gonna cry through this wedding like you did through  
ours?'' asks Tim (Tim Allen). 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' replies Jill (Patricia Richardson), ``but this time I'm  
happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And for viewers who care, there's a bonus: Wilson's face, long  
obscured by the backyard fence, is finally revealed. As dramatic 
revelations go, that's even beyond the capacity of ``Homicide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	GREATEST COACHES: Chris Berman, one of the original  
``SportsCenter'' anchors, serves as host of a two-hour salute to 
the greatest coaches of the century. The big seven: Red Auerbach, 
Boston Celtics; Bear Bryant, University of Alabama; George Halas, 
Chicago Bears; Vince Lombardi, Green Bay Packers; John McGraw, NY 
Giants baseball; Dean Smith, University of North Carolina; John 
Wooden, UCLA. The program also will announce the Greatest Coach of 
the Century, as voted by the 48-member ``SportsCentury'' panel. It 
airs Saturday at 2 p.m. EDT on ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore ``at'' ap.org  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
