<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds Agree To Lease for New Stadium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- The Cincinnati Reds have agreed to a 30-year  
lease for a new baseball park along the Ohio River that will open 
in 2003, baseball sources confirmed Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Reds owner Marge Schott and managing executive John Allen have  
signed off on the lease, removing the last major hurdle to getting 
the project under way, according to once source familiar with the 
agreement who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Architects are still working on a design for the ballpark, which  
will slightly overlap Cinergy Field. A final drawing is expected 
this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton County and Reds officials declined comment pending an  
announcement Friday morning at Cinergy Field, where the Reds have 
played since 1970. A $403 million stadium project for the 
Cincinnati Bengals is under construction just west of the stadium 
and is expected to be finished for the 2000 NFL season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds' lease agreement, first reported in The Cincinnati  
Post, closely resembles the preliminary deal signed last July, 
which provides the Reds with a 45,000-seat park. The cost of the 
stadium alone is estimated at $297 million, not including land 
acquisition and related expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Signing the stadium lease was one of Schott's final acts as the  
Reds' controlling partner. She agreed to sell all but one of her 6 1/2 
shares to three of the current limited partners for $67 million on 
April 20, ending her 15-year reign. 
</P>
<P>
	Major league baseball has to approve the sale before the team  
switches hands. Cincinnati financier Carl Lindner will become the 
new controlling partner once it is approved. 
</P>
<P>
	County voters approved a half-cent increase in their sales tax  
in March 1996 to build new stadiums for the Bengals and the Reds, 
who have shared Riverfront Stadium/Cinergy Field since 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals reached an agreement with county officials first,  
giving them first choice of a stadium site and getting their 
project underway. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Reds supported a plan to build their stadium between  
Cinergy Field and an arena formerly known as Riverfront Coliseum, 
some residents backed a ballot initiative that would have moved the 
ballpark to a northeast corner of downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	Last November, voters supported the Reds' plans by a nearly  
2-to-1 margin, leaving the lease agreement as the final major step 
in getting the construction process rolling. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen has been running the team since June 1996 while Schott  
serves her latest punishments for inflammatory remarks. She agreed 
to leave him in charge rather than face another suspension while 
negotiating to sell the team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 14:42:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Deficit Hits Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The trade deficit broke a record for the third  
straight month in March as countries struggling to recover from 
economic turmoil continued to unload their products in the United 
States' booming economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until the pace of economic growth in the United States slows  
and the rest of the world picks up, the deficit will continue to 
grow. It is just that simple,'' said David Orr, chief economist 
with First Union Corp., in Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	The March trade deficit of $19.7 billion was 2.9 percent higher  
than the previous record of $19.1 billion set in February, the 
Commerce Department said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, the trade deficit is running at an annual rate  
of $222.6 billion, nearly one-third higher than the all-time high 
of $169.3 billion set last year. 
</P>
<P>
	But there are glimmers of hope for improvement now that some  
countries in Asia and elsewhere have begun a fragile recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. exports, which had fallen for four straight months, staged  
a small rebound in March, climbing by 0.9 percent to $77.5 billion. 
Exports of farm goods were up 2.5 percent, led by rising sales of 
soybeans and corn. Farmers have been among the hardest hit by the 
loss of markets abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, a separate report Thursday showed that steel imports fell  
by 14 percent in April, based on preliminary data, a good sign for 
the country's beleaguered steel industry that has been battered by 
cheap imports. 
</P>
<P>
	However, eager American shoppers -- continuing to enjoy the  
lowest unemployment in nearly three decades and healthy stock 
market gains -- caused overall imports to rise much faster than 
exports, climbing 1.3 percent to a record $97.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of that increase reflected rising oil prices, which jumped  
by nearly $1 dollar a barrel, increasing America's bill for foreign 
crude oil by $213 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In a striking example of the impact of cheaper imports on  
American manufacturers, foreign car imports jumped to an all-time 
high of $14.9 billion in March, a 2.5 percent increase. Meanwhile, 
American car makers saw their exports fall by 2.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration has argued that the trade deficit  
reflects American strength. As the only major world economy doing 
well, the United States plays a valuable role by providing a market 
for countries struggling to emerge from deep recessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Many economists also note that the influx of low-priced imports  
has helped keep U.S. inflation under control. 
</P>
<P>
	``The wide trade deficit may cause some to fret, but given the  
labor shortages in this country, let's be glad there is an outlet 
for our demand,'' said Joel L. Naroff, chief economist with Naroff 
Economic Advisers in Holland, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	However, if the trade deficit gets much worse, Congress may face  
irresistible pressure to erect barriers to protect industries hurt 
by foreign competition. The steel industry has already won a House 
vote to impose global quotas on steel imports into the U.S., 
despite a threatened Clinton veto. 
</P>
<P>
	Commerce Secretary William Daley on Thursday reiterated the  
administration's warnings to Japan and European nations that the 
United States can't go it alone forever and they must take steps to 
improve their domestic demand. 
</P>
<P>
	For March, America's overall trade deficit with Japan shot up  
23.2 percent to $6.5 billion as Japanese imports to the United 
States reached an all-time high. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. trade deficit with the 15-nation European Union,  
meanwhile, soared 30 percent to $2.6 billion. America's deficit 
with Mexico, one of its partners in the North American Free Trade 
Agreement, hit a record $2.5 billion, up 26 percent from the 
previous month. 
</P>
<P>
	The deficit with China declined by 10.5 percent in March to $4.1  
billion, but was still the second largest for any nation. China has 
been negotiating an agreement to lower barriers to American goods 
in hopes it will clear the way for its entry into the World Trade 
Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	However, NATO's mistaken bombing of the Chinese Embassy in  
Yugoslavia and tensions over human rights have threatened any quick 
deal. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
