<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stress, Gulf War Illnesses Linked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Studies of Gulf War veterans with unexplained  
illnesses suggest stress may be a cause, an independent report 
released by the Pentagon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientific studies reviewed by the Rand Corp., the research  
group based in Santa Monica, Calif., provide no proof of the link 
between stress and the illnesses of thousands of Gulf War veterans, 
the Pentagon said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The review was commissioned by the Pentagon, which has struggled  
in recent years to find an explanation for Gulf War veterans 
suffering neurological and other disorders. Many veterans groups 
have dismissed the possibility that combat stress could account for 
the health problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Rand concluded that the available scientific literature shows a  
``generally modest'' association between stress exposure and 
veterans' health problems, although the link was more marked in 
people who saw combat. 
</P>
<P>
	Rand analysts looked at 15 studies evaluating the relationship  
between American troops' exposure to deployment and combat stresses 
during the 1991 war against Iraq and the later development of 
symptoms of post-traumatic stress disorder. The disorder results 
from a trauma associated with actual or threatened death or serious 
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``In sum, the possibility that stress may have either  
contributed to or exacerbated the health problems of some 
(veterans), can neither be ruled out nor proven,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 700,000 men and women served in the war, and an estimated  
2 percent of them have reported symptoms that have eluded 
traditional medical explanation, including chronic fatigue, joint 
pain and memory loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Many are convinced their illnesses may be related to exposure to  
toxins or other chemical or environmental factors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon has been fighting a climate of mistrust regarding  
Gulf War syndrome since the end of the war. Defense officials 
initially played down veterans' complaints and did not fully 
investigate the possibilities of exposure to chemical and 
biological weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon has not ruled out chemical or environmental  
explanations and continues to investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a lot of evidence suggesting stress likely plays a  
role,'' said Matt Puglisi, assistant director of the American 
Legion, the nation's largest veterans' group. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes total sense,'' Puglisi said in an interview  
Wednesday. ``As a human being, we know that stress isn't good for 
you, and ... the Gulf War, although short, was pretty stressful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Puglisi was a Marine Corps artillery officer during the war and  
was stationed in the Gulf region for four months in 1990 and 1991, 
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
