<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Demjanjuk Again Faces Deportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- John Demjanjuk is again facing the loss of his  
U.S. citizenship and deportation, 22 years after he was first 
accused of being ``Ivan the Terrible,'' the infamous guard who 
operated a gas chamber at the Treblinka death camp during World War 
II. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department's Office of Special Investigation filed a  
civil complaint in federal court Wednesday accusing the retired 
79-year-old Cleveland auto worker of participating ``in the process 
by which thousands of Jews were murdered.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is the same agency of Nazi-hunters which was criticized by  
a U.S. appellate court for ``reckless'' withholding of evidence 
that might have cleared Demjanjuk years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint drops the charge that Demjanjuk was Ivan the  
Terrible. It instead alleges that he was a guard at the Sobibor 
death camp in Poland and at the Majdanek and Flossenburg 
concentration camps. It also accuses him of serving in the Nazi-run 
Trawniki unit that participated in a campaign to annihilate the 
Jews of Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1977, Demjanjuk was first accused of operating the gas  
chamber at Treblinka. His U.S. citizenship was revoked in 1981, and 
five years later he was extradited to Israel where he was convicted 
and sentenced to die. 
</P>
<P>
	He returned to the United States in 1993 when evidence indicated  
he was a victim of mistaken identity. Despite overturning his 
conviction in the Ivan the Terrible case, the Israeli Supreme Court 
said it was convinced Demjanjuk had worked for the Nazis during the 
Holocaust. 
</P>
<P>
	With Wednesday's complaint, the case against Demjanjuk is the  
longest-running attempt by the U.S. government to revoke an alleged 
Nazi's citizenship. 
</P>
<P>
	His son-in-law, Ed Nishnic, said the Justice Department was  
unfairly targeting a broke and broken man. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a darn shame that a government with a blank-check  
budget can pick out one person with very limited means and 
basically run him into the ground,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Demjanjuk, a native of the Ukraine in the former Soviet Union,  
has denied serving as a guard in any concentration camp. He has 
said he was a Soviet Red Army soldier who spent most of the war in 
a German prison camp. 
</P>
<P>
	The renewed effort by the Office of Special Investigation won  
praise from Jewish groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Demjanjuk worked at a Cleveland auto plant, he built cars  
for a living. When he served at Sobibor, he killed Jews for a 
living'' said Neal Sher, who headed the OSI from 1983 to 1994 and 
is now head of the International Commission on Holocaust Era 
Insurance Claims. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department will try to have him deported, said  
agency spokesman Myron Marlin. Where Demjanjuk would be sent is 
unknown. 
</P>
<P>
	If deported, Demjanjuk could choose what country he would go to,  
but that nation would have to accept him. Meanwhile, a country that 
wants to bring a criminal case against Demjanjuk can ask at any 
time for his extradition. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether Israel would extradite Demjanjuk again, Elan  
Steinberg, executive director of the World Jewish Congress in New 
York, said: ``I doubt very much whether it would happen as a matter 
of practical reality because of the wrenching effect of the 
previous extradition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli Justice Ministry spokeswoman Orit Shemesh declined to  
comment on the case, saying the issue is for U.S. courts to decide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
