<HEADLINE> Sandy Alomar To Undergo Knee Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Indians catcher Sandy Alomar will have  
arthroscopic surgery Friday to have two bone chips removed from his 
left knee and will be out for at least a month. 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar, who last week said he couldn't remember exactly how many  
knee operations he has had, was placed on the 15-day disabled list 
earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	He had hoped a cortisone injection would get rid of the pain in  
his knee, but it didn't. 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar's knee was examined Thursday, and it was decided he would  
have the operation. Team physician Dr. Louis Keppler will perform 
the procedure at Lutheran Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	With Alomar sidelined, the bulk of the Indians' catching duties  
will fall to rookie Einar Diaz. In 20 games, Diaz is batting .257 
with two home runs and 10 RBIs. Diaz has made the most of his 
at-bats with 11 of his 19 hits going for extra bases. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time you lose an All Star-caliber player you're  
concerned,'' said Mark Shapiro, the team's assistant general 
manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fortunately, one of the strengths of our team thus far, and  
hopefully for the rest of the season, has been our bench. We'll 
look at it as an opportunity to develop Einar further.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Diaz will be backed up by Chris Turner, who was recalled from  
Triple-A Buffalo when Alomar went on the DL. Turner started 
Wednesday night's 13-7 win over the White Sox and went 1-for-5 with 
a single. 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar, 32, was batting .317 with three home runs and 16 RBIs in  
22 games for the Indians, whose 29-10 record is baseball's best. 
</P>
<P>
	The six-time All-Star has been reunited this season on the same  
team with his brother, Roberto, the Indians' starting second 
baseman. 
</P>
<P>
	Following a storybook season in 1997 in which he set offensive  
career-highs, won MVP honors in the All-Star game at Jacobs Field, 
had a 30-game hitting streak and homered off New York's Mariano 
Rivera in the division series, Alomar was limited to 117 games last 
season because of injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	He batted just .235 -- his lowest average since 1991 -- during the  
regular season and went 1-for-16 in the ALCS while playing with 
severe back spasms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
