<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Social Security Fund Plan Revealed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A group of lawmakers on Thursday proposed  
raising new money for Social Security by raising taxes through 
reduced inflation adjustments in the tax code. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan seeks to strike a compromise between Republican desires  
to replace some Social Security benefits with a new system of 
personal retirement accounts and Democrats' concerns about the 
risks of that proposal to low-income workers and women. 
</P>
<P>
	Income taxes raised from trimming back inflation adjustments  
would help pay for the new programs, including subsidies to boost 
the personal retirements accounts of low earners and new benefits 
for women who left the work force to rear children. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters said they hope their plan can help jump-start  
congressional action stalled by political tensions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is precisely because of the growing skepticism that Social  
Security reform will not happen this year that we are pushing,'' 
said Sen. John Breaux, D-La. 
</P>
<P>
	Others endorsing the proposal include Sens. Judd Gregg, R-N.H.,  
Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., Fred Thompson R-Tenn., Craig Thomas R-Wyo., 
Chuck Grassley, R-Iowa, and Chuck Robb, D-Va., and Reps. James 
Kolbe, R-Ariz., and Charles Stenholm, D-Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Some economists argue that the government's traditional measure  
of changes in the cost of living -- the Consumer Price Index -- 
overstates inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Making the measure more conservative is one option President  
Clinton and Republican leaders in Congress have said could be part 
of a solution to the cash shortfall Social Security is expected to 
face when baby boomers retire. 
</P>
<P>
	Previous proposals have focused on the money that could be saved  
by reducing the yearly cost-of-living raises senior citizens get in 
their retirement checks. The plan introduced Thursday would go 
further by also capturing for Social Security any increases in 
income taxes resulting from a partial restoration of so-called 
``bracket creep.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Americans pay income taxes at different rates based on what  
income level, or bracket, they fall into. People in higher brackets 
pay a larger percentage of their income in taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Every year the Internal Revenue Service adjusts the income  
brackets to account for inflation. A more conservative measure of 
inflation would tend to widen the higher tax-rate brackets over 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters say the money that would be raised for Social  
Security over the next 75 years if the CPI's measure of inflation 
were trimmed by one-half of 1 percent could be expected to be about 
the same as if there were a 0.78 percent increase in the special 
payroll taxes now used to finance the retirement program. 
</P>
<P>
	Outright tax hikes, likely to be unpopular, have been sworn off  
by both political parties as a possible solution to Social 
Security's looming problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 16:12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Investigates N. Korea Facility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In two steps aimed at penetrating North Korean  
secrecy, a U.S. team began inspecting a suspected nuclear facility 
there Thursday and the White House announced a visit to the country 
by former Defense Secretary William Perry. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department officials confirmed that long-anticipated  
inspections had begun at an underground site U.S. officials believe 
may be part of a North Korean nuclear weapons program. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials hope Perry will be able to meet with North Korean  
leader Kim Jong Il but have no guarantee of such a meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	His visit, as an envoy of President Clinton, is part of his  
review of U.S. policy toward North Korea. He has been a special 
adviser to Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on 
relations with North Korea. The United States is a close ally of 
South Korea but has no diplomatic relations with North Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James P. Rubin on Wednesday expressed  
confidence that the inspections by a 14-member U.S. team would end 
U.S. concerns about activities at the Kumchangni site and its 
purpose. The facility, first detected by satellite last summer, has 
been a major obstacle to a multinational deal aimed at halting 
North Korea's nuclear weapons development. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional critics of the administration have been pointing  
to Kumchangni as a major example of North Korea's unwillingness to 
cooperate with the rest of the world. U.S. officials still rank the 
peninsula as one of the world's most dangerous trouble spots, 
rating its communist regime as unpredictable. More than 37,000 U.S. 
troops are based in South Korea as a deterrence. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House said Perry would be accompanied by Ambassador  
Wendy R. Sherman, counselor of the State Department, and a small 
team of U.S. officials. They will be in Pyongyang May 25-28 and 
have no plans to meet with the U.S. inspection team, which may 
still be in the country then. 
</P>
<P>
	The visit is intended to assess views of the communist regime  
firsthand, the announcement said. It will be Perry's first 
opportunity to get the views of high-level North Korean officials 
and is part of the review he is expected to complete shortly. 
</P>
<P>
	He is meeting with a range of high-level officials, according to  
a State Department official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
However, the official said he had no list and did not know if the 
contacts would include North Korea's top leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a 1994 agreement, North Korea agreed to curtail its  
nuclear weapons program in exchange for fuel oil for its 
conventional power plants and international assistance for 
developing new nuclear power generators, mostly from Japan and 
South Korea. Clinton requested $55 million in his budget for fiscal 
2000 for the oil program, up from $35 million this year. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department officials expect to hear little from the  
inspection team until its work is finished. With no diplomatic 
mission in Pyongyang, secure communications with the team are 
impossible and any communication is limited. 
</P>
<P>
	No time limit has been set on its inspection activity and  
officials do not expect details of its findings until after the 
inspectors leave the country. Led by Joel Wit, a Korean affairs 
officer at the State Department, the team will return to 
Washington, where officials will evaluate its findings before 
making any statements to Congress or the public. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said they are confident that arrangements made with  
North Korea for the inspection will allow satisfactory access at 
the site in order to get all the information needed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
