<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Hospital Abortions Limited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Armed Services Committee voted  
Wednesday to impose new spending restrictions on President 
Clinton's conduct of the military operation in Yugoslavia. 
Democrats denounced the action as the latest in a series of 
conflicting signals by the Republican-led House. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, working on a $288.8 billion defense spending bill for  
the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1, endorsed a provision stating 
that none of the funds ``may be used for the conduct of combat or 
peacekeeping operations'' in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	A Democratic attempt to block it was rejected on a largely  
party-line 31-27 vote. ``That's a heck of a message to send to that 
23-year-old climbing into the cockpit of an F-16 tonight,'' said 
Rep. Gene Taylor, D-Miss., sponsor of the Democratic effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor noted recent conflicting votes by the full House refusing  
to endorse the air campaign but also rejecting efforts to withdraw 
troops or declare war on Yugoslavia. He said the GOP-sponsored 
language would be interpreted as ``pulling the plug'' on U.S. 
forces there. 
</P>
<P>
	But committee Republicans insisted they were just trying to  
reclaim congressional decision-making over the war powers. 
</P>
<P>
	Committee Chairman Floyd Spence, R-S.C., said the measure would  
force Clinton to come to Congress first to request funds in a 
separate piece of legislation if he wants to continue the military 
campaign beyond Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's wrong with that?'' Spence asked, saying the Pentagon  
budget was ``already overstretched'' by the conflict in the Balkans 
and other overseas missions. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, the panel voted to tighten restrictions on abortions at  
military hospitals, prohibiting them when a pregnancy results from 
the statutory rape of a minor. 
</P>
<P>
	Current law prohibits abortions at military hospitals except to  
save the life of the mother or in cases of incest or rape. 
</P>
<P>
	On a 30-29 vote, the committee agreed to modify that restriction  
to apply only to ``forcible'' rapes instead of all rapes. Rep. 
Steve Buyer, R-Ind., the sponsor said it would prevent federal 
facilities and funds from being used when an underage woman becomes 
pregnant after consensual sex. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel also voted 33 to 26 to retain a 3-year-old prohibition  
barring women who are serving in the military overseas from 
obtaining abortions in U.S. military hospitals -- even if they use 
their own money. That reversed a subcommittee's decision to lift 
the restriction. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans pressed their accusations that the Clinton  
administration had shortchanged long-term Pentagon needs. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill goes next to the full House. A Senate version does not  
include the new abortion restrictions nor the language on 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The House bill is about $8 billion more than requested by  
President Clinton, as is a similar one approved last week by the 
Senate. It pays for virtually all the programs requested by the 
administration and adds millions of dollars to other ones, 
including a 4.8 percent military pay raise. 
</P>
<P>
	It would also authorize the Pentagon to replace the cruise  
missiles it has used in the Kosovo conflict and would seek to speed 
up development of a national missile defense by cutting through 
some bureaucratic paperwork. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, however, put aside a proposal that would have also  
exempted the missile defense program from meeting some 
environmental requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, House and Senate leaders reached agreement on the  
language of a measure to make deployment of a system to protect all 
50 states against a limited ballistic missile attack official U.S. 
policy. 
</P>
<P>
	A final House vote is expected on Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration had originally threatened a veto, but  
now says it favors the Senate-passed bill because it promotes 
continued negotiations with Moscow to reduce nuclear warheads and 
stresses that missile-defense funds must be reviewed annually by 
Congress. The Senate bill also states that the missile defense be 
deployed ``as soon as technologically possible,'' a phrase not 
included in the House bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., chief sponsor of the House version,  
said in an interview he was willing to accept the Senate language 
to get the measure to the president quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like it. It gives political cover to the liberals who  
don't support a missile defense,'' Weldon said. But he said he was 
inclined to support it anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration wants to wait until next June before deciding  
whether to go ahead with such a system. The Pentagon has already 
spend about $50 billion on research and tests on various 
missile-defense proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Army chief of staff, Gen. Dennis Reimer, told the  
Senate Appropriations Committee that the fiscal 2000 defense budget 
Clinton submitted doesn't go far enough -- but will help meet 
essential needs. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying that the Army would probably miss its recruitment goals  
this year by as many as 5,000, Reimer said the most important thing 
was ``to be able to give our soldiers a little more pay, fix their 
retirement system. ... We have to make that happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, the committee chairman, suggested  
that the administration's budget not only shortchanges the 
military, but it complicates the problem with what he said were 
accounting sleights of hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``This budget isn't smoke and mirrors, it's just puff,'' Stevens  
said. ``It's a cloud. It isn't even good smoke.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
