<HEADLINE> Following Campaign Trail to 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore, who made education the  
focus of his first major campaign speech, has picked topic No. 2: 
Faith-based organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	The front-running Democratic presidential candidate plans to use  
the address Monday in Atlanta to discuss how he believes churches 
and other religious organizations can play a larger role in solving 
problems that government is currently trying to tackle, such as 
moving people from welfare to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans, including potential GOP presidential rival Texas  
Gov. George W. Bush, have fought to make it easier for faith-based 
organizations to be involved in the delivery of social services. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he needs any information on the topic, there are many  
success stories in Texas for him to look to,'' Bush spokeswoman 
Mindy Tucker said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore will be in Texas next  
week, though don't look for him to seek any advice from Texas Gov. 
George Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president will join President Clinton for an event  
promoting economic incentives in poor communities. After the 
empowerment zone event Tuesday, the vice president will head to 
Houston and Dallas for to discuss education and raise money. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides are debating whether he should take advantage of his  
proximity to Austin by alluding to Bush during the trip. At best, 
look for something subtle; he is not expected to go on the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A gathering of Georgia Republicans this  
weekend will give GOP presidential hopefuls a chance to shine. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander plans to blast Gore by  
association. Association to Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bill Clinton is the king of moral relativism -- self-absorbed,  
self-indulgent, self-righteous, self-pitying. And he is the man Al 
Gore calls one of our greatest presidents,'' Alexander says in a 
draft of his Friday speech provided to The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``With judgment like that, it is time to ring down the curtain  
on Al Gore's brand of hero-worship -- and the year 2000 is when we 
are going to do it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wealthy businessman Steve Forbes will outline his education  
agenda and offer solutions to the rash of school shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Former American Red Cross president Elizabeth Dole and  
conservative activist Gary Bauer also will attend. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Former vice president Dan Quayle lent  
his support Thursday to a movement aimed at abolishing California's 
car tax. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP presidential candidate, who promises a a 30 percent  
across-the-board federal tax cut if elected, said eliminating the 
Vehicle License Fee could send a signal that would resonate 
nationally, just as California did in 1978 with Proposition 13, the 
successful property tax-cutting initiative. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guarantee that if this passes, they will hear this in  
Washington,'' Quayle told several dozen Republicans and reporters 
gathered on the Capitol steps. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Political writer Ron Fournier, and Scott Lindlaw  
and Douglas Kiker contributed to this package. 
</P>
</TEXT>
