<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Star Wars Breaks Opening Day Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The ``Stars Wars'' prequel ``The Phantom  
Menace'' grossed a record $28.5 million on its opening day, topping 
the single-day box office mark set in 1997 by ``The Lost World: 
Jurassic Park,'' figures showed today. 
</P>
<P>
	The film, whose entire title is ``Star Wars: Episode I -- The  
Phantom Menace,'' collected an average of $9,610 at each of the 
2,970 locations, some of which have been playing the movie 
around-the-clock starting at 12:01 a.m. Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-hour receipts totaling $28,542,349 beat the one-day  
record of $26.1 million set by ``Lost World'' on a Sunday of 
Memorial Day weekend in 1997, according to box office tracker 
Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	It also topped ``Lost World's'' opening-day record of $21.6  
million, set on the Friday of that weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say ``The Phantom Menace'' should gross $100 million to  
$140 million by the end of its five-day opening frame Sunday, 
setting more records. 
</P>
<P>
	The film is so big that some employers decided to not fight the  
Force and just pay to send their workers to theaters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone wants to see this movie, and we thought it would be  
fun to send our whole company,'' said Steven J. Lund, president and 
CEO of Provo, Utah-based cosmetics seller Nu Skin Enterprises. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has reserved a theater for all 1,600 employees and  
one guest each for ``The Phantom Menace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For those who didn't get ``Star Wars'' tickets as a company  
perk, there were long lines outside the nation's theaters, dozens 
of which scheduled around-the-clock showings to accommodate the 
crowds. 
</P>
<P>
	Brad Fyfe, wearing the brown robe of a Jedi master, was shaking  
and nearly unable to speak after emerging from a 3:30 a.m. 
screening Wednesday at Hollywood's Mann's Chinese Theater, where 
the original ``Star Wars'' premiered 22 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to see it again today,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The mainly male, 20-something audience that packed the theater  
for the 12:30 a.m. and 3:30 a.m. shows raved about George Lucas' 
$115 million prequel to the famed ``Star Wars'' series. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was so awesome. I think I'm going to hit double digits, and  
see it at least 10 times,'' said Larry Crouse, 24, who also wore a 
Jedi costume. 
</P>
<P>
	In Waite Park, Minn., Mike Kunkel stood in line for more than 12  
hours to get his ticket to the midnight showing. The 19-year-old 
said he and his friend planned to see the movie repeatedly. 
</P>
<P>
	Sounding like a Jedi master, he summed up his philosophy this  
way: ``The first time to see it. The second time to notice things. 
And the third time to know it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although there were fears of mass labor shortages due to ``Star  
Wars,'' companies with big Force fans -- particularly computer and 
electronics firms -- reported no serious problems, due in part to 
lots of understanding from management. 
</P>
<P>
	At River Park Computer Group, a consulting company in San Jose,  
all five so-called ``home and small office gurus'' said they would 
be pulling a Silicon Valley Skywalker Walk-Out during the next day 
or two, said owner Frank Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're prepared for no one to be here,'' he said. ``I'm going  
myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And at Electronic Theater Controls in Middleton, Wis., about 500  
employees were told they would be bused to downtown Madison for a 
Friday matinee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't call myself a rabid 'Star Wars' fan but I did see  
the original about a dozen times,'' said company president Fred 
Foster, who also had closed down ETC when the first ``Star Trek'' 
movie opened in 1979. The company makes lighting control systems. 
</P>
<P>
	The main problem was how they would handle the phone lines. When  
the company shut down for ``Star Trek'' it was much smaller and 
simply put the phones on hold. Now, with operations in New York, 
Hollywood, Orlando, Dallas, Copenhagen, Rome, London and Hong Kong, 
that might not work so well. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a lot of theater people in our customer base,'' said  
Foster. ``I hope they'll be tolerant of us.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
