<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Lower; Dow Off 20.65 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell Thursday as lingering concerns about  
high-tech companies sapped the modest gains of a market still 
struggling to find a direction. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 20.65 to close at  
10,866.74. The index of blue-chip stocks was higher for much of the 
session, and the decline was concentrated in the final half-hour of 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
dipped 5.40 to 1,338.83, and the technology-dominated Nasdaq 
composite index fell 35.17 to close at 2,542.23. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks have traded in a narrow band for several days as  
investors struggle to determine whether a recent rise in inflation 
will prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates in an 
effort to slow the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Philadelphia Federal Reserve offered fresh evidence Thursday  
that the economy is growing at a steady but not inflationary rate. 
The group reported that manufacturing growth eased slightly in 
April, which calmed an anxious market and set the stage for some 
mild, broad-based gains. 
</P>
<P>
	For a fourth consecutive day, light volume indicated that many  
market players want a clearer picture of the U.S. economy before 
they return to active trading. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the markets are still paying attention to interest  
rates and to unemployment, said Robert Freedman, chief investment 
officer for the John Hancock Funds in Boston. ``People are still 
wondering whether the inflation scare is really something to worry 
about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Without a definitive answer, analysts said investors began  
moving their money from some big-name technology companies that are 
seen as somewhat risky. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell Computer, which disappointed analysts earlier this week  
with a profit report that merely matched expectations, fell again, 
dropping 1 9/16 to 38 1/4 and pulling other computer stocks down with 
it. IBM, one of the Dow stocks, dropped 3 to 232 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet stocks suffered as well. Amazon.com dropped 3 7/8 to 135  
11/16 after the company said it plans to sell $2 billion in stocks 
and bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts said many investors, in search of security, are  
just moving their money to other sectors. Utility stocks, often 
seen as a safe haven, have mostly risen in recent sessions. 
Investors were also seeking bargains in the long-neglected 
small-capitalization stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer products companies, which are seen as relatively immune  
from the economy's ups and downs, also rose Thursday. Procter &AMP; 
Gamble, a Dow component, rose 1 11/16 to close at 96 11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	``Money isn't leaving this market,'' said Larry Wachtel, a  
market analyst at Prudential Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Mergers set the stage for some gains Thursday. Healtheon soared  
20 3/8 to 100 5/8 as it announced it will merge with WebMD Inc. to create 
an Internet-based health care services company. 
</P>
<P>
	Merck was among the Dow's biggest advancers, rising 1 1/2 to 72 as  
it nears approval for a new painkiller. 
</P>
<P>
	Paper and forest products stocks rose after Morgan Stanley Dean  
Witter raised earnings estimates for the group. International Paper 
rose 13/16 to 54 13/16, and Georgia Pacific rose 1 9/16 to 91 7/16. 
</P>
<P>
	And there was room for at least one successful new issue. EToys  
soared from its initial price of 20 to 76 9/16 in its Nasdaq debut. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 0.12 to 639.42. The American Stock  
Exchange composite index rose 3.67 to 792.03, and the Russell 2000 
index of smaller companies rose 1.88 to 448.02. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-5 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 905.9 million shares, 
slightly behind Wednesday's quiet pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume will most likely increase Friday, analysts said, as the  
market faces a ``double witching'' day. Stock and index options are 
both set to expire, which traditionally stimulates volume as 
traders settle their portfolios. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.45 percent.  
European markets were mostly higher, as Germany's DAX index rose 
0.6 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 rose 1.6 percent, and France's 
CAC-40 closed up 1.1 percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
