<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Immunity Sought for WWII Insurers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Imposing sanctions against insurance companies  
that are trying to resolve unpaid claims of families of Holocaust 
victims would undermine the work of an international commission, a 
top State Department official said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat appealed to all state  
insurance commissioners to give insurance companies immunity from 
lawsuits while an international commission tries to move quickly to 
settle Holocaust claims. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe the commission is the best vehicle for resolving  
Holocaust-era insurance claims because it brings together many of 
the interested parties in a cooperative, nonconfrontational 
process,'' Eizenstat said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he was pleased with the decision by the International  
Commission on Holocaust Era Insurance Claims this month in London 
to pay the families of Holocaust victims the real value of their 
life insurance policies to compensate for post World-War II 
currency devaluations. 
</P>
<P>
	Many European Jews bought life or property insurance policies to  
protect their assets in the uncertain days leading up to World War 
II. But thousands of survivors and relatives of those who died 
claim insurers refused to honor policies after the war. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 50,000 to 100,000 Holocaust survivors live in the  
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The international commission, which is headed by former  
Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger, is expected to meet again 
next month in Jerusalem. It includes representatives of the World 
Jewish Congress, the World Jewish Restitution Organization and 
Israeli and U.S. insurance regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Elan Steinberg of the World Jewish Congress said firms that were  
not working with the commission might be subject to sanctions. 
These include Aegon of the Netherlands and Munich RE of Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Eizenstat said five European insurance companies participating  
in the commission have already contributed $90 million toward claim 
resolution and humanitarian issues. The companies are Assicurazioni 
Generali of Italy, Allianz of Germany, AXA of France and Winterthur 
and Zurich of Switzerland. Eizenstat said they estimate their 
market share from the pre-World War II era to be about 30 percent 
of the total. 
</P>
<P>
	``In light of these developments, sanctions against companies  
participating in the Eagleburger commission would gravely undermine 
the commission's work to the ultimate disadvantage of Holocaust 
survivors,'' Eizenstat said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said insurance commissioners in California, New York and  
Florida were getting restless and had called him to complain the 
process was not moving fast enough. 
</P>
<P>
	The commissioners could bar insurance companies and their  
U.S.-owned subsidiaries from doing business in their states. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be enormously counterproductive'' if this were to  
happen, Eizenstat said. He said litigation to settle claims would 
take years while the commission process promised faster payment. 
</P>
<P>
	Eizenstat will continue to be the Clinton administration's point  
man on Holocaust issues when he becomes deputy treasury secretary 
in July. He spoke at a news conference to present the 1,146-page 
proceedings of the Washington Conference on Holocaust-era assets 
held last December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
