<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jack Nicklaus Returns at Pro-Am  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AVONDALE, Pa. (AP) -- The comeback began with a wave to the crowd  
and then a short, slicing tee shot that landed in the rough. Jack 
Nicklaus laughed it off, caring little about the location of the 
ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicklaus, warming up for his first round of competitive golf in  
nearly a year, shot an even-par 72 Thursday in a pro-am round just 
four months after having his left hip replaced. The Golden Bear 
tried to look beyond the windswept treetops and mushroom farms that 
surround the course, dreaming of one final charge that will cap his 
brilliant career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll play a little bit this fall, just because I want to play  
next year,'' said Nicklaus, who will test his new hip Friday in the 
first round of the Senior PGA Bell Atlantic Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	``My goal next year is to try to play the four majors and try to  
be as competitive as I can be. Beyond that point, I'm not saying 
that's going to be the end of my playing major championship golf, 
but it'll probably be the end of my playing all four of them in one 
year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So Nicklaus, eight months shy of his 60th birthday, can see the  
end after all these years. He has to struggle to keep his mind from 
wandering beyond the present. 
</P>
<P>
	``Beyond that, heck, I don't know,'' Nicklaus said. ``I haven't  
even gotten to the first round of the Bell Atlantic yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Out of habit, impatience, or a little of both, Nicklaus clutched  
a microphone as if it were a 9-iron while discussing his quick 
comeback from surgery that replaced his deteriorated left hip with 
an experimental ceramic one. He had the operation in January, 
forcing him to miss his first Masters in 40 years. 
</P>
<P>
	When he tees off Friday, Nicklaus will end a 299-day layoff from  
competitive golf -- his longest since turning professional in 1961. 
He last played in the U.S. Senior Open on July 26, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors told him he couldn't return for six months, and Nicklaus  
eagled that estimate, so to speak, beating it by two months. If all 
goes well this weekend at this senior tournament in the 
Philadelphia suburbs, Nicklaus will play the Memorial Tournament on 
the course he designed in Dublin, Ohio, June 3-6. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he plans to play in the U.S. Open, U.S. Senior Open and  
Senior Players Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``I doubt that I'll go to the British this year,'' Nicklaus  
said. ``That's too many weeks in a row. I might play the PGA 
Championship and I might not. I haven't made up my mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicklaus teed off on No. 10 in the pro-am, bogeying the first  
hole, double-bogeying the fifth. He finished with four birdies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just don't have my strength yet,'' Nicklaus said. ``I mean,  
I'm not terrible. I surprise myself every once in while and hit one 
pretty good. But I'm 85 percent top form.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicklaus' four amateur partners, picked randomly to spend an  
afternoon with one of the greatest golfers who ever lived, tried to 
hide their nervousness. 
</P>
<P>
	The lucky hackers were Frank Pension of Bryn Mawr, Pa.; Charlie  
Parks of Akron, Ohio; Bob Sokol of Long Beach, N.Y.; and Larry 
Sullivan of Baltimore. Pension, a Christopher Lloyd lookalike from 
the ``Back to the Future'' movies, seemed to have the most game. 
Sokol took a carefree approach, walking up to the ball and just 
whacking it like Adam Sandler in ``Happy Gilmour.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``All right, guys, this is what I say to you,'' Nicklaus told  
them before they teed off. ``We're out to get them today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pension swore he wasn't nervous, then fumbled his sunglasses  
after shaking Nicklaus' hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I swing, I want you to throw my ball as far as  
possible,'' Sokol said. 
</P>
<P>
	Playing to the crowd and signing autographs, Nicklaus walked  
nearly all of the hilly course. He plans to do the same in the 
tournament, even though carts are legal on the senior tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't think that I played great, but I played better than  
I've been playing,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicklaus made a terrific second shot on the par-3 11th, coaxing  
a short chip 3 feet from the cup before sinking the easy putt for 
par. He has come a long way since first clutching a club in his 
hands after the surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Imagine Nicklaus, the six-time Masters champion, starting from  
scratch in the weeks after the surgery -- with half swings, 
three-quarter swings and finally full swings that drove the ball 
only 170 yards or so. He joked that he's not even a four-handicap. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm trying to get back to a four,'' Nicklaus said. ``I was a  
four when I was about 12 years old and haven't worried about it 
much since then.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Nicklaus stirred memories of his triumphant, youthful  
days when he became the oldest player to finish in the top 10 at 
the Masters, shooting a final-round, 4-under-par 68 to tie for 
sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	If his bid for one last shot at the four majors goes as planned,  
he wonders how his mind and body will respond. 
</P>
<P>
	``You find something inside you that will sort of drive you on,  
like at the Masters,'' Nicklaus said. ``I remembered how to finish 
a golf tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that will come back. I'll remember.''  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
