<HEADLINE> Discovery Back on NASA Launch Pad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Discovery was back on  
the launch pad today following repairs to its hail-damaged fuel 
tank. 
</P>
<P>
	Discovery is scheduled to blast off next Thursday with 1 1/2 tons  
of gear for the new international space station. Launch time is a 
little before 7 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA returned the shuttle to the pad this morning, the same day  
it should have lifted off. The mission was delayed a week by a 
hailstorm that punched 648 holes into the insulating foam on the 
external fuel tank. 
</P>
<P>
	The larger holes in the insulation were sanded or patched. The  
insulation prevents ice from forming when the tank is filled with 
super-cold fuel. Engineers feared ice forming in the holes could 
break off during liftoff and damage the shuttle. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven astronauts from three countries are assigned to the 10-day  
mission, the first of the year for NASA's shuttle program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
