<HEADLINE> Allianz Plans NYSE Listing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MUNICH, Germany (AP) -- With profits expected to rise at least 10  
percent this year, insurance giant Allianz said today that it is 
weighing acquisitions in the United States and Britain to boost its 
presence in those markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Allianz, Europe's biggest insurer, reported group premium income  
rose 26 percent to $17 billion in the first quarter, at the high 
end of analyst forecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on those developments, Allianz said it expects group  
premium income to rise as much as 8 percent to $53 billion this 
year. Profits should improve by at least 10 percent, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Allianz posted net premium income of $50 billion in 1998, up 20  
percent on the year. 
</P>
<P>
	At the company's annual earnings news conference, chairman  
Henning Schulte-Noelle said Allianz planned to expand its business 
in financial services as well as health and life insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	Allianz also is weighing acquisition opportunities in the United  
States and Britain -- markets in which it's underrepresented, 
Schulte-Noelle said, adding the firm is also eager to acquire 
insurers in Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	Allianz, which is still in the process of consolidating  
Assurances Generales de France SA, acquired in 1997, announced two 
more purchases in the past few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, the group's U.S. life insurance subsidiary  
fully acquired Life USA Holding Inc., in which it had a 23-percent 
stake. It also said earlier this month it plans to acquire South 
Korea's fourth-largest insurer, First Life, subject to regulatory 
approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Allianz also reiterated it intended to list its shares in New  
York as soon as possible, most likely next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
