<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Utah Won't Relax Liquor Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Legislative leaders aren't willing to make  
even minor changes to Utah's strict liquor laws to please 
foreigners at the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The state gave its blessing to the Olympic bid on the condition  
it wouldn't have to bend its alcohol rules, said Senate President 
Lane Beattie, R-West Bountiful, and House Speaker Marty Stephens, 
R-Farr West. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is we're going by the commitment that was  
made,'' Beattie said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Added Stephens: ``I'm not a big proponent of making changes to  
our liquor laws to accommodate the international community. We have 
a society here we are proud of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The International Olympic Committee Wednesday asked Salt Lake  
organizers to seek permission for unfettered alcohol sales at the 
main press center, which will be set up at the Salt Palace 
convention center downtown for some 9,000 members of the media. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday, Olympic officials said they had some kind of variance  
in mind, not a repeal of alcohol restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have made no attempt to change the laws and we are not  
lobbying to change the laws,'' said Mitt Romney, president of the 
Salt Lake Organizing Committee. ``We'll just have to see how the 
laws apply to the situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marc Hodler, who heads up IOC's Olympic coordination commission,  
said ``we just want to be good guests and apply by the laws.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coincidentally, the Utah Alcoholic Beverage Control Commission  
is considering a new banquet license that sponsors say could 
authorize full beverage service for events at the dry Salt Palace. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission scheduled a public hearing for 10:30 a.m. Friday  
on the new uniform license sought by Utah's restaurants, lodges and 
convention centers, including Snowbird Resort. The ABC isn't 
expected to immediately take a position and can only recommend a 
change to the full state Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
	Cap Ferry, a lobbyist for restaurants and lodges, said the Salt  
Palace could use the banquet license to set up a private bar for 
two weeks for Olympic reporters and technicians. 
</P>
<P>
	Under state law, convention centers can serve alcohol only with  
a special permit good for 72 hours and can get only two of the 
permits each year, ABC licensing attorney Earl Dorius said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferry said some organizations need as many as seven permits, all  
with their own terms and conditions, to sponsor private events 
where alcohol is served. A single banquet license would streamline 
the process and impose one set of rules the ABC could more easily 
enforce, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislation authorizing a banquet license went nowhere in the  
legislature earlier this year during the 1999 session. But the 
legislature typically waits for an ABC recommendation before 
changing licensing procedures, Stephens said. 
</P>
<P>
	The House speaker said he found the IOC request odd.  
</P>
<P>
	``When Salt Lake was bidding for the Games, all of our  
competitors used what they call our strange alcohol laws against us 
before the IOC as a negative,'' Stephens said. ``So everybody knew 
what our liquor laws were before the IOC voted to have the Games 
here in Salt Lake City.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beattie said Salt Lake bid organizers assured the state and  
legislators that ``we would not have to change our liquor laws'' 
for the duration of 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Beattie said he thinks that ``people who sell or serve alcohol''  
are behind the IOC request. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
