<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Briefs / Religion Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT DIX, N.J. (AP) -- Officials in charge of this growing  
sanctuary for Albanian refugees have converted barracks classrooms 
into prayer rooms and brought in Muslim clerics. They have also 
bought 1,000 copies of the Koran. 
</P>
<P>
	The prayer rooms are used five times a day by refugees who  
practice Islam. The jumma, an hour-long community prayer service 
that marks their weekly Sabbath, takes place on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Army chaplains and civilian clerics say such observances  
are especially important for the disenfranchised Albanians because 
of what they have endured. 
</P>
<P>
	Lt. Col. Eric Wester, an Army chaplain, observed: ``... because  
everything else has been stripped away, their faith becomes a 
cornerstone for renewing and rebuilding their lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Each dormitory in the refugee village has two prayer rooms, one  
for women and one for men. In each, a picture of a mosque is 
mounted on an East wall, the direction of Mecca and the birthplace 
of Mohammed. 
</P>
<P>
	During the jumma, a black-robed cleric from Staten Island, N.Y.,  
stood in front of the congregation praying in Arabic. ``God is 
compassionate, God is merciful,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kneeling or sitting on prayer rugs, the refugees listened  
intently, occasionally bowing their heads to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're certainly capable of providing bedding, good meals and  
medical care,'' Wester said. ``But the biggest challenge will be to 
try to make meaning out of what they've experienced and to move 
into the future with a sense of hope and direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Jewish activist opposes sainthood for pope    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A leading Jewish activist says Pope Pius XII  
should never become a Catholic saint because the notion 
``desecrates the memory of the Holocaust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rabbi Marvin Hier of the Simon Wiesenthal Center said Pius ``sat  
on the throne of St. Peter in stony silence, without ever lifting a 
finger, as each day thousands of Jews from all over Europe were 
sent to the gas chambers, with his full knowledge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pro-Pius historians maintain that the pope felt public protest  
would have worsened things for Jews and Catholics alike and also 
hoped to be in a position to mediate peace between the Allies and 
the Nazi regime. 
</P>
<P>
	During an address on the state of world Jewry, Hier said ``the  
Vatican adamantly refuses to open its files on this period.'' If it 
agreed, he said, the files ``would prove conclusively that Pius XII 
knew all about the 'Final Solution'.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rabbi acknowledged that Pius helped the Jews of Rome in late  
1943 and 1944, and that his efforts won praise from Jewish leaders 
of the day. But he said by then Pius knew Hitler would lose the 
war. ``In the critical years, when millions could have been spared, 
he preferred silence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Wiesenthal Center, based in Los Angeles, does research on  
Jewish rights and the Holocaust. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *U.S. Muslims ask action on Turkey    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Council on American-Islamic Relations has  
asked the State Department to back religious freedom for Muslims in 
Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
	The council's executive director, Nihad Awad, in writing to  
Robert A. Seiple, the ambassador for international religious 
freedom, said his group had defended the right of Muslim women in 
America to wear religious headgear and said Turkey should do the 
same. 
</P>
<P>
	Awad said Turkish Muslim women ``are routinely harassed,  
discriminated against and denied access to an education or 
government offices simply for choosing to practice their faith by 
wearing a scarf.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Episcopal parish leaves diocese    	
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A small Episcopal parish has voted to leave  
the diocese in a dispute between the conservative congregation and 
the denomination's liberal leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the moment, we will be essentially independent,'' the Rev.  
David Ousley, rector at the Church of St. James the Less, said. 
``Our goal is to be faithful to classical Anglicanism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ousley said the overwhelming vote came after years of growing  
tension and soul-searching at the North Philadelphia congregation. 
Nonetheless, Pennsylvania Bishop Charles E. Bennison Jr. said the 
vote came as a surprise. He said he has asked to meet with 
parishioners to try for a reconciliation. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute stems from a decision at a 1997 general convention  
of the Episcopal Church USA in which four conservative dioceses 
were ordered to ordain and hire women as priests. It also endorsed 
ordaining noncelebate gay men and lesbians. 
</P>
<P>
	About a half-dozen parishes in the United States have seceded  
from the Episcopal Church in the past decade, said William 
Franklin, the dean of the Berkeley Divinity School at Yale 
University. Most joined the Roman Catholic Church. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Hispanic priests on the increase    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A survey of men to be ordained as U.S.  
Catholic priests this year shows 25 percent are from minority 
groups and nearly 20 percent were born outside the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey was commissioned by the U.S. bishops' committee on  
vocations. It was directed by Dean Hoge of the Catholic University 
of America. 
</P>
<P>
	The study found that 10 percent are Hispanic, a higher  
proportion than in the past, but below the 25 percent to 30 percent 
of U.S. Catholics who are Hispanic. 
</P>
<P>
	Black-American ordinands account for 2 percent of the total,  
compared with 3 percent to 4 percent of American Catholics who are 
black. On the other hand, 9 percent are Asian or Pacific Islanders, 
well above those ethnic groups that are Catholic. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 46 percent of the ordinands are 35 or older, 3 percent have  
law degrees and 1 percent are physicians; 63 percent attended 
Catholic elementary schools, well above the average for U.S. 
Catholics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
