<DOCNO> APW19990520.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 10:15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Students Thought Shots Were a Prank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- For seniors at Heritage High, it was a time  
to revel in their last full day of school before graduation. 
</P>
<P>
	The bell for the first class of the day was still 20 minutes  
away. Students were chatting and laughing in the common area and 
others were eating breakfast in the adjacent cafeteria when a 
sophomore allegedly walked in wielding a .22-caliber rifle and 
began firing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just crazy and chaos,'' said Alaina Mitchell, 16,  
hugging her brother who had come to school to pick her up after the 
shooting prompted officials to send students home for the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Many students first thought the loud popping sounds they heard  
were a senior prank. Just a day earlier, a student had released 
2,000 crickets into the school. 
</P>
<P>
	But others feared their suburban school had turned into another  
Columbine High, the Colorado school where 15 died a month ago 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every day since then I've been thinking about whether it could  
happen here,'' Chris Scroggs, 15, who recalled watching the 
Colorado school attack unfold on live television in his drama class 
at Heritage. ``Last night I was thinking that this might be the 
day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the shooting, small groups of students stood outside  
waiting for rides and trading versions of how the event unfolded. 
</P>
<P>
	Joel Thomas, 14, said he was standing and talking to friends in  
the common area when he heard what sounded like gunshots. 
</P>
<P>
	``Somebody yelled he's got a rifle and we started running,''  
Thomas said, shaking his head outside the school as police and news 
media helicopters hovered overhead and investigators moved through 
the school and grounds. ``It's hard to believe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Janice Pugh, her voice cracking and her eyes red, kept one arm  
wrapped around her son, William, while her other hand gripped up 
balled-up tissue. 
</P>
<P>
	She had waited at home for a while after the first news report,  
hoping for a phone call from her son, then decided she couldn't 
wait any longer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not knowing what exactly had happened, not knowing what I  
would find, I just prayed that he would be all right,'' she said of 
her only child. ``I'm just happy that he's OK and I pray for the 
others.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
