<DOCNO> APW19990520.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 18:17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Annan Calls for U.N. Role in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUKES, Albania (AP) -- Encircled by cheering refugees, U.N.  
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Thursday that the United Nations 
should play a key role in resolving the Kosovo crisis and 
resettling hundreds of thousands of displaced people. 
</P>
<P>
	Annan arrived by helicopter in this dusty frontier town and  
toured refugee camps on the edge of Kukes, temporary home to 
100,000 refugees from Kosovo, the largest single concentration of 
the nearly 800,000 people who have fled the province. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are all doing our best to get them home before the  
winter,'' Annan said. ``I hope we succeed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations has been largely sidelined in diplomatic  
efforts to settle the conflict between NATO and Yugoslavia, but 
Annan said there was a growing consensus that the world body would 
have to be involved. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the parties engaged in this conflict have agreed that the  
(U.N.) Security Council should play a central role and that a 
Security Council resolution would be necessary for us to move 
forward,'' Annan said at a brief news conference inside one of the 
camps. 
</P>
<P>
	``What is important is that we get the Yugoslav soldiers and  
paramilitias and police to withdraw, (that) we are able to put in 
an international military force that will secure and protect the 
refugees when they go back,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Annan and his wife, Nane, visited one camp hospital and spoke  
briefly with a woman who had been shot in the foot as she was 
fleeing from Kosovo. The woman was also caring for her 
seven-week-old baby. 
</P>
<P>
	Annan said the conditions in the camps appeared ``reasonably  
good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, aid groups have had trouble persuading the refugees to  
move further south into Albania, away from the unstable border 
region. Kukes is only 15 miles from the border, and more than half 
the refugees coming out of Kosovo have passed through here. 
</P>
<P>
	The refugees want to remain close to the border in hopes that  
they will be able to return soon. But their presence is straining 
the limited resources of Kukes. 
</P>
<P>
	Kukes authorities have threatened to turn off the water if the  
refugees don't start leaving soon. Water consumption has tripled 
since the Kosovo Albanians began arriving almost two months ago, 
and the town could run dry in two to three weeks, officials have 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Local officials and the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees were  
trying to negotiate a compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a few dozen Kosovo refugees have crossed the Albanian  
border in the past week, while the number of departures from Kukes 
has been running at around 2,000 a day. Aid groups say they have 
the capacity to move out around 5,000 refugees a day, but will not 
force them to leave. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
