<DOCNO> APW19990520.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 05:52:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.J. Company Recalls Mascara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORTH ARLINGTON, N.J. (AP) -- A company issued a worldwide recall  
of nearly 30,000 tubes of mascara that may contain bacteria that 
could be dangerous to users who already have other diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials said A.M. Cosmetics of North Arlington is  
recalling Wet 'n Wild Megalash Mascara distributed about five 
months ago. The recall applies to Lot Nos. 161298 and 171298. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Food and Drug Administration said the mascara may  
contain the bacterium Burkholderia cepacia, which can be fatal to 
people suffering from cystic fibrosis or weakened immune systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials said they believe the bacteria entered the  
mascara through contaminated water used in the manufacturing 
process in New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	The mascara was tested before it was shipped for sale, A.M.  
Cosmetics vice president Ron Bowen said. A second backup test 
revealed the contamination. Most of the mascara was recalled before 
it was sold, but some has reached the consumer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We took the safest possible route,'' Bowen said.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very small amount of product,'' Bowen said. ``The  
population at risk is a very small one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No infections caused by mascara use have been reported, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
