<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Congress Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Highlights of the $15 billion measure paying for the fight with  
Yugoslavia and other items that Congress sent to President Clinton 
on Thursday: 
</P>
<P>
	--Attack on Yugoslavia, general defense: $12 billion. To  
Clinton's $6 billion request, adds $2.3 billion for spare parts, 
maintenance and training; $1.8 billion for improved military 
benefits; $475 million for projects at military bases. Includes 
$1.1 billion for refugees, doubling Clinton's request, including up 
to $220 million for Balkan countries near the fighting, $100 
million for bringing Kosovo Albanians to the United States and $149 
million in U.S. food aid. 
</P>
<P>
	--Natural disasters: $1 billion, mostly for Central American  
countries hit by last fall's Hurricane Mitch and for Hurricane 
Georges, which walloped Caribbean nations, Florida and Mississippi. 
An additional $900 million is for damage from recent Midwestern 
tornadoes and disasters that may occur in coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	--U.S. farmers: $574 million, largely to help corn, hog and other  
commodities farmers faced with plunging market prices. 
</P>
<P>
	--Jordan: $100 million in military and economic aid.  
</P>
<P>
	--Land disputes: Postpones federal plans to boost royalties paid  
by some oil companies and to issue stricter rules for some mining 
operations. Allows Crown Jewel gold mine in Washington to move 
forward with an open-pit mine and gold-leaching operations, over 
Interior Department objections. 
</P>
<P>
	--Tobacco: Federal government can't share $246 billion settlement  
between states, tobacco companies. 
</P>
<P>
	--Congress: $3.8 million to renovate dormitory for House pages,  
$1.8 million to upgrade House office building. 
</P>
<P>
	--Financing: All but $2 billion paid for from federal surplus,  
which comes from Social Security. Of the rest, $1.3 billion would 
come from food stamp funds that would not have been spent anyway. 
Other savings come from public housing, other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	--Miscellaneous: $4.5 million to expand Bureau of Alcohol,  
Tobacco and Firearms facility in West Virginia; $200 million for 
Coast Guard; $48 million to help National Public Radio replace lost 
satellite; names post office under construction in Tuscumbia, Ala., 
for former Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
