<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fox Adds Eight New Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Fox is betting on some proven performers for its  
new fall schedule: Jennifer Love Hewitt, Chris Carter and David E. 
Kelley. 
</P>
<P>
	The network will premiere a condensed version of Kelley's  
creation, ``Ally McBeal,'' a spinoff series with ``Party of Five'' 
star Hewitt and a drama about a virtual reality game gone awry from 
Carter, the man behind ``The X-Files.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, struggling UPN on Thursday cemented its effort to  
appeal to young men by sinking its ``Love Boat'' remake and adding 
a two-hour weekly World Wrestling Federation show to its fall 
schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	UPN and Fox were the last of the seven broadcast networks to  
unveil their fall schedules to advertisers this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox is the fourth-rated network, but near the top among young  
people. It returns three dramas to its schedule -- ``Party of 
Five,'' ``The X-Files'' and ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' -- but there's 
a strong possibility this is the final season for all of them. 
</P>
<P>
	Searching for the next generation of programming, Fox included  
five dramas among the eight new shows that will join its fall 
lineup. One is ``Time of Your Life,'' which moves Hewitt's 
character to New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter is behind the dark action series, ``Harsh Realm.'' Fox  
also returns ``Cops'' and ``America's Most Wanted'' on Saturday 
nights and premieres a gritty drama about a 19-year-old policeman, 
``Ryan Caulfield,'' at a time when there's a concern about media 
depiction of violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a sensitive issue and we'll be keeping our eye on it, no  
question about it,'' Fox entertainment president Doug Herzog said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesdays, Fox will run a half-hour ``Ally McBeal'' edition  
fashioned from outtakes and material from the show's first two 
seasons. It's an intriguing new programming concept that appeals to 
network executives' search for cheaper shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Herzog promised this winter to cut back on Fox's reality shows.  
He left ``Guinness Book of World Records'' and ``World's Funniest'' 
off the schedule. Most of the reality shows air as specials, 
however. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox canceled ``Millennium'' and left the animated comedy, ``The  
PJs,'' off the schedule, although it will return as a sub series. 
``Melrose Place'' has retired. ``Party of Five'' is moving to 
Tuesdays, and the cartoons ``King of the Hill'' and ``Futurama'' 
will be shifted to Sundays. 
</P>
<P>
	Low-rated UPN has taken note of pro wrestling's hold on the  
cable TV audience and asked the World Wrestling Federation to 
produce a broadcast version. ``WWF Smackdown!'' will air at 8 p.m. 
Thursdays and will be tamer than the cable shows, UPN president 
Dean Valentine said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will probably be toned down a bit in terms of language and  
the upraised finger -- you'll see a lot less of it,'' Valentine 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	UPN will spin off its most popular sitcom, ``Moesha,'' with the  
comedy, ``Mo'Nique,'' and shift its comedies that appeal to a black 
audience to Mondays. Its five new series also include ``The Grown 
Ups,'' starring former ``Family Matters'' actor Jaleel White. 
</P>
<P>
	Its other new series are ``Shasta McNasty,'' a modern-day  
version of the Monkees, and the spy drama, ``Secret Agent Man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to ``Love Boat,'' the network is canceling  
``Clueless,'' ``The Sentinel'' and ``Between Brothers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fox's other new programs include:  
</P>
<P>
	--''Get Real,'' a family drama about a couple and their three  
high school-aged children. 
</P>
<P>
	--''Manchester Prep,'' a drama about a prep school student from  
New York City who moves in with his father's new family, setting up 
a rivalry with his stepsister. 
</P>
<P>
	--''Action,'' a comedy starring Jay Mohr and Illeana Douglas that  
is a satirical look at Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
	--''Malcolm in the Middle,'' a family comedy about a 9-year-old  
genius. 
</P>
</TEXT>
