<DOCNO> APW19990520.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 18:17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Envoys Confer in Moscow on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Three top envoys discussed a peace proposal to end  
the Kosovo conflict Thursday, but acknowledged a lot of work still 
had to be done and said it was not clear if Yugoslavia would accept 
the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, who is heading  
Russia's mediation efforts for Yugoslavia, briefed U.S. Deputy 
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and Finnish President Martti 
Ahtisaari on his talks with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic 
in Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	Talbott said the talks had been constructive and would continue,  
but gave no indication if any progress had been made. The other 
participants also gave few details. 
</P>
<P>
	Ahtisaari said the peace efforts were at a preliminary stage  
even though all sides wanted swift progress. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still unclear whether we'll be able to persuade the  
Yugoslav leadership,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin, who has in the past claimed breakthroughs that  
later failed to materialize, gave no details on the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	The three men conferred at a government resort on Moscow's  
outskirts after Chernomyrdin visited Belgrade for talks on ending 
the conflict over Yugoslavia's Kosovo province that has killed 
hundreds of people and displaced nearly 800,000 ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a tense talk. It took quite a long time,'' Chernomyrdin  
told reporters Thursday, referring to his talks with the Yugoslav 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin and Milosevic discussed a plan by the Group of  
Eight industrialized nations to end the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic told Chernomyrdin that Yugoslavia opposes pulling all  
its troops out of Kosovo and allowing an international force to 
control the province -- both of which NATO demands. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Chernomyrdin said there had been ``a step forward,''  
the ITAR-Tass news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia strongly opposes NATO attacks on Yugoslavia and has been  
working for a diplomatic solution. Talbott, Chernomyrdin and 
Ahtisaari met in Finland twice this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Ahtisaari said earlier Thursday he had no new initiatives to  
discuss. 
</P>
<P>
	``One thing we don't need now is more proposals,'' he told  
reporters before leaving Finland. ``What we are doing now is 
measuring how ready the Yugoslav political leadership is for a 
peaceful solution and on what conditions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic's office said that ``the solution could be found only  
politically and within the United Nations, and with the active and 
direct participation of Yugoslavia, starting from the principles of 
the G-8.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the G-8 plan include withdrawal of Milosevic's  
``military, police and paramilitary forces'' from Kosovo. NATO 
wants a total withdrawal of all Serb forces, including regular 
troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Russian Foreign Ministry condemned NATO's latest  
bombings, which hit a hospital Thursday and killed at least three 
people. President Boris Yeltsin called for ``an immediate end to 
the senseless, barbaric bombings,'' his office said in a statement 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Acting Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov met in Moscow with the U.N.  
special envoy on Kosovo, Slovak Foreign Minister Eduard Kukan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Russia's position (is) that the role of the United Nations  
must be the leading one,'' Ivanov told reporters after the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is unhappy with NATO's prominence and wants the United  
Nations -- a body where Moscow has considerable influence -- to call 
the shots in the Yugoslav settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	The other top U.N. envoy on Kosovo, Carl Bildt, is due to join  
Kukan in Moscow on Friday for talks on the conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 17:49:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Carr Not the Show on De La Hoya Card </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Oba Carr walked unnoticed Thursday behind dark  
glasses past the posters of Oscar De La Hoya in the hotel lobby. 
</P>
<P>
	Carr fights De La Hoya for the welterweight title Saturday  
night. You might not have known it by looking at posters, which 
featured only the champion. 
</P>
<P>
	Such is the plight of an opponent, which is all 10-1 underdogs  
like Carr are expected to be. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only way for me to have my picture up there is to win the  
title,'' Carr said. ``When I do, you'll see my pictures all over 
town.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carr, in the biggest fight of his boxing career, meets De La  
Hoya for the WBC 147-pound title. It's the fight of his life, but 
not many are noticing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't bother me,'' Carr said. ``I don't feel like Oscar  
is overlooking me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not only that Carr is overshadowed by De La Hoya, who makes  
millions each fight and is the biggest non-heavyweight attraction 
in boxing. He's also been overshadowed by negotiations all week 
long for De La Hoya's next fight -- a showdown with IBF champion 
Felix Trindiad. 
</P>
<P>
	Carr fought Trindiad and knocked him down in the second round  
before being stopped in the eighth. His only other loss was to Ike 
Quartey, De La Hoya's last opponent, and he put Quartey down in the 
11th round, only to lose by decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``Trinidad and Oscar is an attractive fight,'' Carr said.  
``People want to see that fight. But in the future they're going to 
want to see Oba Carr and Trinidad in a rematch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carr (48-2-1) beat Frankie Randall on the De La Hoya-Quartey  
undercard to earn a shot at De La Hoya. He'll earn $350,000 to $5 
million for the champion, but he'll also get the opportunity to 
finally make a name for himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm at the epitome of my boxing game,'' Carr said. ``I have a  
serenity in myself, a peace in myself that is almost not 
understandable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carr, of Detroit, and De La Hoya appeared at a final pre-fight  
press conference Thursday, where few listened as Carr delivered a 
sermon-like speech. When it came time for De La Hoya to talk, 
though, they were all ears. 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya (30-0, 24 knockouts) vowed to mix it up with Carr and  
every other fighter who gets in the ring with him in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've gone to my old style. Enough about this boxing stuff,''  
said De La Hoya, who has gone the 12-round distance in four of his 
last eight fights. 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya said he decided suddenly five weeks ago in training  
camp that he would not box opponents anymore, but would try to 
knock them out instead. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a tactic that is more crowd-pleasing but also carries  
risks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was losing total respect from people,'' De La Hoya said. ``I  
have it now. It's back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya and promoter Bob Arum have given Trinidad a Friday  
deadline to accept an $11 million offer for a Sept. 18 unification 
fight. But De La Hoya said he is not underestimating Carr or his 
ability to thwart his future fight plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oba Carr is a dangerous opponent. He's experienced, but he has  
had bad luck,'' De La Hoya said. ``When I fight an opponent, they 
lift themselves up to sky. I expect the same from Oba.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 17:49:36 </DATE_TIME>
