<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baffert Filly Might Run in Belmont </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Trainer Bob Baffert is toying with the idea of  
running the sensational filly Silverbulletday in the Belmont 
Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	If she does start, however, there won't be any side bet with Bob  
Lewis, owner with his wife, Beverly, of Charismatic, who will try 
to win the Triple Crown in the Belmont on June 5. 
</P>
<P>
	After Baffert was quoted as saying Silverbulletday was the best  
3-year-old in the country, Lewis offered to bet Baffert $100,000, 
with the money to go to charity. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert told The Associated Press on Thursday by phone from  
California that what he had said was Silverbulletday was the best 
3-year-old filly. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be no bet,'' Baffert said. ``I was misquoted, and  
when he read that he got fired up. He didn't want people to think 
that I would stay out because of him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert also trains horses for the Lewises, including Silver  
Charm, winner of the 1997 Kentucky Derby and Preakness and 
runner-up in the Belmont Stakes. Silverbulletday is owned by Mike 
Pegram, whose Real Quiet won the Derby and Preakness and was second 
in the Belmont last year. 
</P>
<P>
	For Silverbulletday, winner of 11 of 12 starts, to make her  
debut against males in the 1 1/2-mile Belmont, Baffert said, the field 
could not have more than 12 starters, and ``then I've got to see 
how she's working to see if I want to send her that far. She's got 
to tell me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's possible the Belmont could have a full 16-horse field.  
</P>
<P>
	Of all the owners and trainers considering starting a horse in  
the Belmont, Baffert said: ``They must not have been watching 
Charismatic run. The move he put in (in the Preakness) ... this 
horse is for real.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 18:11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed OKs Bankers Trust Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve approved Thursday the  
proposed $10.2 billion merger of Bankers Trust Corp. and Germany's 
Deutsche Bank AG, which would create the world's largest financial 
institution. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was 6-0 by the central bank's board of governors, who  
determined the merger of the nation's eighth-largest bank with 
Germany's largest would not threaten banking competition in this 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	New York-based Bankers Trust concentrates on banking for big  
corporations and does no business with consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger, proposed last November, would create a financial  
powerhouse with $830 billion in assets. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition of Bankers Trust would be the biggest takeover  
of a U.S. financial institution by a foreign bank. The institution 
would be larger than UBS AG of Switzerland, currently the largest 
bank, and the recently formed Citigroup Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The regulators apparently were not troubled by Deutsche Bank's  
12 percent stake in the newly formed DaimlerChrysler AG. According 
to U.S. laws that separate banks from other kinds of corporations, 
banks in this country are prohibited from owning more than 5 
percent of a nonfinancial company. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed's approval was the latest in a series of big hurdles  
cleared by the merger recently, leaving only approval from 
authorities in Canada and New Jersey to be secured. 
</P>
<P>
	The two banks said in a statement Thursday they expected the  
merger might be completed as early as next month. They called the 
central bank's approval ``a further decisive step'' towards 
completion. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, under pressure from the U.S. State  
Department, New York City Comptroller Alan Hevesi withdrew his 
opposition to the deal, acknowledging that the two banks had made 
progress in resolving Holocaust claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Holocaust survivors and heirs have been seeking restitution for  
millions of dollars in Jewish property and financial holdings 
stolen by the Nazis in the World War II era and hidden in various 
European banks. 
</P>
<P>
	A State Department official had warned that opposition to the  
merger on political grounds could chill the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed noted in its decision that it had received written  
comments from people and groups expressing concern about Deutsche 
Bank's activities during the war and urging it to investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently discovered files from eastern Europe showed that loans  
from a Deutsche Bank branch in Nazi-occupied Poland helped finance 
the Auschwitz death camp. 
</P>
<P>
	After a careful review, the Fed said it had concluded that  
Holocaust-related issues ``do not warrant denial'' of the proposed 
merger. The Fed noted that Deutsche Bank had recently joined with 
other German banks, insurers and other companies to set up a 
humanitarian fund to benefit Holocaust victims and compensate slave 
laborers from the wartime era. 
</P>
<P>
	New York state's banking regulators and European Union  
authorities have also approved the merger. 
</P>
<P>
	In the resolution of another matter, Bankers Trust agreed in  
March to pay $63.5 million in fines to settle federal prosecutors' 
charges that it boosted its financial performance by unlawfully 
diverting millions of dollars from unclaimed customer accounts into 
its own coffers. 
</P>
<P>
	The plea entered in a federal court brought a speedy resolution  
to accusations that the bank made false entries in its books to 
conceal the true source of $19.1 million its employees diverted. 
</P>
<P>
	Bankers Trust has some $133 billion in assets. Deutsche Bank has  
assets of $734 billion. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 05:43:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How Federal Agents Trace Guns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	At the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms' tracing center  
in West Virginia, trucks unload boxes of paper records from 
federally licensed gun dealers who have gone out of business. 
Workers scan the handwritten pages onto microfilm -- the basic 
building blocks of the system to trace guns used in crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	About half the time, by using these records and making phone  
calls to manufacturers and dealers, the ATF successfully traces a 
gun used in a crime to its first retail sale. After that, local 
police conduct door-to-door interviews to determine how a gun moved 
from that first owner to a criminal. 
</P>
<P>
	How the process works:  
</P>
<P>
	A police department faxes or calls in a trace request.  
</P>
<P>
	An ATF worker usually begins by checking the gun's style and  
serial number and calls the manufacturer to find out where and when 
the gun was shipped. (A few gun makers share computerized sales 
records with ATF). 
</P>
<P>
	Another ATF worker then moves on to whoever handled the gun  
next, a wholesaler or distributor. Eventually, the trail -- if it 
hasn't gone cold -- should lead to the federally licensed dealer who 
sold the gun to a private individual. 
</P>
<P>
	If the federally licensed dealer is still in business, the ATF  
calls and requests a records check to see who bought the gun. If 
the dealer is out of business, the ATF searches for the gun's 
serial number in its microfilmed records. 
</P>
<P>
	Glitches occur for many reasons: The microfilmed records may  
list the same serial number for many guns, because different 
manufacturers often use the same serial numbers. Or a gun maker has 
gone out of business. Older guns generally are more difficult to 
trace because they've gone through more private, unrecorded sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The tracing center has no access to the instant background  
checks done on everyone who tries to buy a gun from a licensed 
dealer. However, the center does get the records of all multiple 
sales made by dealers and can check those against traces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 06:31:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GE To Invest in Thai Plastics Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- GE Plastics, a division of General  
Electric Co., said Thursday it will invest $20 million in a 
plastics plant in Thailand. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant, which will be located in Rayong on the country's  
industrialized eastern seaboard, is expected to be operational by 
mid-2000, company officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new plant will produce some 30,000 tons a year of compounded  
engineering thermoplastic resins, used in computer monitor 
housings, printers, small electric appliances, compact discs and 
auto parts, the company said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20 percent of the plant's output will be for direct  
export, and the rest will be used for making products for export, 
it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign investment in Thailand is expected to increase this year  
following a slump caused by Thailand's economic crisis, which began 
in July 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	General Electric Co., which is headquartered in Fairfield,  
Conn., is America's fifth largest corporation. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
