<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Sentences Kurd Rebel to Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) --The top lieutenant to Kurdish rebel leader  
Abdullah Ocalan was sentenced to death today for masterminding 
hundreds of deaths in Turkey in a bid to win autonomy for the 
Kurds. 
</P>
<P>
	A panel of three judges gave Semdin Sakik the death penalty for  
treason. He was held responsible for the slayings of 283 people in 
191 acts of violence carried out by the Kurdistan Workers Party, or 
PKK. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey has not carried out a death penalty in more than a decade  
and the court's decision for Ocalan's second-in-command does not 
bode well for the PKK leader. Ocalan himself has been accused in 
the deaths of over 30,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Sakik's brother, Arif, was also sentenced to death for treason  
in the trial today in Diyarbakir, the main city in Turkey's 
southeast, where the guerrilla war has been carried out since 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	The conflict between the separatist PKK and the Turkish army has  
killed some 37,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Both brothers have the right to appeal. Their trial, which  
started in June 1998, was held in a state security court. One 
military and two civilian judges presided. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the sentencing, Sakik expressed remorse and asked for  
mercy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was the one who carried out the most radical struggle  
against armed conflict within the organization, because I saw that 
what was being done amounted to terrorism,'' he told the court. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey has not executed anyone since 1984. The death penalty  
requires the approval of Parliament and it was unclear if lawmakers 
would approved the Sakik's execution, which in Turkey is carried 
out by hanging. 
</P>
<P>
	Sakik, 40, known by his nom de guerre ``Fingerless Zeki'' for  
his missing finger, was the mastermind of PKK operations in Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
	He reportedly fell out with the PKK leader after military  
crackdowns on the group and found refuge with an Iraqi Kurdish 
group before being captured last year in northern Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan is awaiting trial on the prison island of Imrali, where a  
special court has been set up for security reasons. The first 
hearing is scheduled May 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
