<DOCNO> APW19990520.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 05:43:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Details of Federal Gun Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The federal laws that govern the sale of guns in the United  
States are designed to funnel most interstate commerce in firearms 
through federally licensed dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	State and local officials can impose additional restrictions, if  
they choose. 
</P>
<P>
	Generally, all those ``engaged in the business'' of selling  
firearms must acquire a federal license that requires them to do 
several things: 
</P>
<P>
	--Run a Brady Law background check on anyone who wants to buy a  
gun to ensure the person is not a convicted felon or otherwise 
unqualified to own a firearm; 
</P>
<P>
	--Keep a record of all purchases and sales back 20 years, and  
make it available to the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms if 
it seeks to trace a gun. When dealers go out of business, they must 
ship their old records to ATF, a branch of the Treasury Department. 
</P>
<P>
	--Report immediately to the ATF all multiple gun sales to one  
buyer. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of federally licensed firearms dealers dropped to  
just over 100,000 in recent years, from more than 200,000, after 
the Brady Law set higher fees and tighter restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	After an initial gun sale by a federally licensed dealer, all  
sales between private individuals not engaged in the business are 
exempt from the background check and recording requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	However, there is no specific definition of ``engaged in the  
business.'' Collectors and hobbyists are exempt, for example. But a 
person who sells many guns without a license can often operate for 
years without ATF discovering him, says Harvard University 
researcher David Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	At gun shows -- a flashpoint in recent debates in Congress -- all  
licensed dealers must run background checks and keep sales records, 
just as if they were operating from a store. But private sellers, 
again, need not run background checks or keep records. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun control groups contend some private sellers abuse the system  
by selling large numbers of guns at shows. The National Rifle 
Association disputes that, saying there's no proof gun shows are a 
major source of illegal trafficking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 05:52:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Holdsclaw Gets Jordan's No. 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw finally got her No. 23.  
</P>
<P>
	``My baby's back,'' said Holdsclaw, stretching the black  
practice Washington Mystics jersey and patting the two white 
numerals as she sat down after Wednesday's practice. ``I'm excited 
about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw, the No. 1 overall pick in the WNBA draft and hailed  
as the ``female Michael Jordan,'' did not wear a number her first 
two days at training camp. Twenty-three was her number when she won 
championships in high school in New York and in college at 
Tennessee, but Rita Williams wore that number last year for the 
Mystics. 
</P>
<P>
	The team decided to leave it in the hands of the players.  
Earlier this week, the two sat and talked about it. Williams 
finally gave in. 
</P>
<P>
	``She has a special attachment to it, so I'd figure I'd give it  
to her,'' Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw originally chose No. 23 because of Jordan, but she  
says it also has come to represent Psalm 23. At public appearances 
since the draft, the Mystics have given her ceremonial jerseys such 
as No. 99 -- for 1999 -- and No. 1 -- for first overall pick -- while 
fans yelled comments such as ``Where's No. 23?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt kind of strange,'' Holdsclaw said.  
</P>
<P>
	And what did Holdsclaw have to give up to get the number from  
Williams? 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to buy her golf clubs,'' Holdsclaw said. ``We're  
going to take lessons together, and today she told me I had to pay 
for her lessons, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for Williams, she has a new favorite number. She wore No. 13,  
her overall draft position last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thirteen was my lucky number last year,'' Williams said, ``so  
I just picked this one.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
