<DOCNO> APW19990520.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 21:31:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Merrill Lynch Charged in Copper Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators, seeking to close the books  
on a scandal in the world copper market three years ago, have 
charged Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. with allegedly helping a commodities 
firm manipulate copper prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Commodity Futures Trading Commission said Thursday that  
Merrill Lynch worked with Global Minerals and Metals Corp. and 
Japan's Sumitomo Corp. to artificially force prices higher in late 
1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Geoffrey Aronow, the CFTC's enforcement director, said the  
charges capped a three-year investigation of ``one of the most 
serious worldwide manipulations'' of a commodity in 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch and Global Minerals denied the allegations.  
</P>
<P>
	Merrill said it fully cooperated with the CFTC's investigation  
and was ``extremely disappointed'' that the agency decided to 
proceed with charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The CFTC also announced charges against New York-based Global  
Minerals, its president and chief executive officer, R. David 
Campbell, and its chief copper trader, Carl Alm. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Haveles, an attorney for Global Minerals and Campbell,  
said the CFTC's complaint was ``based on an Alice-in-Wonderland 
view of the facts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, Haveles said the company's trading activities  
occurred in a market with a big copper deficit due to a dramatic 
increase in demand in the mid-1990s, which would have pushed up the 
metal's price. He also said British commodities regulators were 
``fully informed'' about Global Minerals' activities at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Alm's attorney, David Frankel, didn't immediately return a  
telephone call seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The case stems from a scandal that rocked the world copper  
market in 1996, based on trades that occurred as much as 10 years 
beforehand. 
</P>
<P>
	Yasuo Hamanaka, a former Sumitomo star trader who has been  
convicted of fraud and forgery by a Japanese court, caused $2.6 
billion in losses in unauthorized copper trading over a decade 
after cornering as much as 5 percent of the market. When the losses 
were exposed in 1996, copper prices plunged. 
</P>
<P>
	According to traders, Hamanaka's activities kept the price of  
copper high on the New York and London commodity futures markets in 
1995 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	CFTC Chairwoman Brooksley Born has said the alleged manipulation  
caused serious harm to the U.S. copper market and American users of 
the metal by driving up prices. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, Sumitomo agreed to pay $150 million to settle the  
CFTC's charges that it manipulated the world copper market. The big 
Japanese trading house, which also agreed to pay $8 million to 
British regulators, neither admitted to nor denied wrongdoing in 
the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The CFTC alleged Thursday that Merrill ``knowingly and  
intentionally aided, abetted and assisted'' the manipulation scheme 
by providing substantial credit and financing that Global Minerals 
and Sumitomo used to corner warehouse stocks of copper. The 
regulators also accused Merrill of intentionally advising Global 
Minerals and Sumitomo on how they could best corner the market. 
They alleged that Merrill benefitted from the scheme in its own 
copper trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, Merrill said it had no knowledge that Sumitomo's  
conduct was unlawful and had no intention of aiding any improper 
activities. 
</P>
<P>
	``The business transactions that occurred more than three years  
ago between Merrill Lynch and Sumitomo, including copper trading 
..., were conducted in a commercially reasonable fashion and were 
fully visible to the regulators at the time,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Merrill spokesman said the company similarly had no knowledge  
of unlawful conduct by Global Minerals and had made reasonable 
transactions with the commodities firm. 
</P>
<P>
	The CFTC filed a civil complaint against the companies and  
individuals, asking for a hearing before an administrative law 
judge at the agency to determine if the charges are true and what 
penalties may be appropriate. 
</P>
<P>
	Possible penalties include an order requiring the companies and  
individuals to refrain from future violations of federal 
commodities laws and civil fines and restitution of damages, the 
agency said. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 05:52:39 </DATE_TIME>
