<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mom Convicted of Starving Her Boy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A young mother who blamed breast-feeding  
problems for the death of her emaciated 2-month-old son wept as she 
was convicted of criminally negligent homicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Tabitha Walrond, 21, faces up to four years in prison when she  
is sentenced. She was acquitted Wednesday of the more serious 
charge of manslaughter, which could have brought her a 15-year 
sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Ms. Walrond starved 2-month-old Tyler in 1997  
to spite his father, who left her shortly after she got pregnant -- 
or, at the very least, ignored signs that the baby was starving. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense said she was a doting mother who didn't realize that  
her surgically reduced breasts were failing to nourish her child. 
Defense attorney Susan Tipograph said Tyler may have suffered from 
an adrenal gland disorder -- not malnutrition. 
</P>
<P>
	But autopsy photographs showed the boy was emaciated, having  
dropped from his birth weight of nearly 8 pounds to about 5 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a child of that size, with skin folds creasing over  
the legs and the arms, would have been hard to not notice,'' juror 
Anthony Bosco, 24, said outside the courthouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Walrond testified that she never noticed Tyler's weight  
loss. She said she took natural-childbirth classes, went to night 
school to finish high school before Tyler was born and chose to 
breast-feed because doctors and family told her ``breast is best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All those actions, Ms. Tipograph said, demonstrated motherly  
love. She said Ms. Walrond brought Tyler to a clinic for a checkup 
but was turned away because she did not have a Medicaid card for 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Walrond sobbed on the witness stand as she described how she  
found Tyler looking lifeless and foaming at the mouth and rushed 
him to the hospital in a taxi. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said `Faster, faster! ... Something's wrong with my baby!'''  
she said. ``He left me, he died in the cab. I felt him leave.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990520.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 12:31:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., EU Still at Odds on Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- The United States and the European Union  
have agreed to keep talking about their trade dispute over 
hormone-treated beef but otherwise senior officials had no progress 
to report after concluding two hours of discussions Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is committed to imposing retaliatory tariffs  
on European Union goods because of the EU's refusal to accept 
hormone-treated North American beef. 
</P>
<P>
	But U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman and his European  
Union counterpart, Franz Fischler of Austria, said even if 
Washington retaliates as threatened, it wouldn't amount to a trade 
war. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is threatening to impose $202 million in  
tariffs on EU exports June 3 in retaliation for the EU's rejection 
of a World Trade Organization decision requiring the 15-nation 
union to begin accepting hormone-treated beef, which Canada also 
wishes to export to Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO has ruled three times that the EU has not produced  
enough evidence to satisfy international trade rules allowing 
states to ban items on public health grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Fischler insists EU-instigated research indicates  
hormone-treated beef is unsafe and that more thorough studies need 
to be done. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked whether he thought America would accept compensation  
payments from the EU while the beef ban remained, Fischler said: 
``It's not the right moment to make speculations about that.'' 
Glickman said he had received no specific compensation proposal 
from Fischler. 
</P>
<P>
	But Fischler was emphasized his desire to avoid a lengthy public  
argument between Europe and America on this issue. Such bickering 
would likely lower consumers' confidence in beef products 
generally, he said, ``and this can't be in anybody's interest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The EU does accept up to 11,500 tons of hormone-free U.S. beef  
annually. Fischler has previously suggested that raising this 
figure could form part of a compromise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
