<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 17:11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Georgia School Shooting Wounds 6  
</P>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- A 15-year-old boy who opened fire in a  
suburban Atlanta high school today was apparently aiming below 
student's waist so as not to fatally injure them, witnesses said. 
Six people were hit by the shots at Heritage High School, with none 
of the injuries being life-threatening. The student was carrying a 
.22-caliber rifle and a .22-caliber revolver. Authorities said the 
boy has been charged as a juvenile with aggravated assault, and may 
face other charges. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate OKs Gun-Show Restrictions  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With gunshots ringing out in yet another high  
school, legislation restricting firearms sales at gun shows and 
pawnshops barely passed the Senate today. Vice President Al Gore 
broke a tie vote in order to pass the curbs opposed by most 
Republicans. The proposal would require background checks for all 
sales at gun shows. It also would close what gun control advocates 
said was a loophole that allows anyone to pawn his gun and reclaim 
it without undergoing a check. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds Approve Bankers Trust Merger  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A merger that would create the world's largest  
financial institution was approved by the Federal Reserve today. 
The $10.2 billion merger between Bankers Trust Corp. and Germany's 
Deutsche Bank AG, passed on a 6-0 vote by the central bank's board 
of governors, who determined the merger of the nation's 
eighth-largest bank with Germany's largest would not threaten 
banking competition in this country. The merger, proposed last 
November, would create a financial powerhouse with $830 billion in 
assets. 

</P>
<P>
	House Approves Missile Defense Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is expected to sign  
legislation passed today that would commit the United States to an 
anti-missile national defense system. The legislation, passed 
345-71, states that it is the policy of the United States to 
deploy, as soon as technologically possible, an effective system 
capable of defending U.S. territory against limited ballistic 
missile attack. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Bombs Damage Belgrade Hospital  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Belgrade and its suburbs were  
heavily bombed by NATO jets today, leaving three patients dead at a 
hospital hit hard in the attacks. Homes of three European 
ambassadors were damaged, as was the Libyan embassy. There were new 
accounts of desertions in the Yugoslav army, and there was a fresh 
round of diplomacy in Moscow involving Russian, Finnish and 
American envoys. 

</P>
<P>
	Sunken Cruise Ship Passengers Saved  
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- A cruise ship caught fire and sank  
off the western coast of Malaysia early Friday, and authorities 
rescued more than 1,000 passengers. The passengers, including 
Americans, Britons, Canadians and Japanese, were rescued from the 
Bahamian-registered Sun Vista, said a spokesman for the Marine 
Rescue and Coordination Center in Port Klang. There have been no 
reports of fatalities. 

</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch Charged in Copper Case  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators charged Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.  
today with allegedly helping a commodities firm manipulate the 
world copper market. The U.S. Commodity Futures Trading Commission 
said that Merrill Lynch worked with New York-based Global Minerals 
and Metals Corp. and Japan's Sumitomo Corp. to artificially force 
prices higher in late 1995. Possible penalties include an order 
requiring the companies and individuals to refrain from future 
violations of federal commodities laws and civil fines and 
restitution of damages. 

</P>
<P>
	Vitamin Makers To Pay $725M Fine  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two foreign companies agreed today to pay $725  
million in fines for plotting to raise and fix the prices of 
vitamins used in virtually every American home and added to bread, 
milk and breakfast cereal. One fine of $500 million is to be paid 
by F. Hoffmann-LaRoche Ltd., a Swiss pharmaceutical company, and it 
is the largest federal criminal fine ever imposed in any type of 
case. A German firm, BASF AG, agreed to pay a $225 million fine. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 20.65  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned lower in late trading today as  
lingering concerns about leading technology companies sapped the 
market's modest gains. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 20.65 
to close at 10,866.74. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,750-1,219. 
The Nasdaq composite index fell 34.98 to 2,542.42. 

</P>
<P>
	Armstrong Is NBA's Most Improved  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Darrell Armstrong of the Orlando Magic today won  
the NBA's Most Improved Player Award, making him the first to win 
both that honor and the Sixth Man Award. Eric Snow, Philadelphia's 
point guard, was second with 15 votes. Armstrong, a guard, averaged 
career highs of 13.8 points, 6.7 rebounds and 2.16 steals in 30 
minutes a game while coming off the bench in 35 of 50 games. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
