<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US-Israeli Music Team Has New Style </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) -- Gabriel and Eddie Butler grew up in a  
dusty Israeli desert town listening to gospel, blues and soul, the 
music their parents brought with them when the family moved from 
Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't the sound coming from other Israeli homes but it was  
the favorite among the Black Hebrews, a clan including the Butlers 
who believe they are a lost tribe of Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	That's probably why ``Lover,'' a sugary ballad sung mostly in  
Hebrew about a man desperate to stay in his woman's arms, sounds 
more like the stuff of an American boy-band than a typical Israeli 
song, with serious lyrics and soft guitar. 
</P>
<P>
	The love-sick lyrics and the hint of rhythm 'n' blues are the  
touches of the Butler brothers who make up half of the singing 
foursome Eden, a new Israeli group hoping to break onto the world 
stage by peppering Hebrew songs with English lyrics. 
</P>
<P>
	The songs were originally written in English but then translated  
into Hebrew to familiarize Israelis with the group before it is 
showcased at the Eurovision song contest May 29. Even the band's 
name was chosen to appeal in both languages; ``Eden'' also means 
paradise in Hebrew. The back-and-forth on language and style is 
indicative of the group's search for an identity of its own. 
</P>
<P>
	A leggy Israeli transsexual with a sultry voice won the contest  
last year. Dana International's agents and promoters have also 
taken on Eden, hoping the contest will do for them what it did for 
Dana and many others -- bring an international recording contract 
and spots on MTV Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Eden, which has yet to make a name in Israel, is eager for the  
boost. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to start at the top,'' said singer and lyricist  
Gabriel Butler, ``but we realized we needed a home base, a place to 
start.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the Chicago-born singer-songwriter, that meant rewriting  
most of the group's songs from English into Hebrew. 
</P>
<P>
	``We translated many of our songs into Hebrew and where the  
words didn't work with the melodies, we sort of adapted 
everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Black Hebrews first began immigrating to Israel in the  
1970s. Some of them gravitated toward the country's music scene, 
singing back-up and harmony for Israeli musicians. 
</P>
<P>
	Butler, 34, and his brother Eddie, 26, are no strangers to life  
in two languages. They spoke English at home, and Hebrew in school. 
The mixed cultural upbringing was the driving force behind Eden's 
music. 
</P>
<P>
	``At home my parents listened to gospel music, The Temptations  
and The Platters,'' said the elder Butler. Those are the sounds he 
hopes to infuse in his own music. 
</P>
<P>
	But for the band's other two members, Israeli-born Doron Oren  
and Rafael Dahan, inspiration comes from homegrown artists and 
their Jewish roots. 
</P>
<P>
	``I started singing at my Bar Mitzvah,'' said Oren, 29, whose  
youthful looks and piercing eyes give Eden a ``boys band'' appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	When Oren joined the group, the other three had already started  
writing songs in English. ``I prefer to sing in Hebrew, it's my 
language,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Hebrew language may not be enough to convince Israeli  
audiences that the band is from their own backyard. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Israeli music has a very, very serious attitude toward  
music and words,'' said Michal Palti, music critic for the Haaretz 
newspaper. ``Even musicians who appeal to teen-age girls use 
sophisticated lyrics and sing about powerful social and political 
issues. I'm not sure how far `baby, baby, baby,' will go,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a surprise that a panel of Israeli judges connected to  
the state-run Israel Broadcast Authority chose the band's song 
``Happy Birthday,'' with a chorus song in English, to represent 
Israel at the May 29 Eurovision contest. 
</P>
<P>
	Like many countries experiencing an American cultural invasion,  
Israel is trying to keep Hebrew at the forefront. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from the language, the birthday message has been another  
subject of concern raised. The band's promotions agency billed the 
song as a millennium greeting -- in other words, 2,000 years since 
the birth of Jesus Christ -- not exactly the kind of theme one would 
expect from the Jewish state. 
</P>
<P>
	Sensing the criticism, the Butler brothers, who prefer not to  
talk about their religious upbringing, said the song had nothing to 
do with Christ. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a birthday song, for anyone,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
