<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 09:12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colo. Student Says Wounds Reopened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- A classmate of students killed in the  
Columbine High School shooting exactly one month ago said today's 
school shooting in Georgia has reopened fresh wounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``What do you do now?'' asked Kim Blair, who saw Eric Harris and  
Dylan Klebold open fire on fellow students on April 20. ``It's 
happening again. What school is going to be next? It's kind of 
scary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other classmates and relatives of Columbine victims agreed that  
the country may be in for more school shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have said since this thing happened that they better beware  
because it's going to happen again and again,'' said Michael 
Shoels, whose 18-year-old son, Isaiah, was among those killed. 
Witnesses said the gunmen singled out Isaiah because he was black. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has some kind of organization to it, so we better  
beware,'' Shoels said in an interview with KOA radio. 
</P>
<P>
	Zoe Bruschke, grandmother of Columbine student Grant Taylor, 16,  
who got out when the shooting started, said she was shocked by the 
Georgia shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	``There may be more,'' Bruschke said. ``Where does this start?  
Aren't there warning signs?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blair said she was troubled that anyone would want to emulate  
Harris and Klebold. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like how people are trying to copycat the Columbine  
shooting. It was a big tragedy. Those two kids are famous because 
they killed people, and that's not what this should be about,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Good, a classmate and neighbor of Harris, said the latest  
shooting shows school violence ``needs to be stopped somehow,'' but 
he has no solution. He said the Jefferson County school district is 
doing what it can to make students feel safe as they try to finish 
out the school year at another high school. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris, 18, and Klebold, 17, hiding their arsenal under black  
trench coats, killed 12 classmates and a teacher before turning 
their guns on themselves. They also wounded 23 people and planted 
more than 50 bombs at the school and in their homes. Diaries show 
the plot had been planned for a year. 
</P>
<P>
	This morning, a student opened fire at Heritage High School in  
Conyers, Ga., exactly one month after the Colorado shootings, 
authorities said. Six students were injured and a suspect was 
quickly taken into custody. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
